command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | egrep '(/etc/passwd)' \n-w /etc/passwd -p wa -k identity\n\nIf the command does not return a line or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"In addition to auditing new user and group accounts, these watches will alert the system administrator(s) to any modifications. Any unexpected users, groups, or modifications should be investigated for legitimacy.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000004-GPOS-00004, SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000304-GPOS-00121, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000470-GPOS-00214, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215, SRG-OS-000239-GPOS-00089, SRG-OS-000240-GPOS-00090, SRG-OS-000241-GPOS-00091, SRG-OS-000303-GPOS-00120, SRG-OS-000466-GPOS-00210, SRG-OS-000476-GPOS-00221, SRG-OS-000274-GPOS-00104, SRG-OS-000275-GPOS-00105, SRG-OS-000276-GPOS-00106, SRG-OS-000277-GPOS-00107","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000018","CCI-000130","CCI-000135","CCI-000169","CCI-000015","CCI-002884","CCI-000172","CCI-001403","CCI-001404","CCI-001405","CCI-002130"],"reference_identifier":"5332","uuid":"a77923e3-af86-416e-9053-ec1f3ae9139b","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: AF57F531BE61E6F85D056031602D7C66F63B6CB9\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must generate audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events that affect /etc/passwd.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271533","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271533","title":"SRG-OS-000004-GPOS-00004","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271533","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000004-GPOS-00004","rule_id_src":"SV-271533r1092486_rule","rule_id":"SV-271533","rule_version":"OL09-00-000530","rule_title":"OL 9 must generate audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events that affect /etc/shadow.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to generate audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events that affect \"/etc/shadow\".\n\nAdd or update the following file system rule to \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-w /etc/shadow -p wa -k identity\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 generates audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events that affect \"/etc/shadow\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | egrep '(/etc/shadow)' \n-w /etc/shadow -p wa -k identity\n\nIf the command does not return a line or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"In addition to auditing new user and group accounts, these watches will alert the system administrator(s) to any modifications. Any unexpected users, groups, or modifications should be investigated for legitimacy.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000004-GPOS-00004, SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000304-GPOS-00121, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000470-GPOS-00214, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215, SRG-OS-000239-GPOS-00089, SRG-OS-000240-GPOS-00090, SRG-OS-000241-GPOS-00091, SRG-OS-000303-GPOS-00120, SRG-OS-000466-GPOS-00210, SRG-OS-000476-GPOS-00221","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000018","CCI-000130","CCI-000135","CCI-000169","CCI-000015","CCI-002884","CCI-000172","CCI-001403","CCI-001404","CCI-001405","CCI-002130"],"reference_identifier":"3131","uuid":"5e1076d8-f295-4dc6-a005-4ba4906bf394","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 5FB9F9057A7B618F96BF4DC690E3D1C60D9C2ECA\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'OL 9 must generate audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events that affect /etc/shadow.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271534","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271534","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271534","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-271534r1092488_rule","rule_id":"SV-271534","rule_version":"OL09-00-000535","rule_title":"OL 9 must audit all uses of the unix_update command.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to generate audit records upon successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the \"unix_update\" command by adding or updating the following rule in \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/sbin/unix_update -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-unix-update\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured to audit the execution of the \"unix_update\" command with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep unix_update\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/sbin/unix_update -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-unix-update\n\nIf the command does not return a line or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit record specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nWhen a user logs on, the auid is set to the uid of the account being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to -1. The auid representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals 4294967295. The audit system interprets -1, 4294967295, and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each system call made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use system call rules only when absolutely necessary since these affect performance. The more rules, the bigger the performance hit. The performance can be helped, however, by combining system calls into one rule whenever possible.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000064-GPOS-00033, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000130","CCI-000135","CCI-000169","CCI-000172","CCI-002884"],"reference_identifier":"9710","uuid":"bf2e6036-b979-4a2c-8736-3378979ae4ed","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-271535","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271535","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271535","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-271535r1092490_rule","rule_id":"SV-271535","rule_version":"OL09-00-000540","rule_title":"OL 9 must audit all uses of the su command.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to generate audit records upon successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the su command by adding or updating the following rule in \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/su -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-priv_change\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured to audit the execution of the su command with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep /usr/bin/su\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/su -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-priv_change\n\nIf the command does not return a line or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit record specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nWhen a user logs on, the auid is set to the uid of the account being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to -1. The auid representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals 4294967295. The audit system interprets -1, 4294967295, and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each system call made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use system call rules only when absolutely necessary since these affect performance. The more rules, the bigger the performance hit. The performance can be helped, however, by combining system calls into one rule whenever possible.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000064-GPOS-00033, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215, SRG-OS-000466-GPOS-00210","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000130","CCI-000135","CCI-000169","CCI-000172","CCI-002884"],"reference_identifier":"7822","uuid":"d08b1b72-2720-4f5e-af62-27e69e282358","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 9AED91179C52C6B763D4181A0E7CCF56704C2CC4\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'OL 9 must audit all uses of the su command.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271536","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271536","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271536","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-271536r1092492_rule","rule_id":"SV-271536","rule_version":"OL09-00-000545","rule_title":"OL 9 must audit all uses of the setxattr, fsetxattr, lsetxattr, removexattr, fremovexattr, and lremovexattr system calls.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to audit the execution of the setxattr, fsetxattr, lsetxattr, removexattr, fremovexattr, and lremovexattr system calls by adding or updating the following lines to \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S setxattr,fsetxattr,lsetxattr,removexattr,fremovexattr,lremovexattr -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S setxattr,fsetxattr,lsetxattr,removexattr,fremovexattr,lremovexattr -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S setxattr,fsetxattr,lsetxattr,removexattr,fremovexattr,lremovexattr -F auid=0 -k perm_mod\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S setxattr,fsetxattr,lsetxattr,removexattr,fremovexattr,lremovexattr -F auid=0 -k perm_mod\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured to audit the execution of the setxattr, fsetxattr, lsetxattr, removexattr, fremovexattr, and lremovexattr system calls with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep xattr\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S setxattr,fsetxattr,lsetxattr,removexattr,fremovexattr,lremovexattr -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S setxattr,fsetxattr,lsetxattr,removexattr,fremovexattr,lremovexattr -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S setxattr,fsetxattr,lsetxattr,removexattr,fremovexattr,lremovexattr -F auid=0 -k perm_mod\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S setxattr,fsetxattr,lsetxattr,removexattr,fremovexattr,lremovexattr -F auid=0 -k perm_mod\n\nIf both the \"b32\" and \"b64\" audit rules are not defined for the setxattr, fsetxattr, lsetxattr, removexattr, fremovexattr, and lremovexattr system calls, or any of the lines returned are commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nWhen a user logs on, the auid is set to the uid of the account being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to -1. The auid representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals 4294967295. The audit system interprets -1, 4294967295, and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each system call made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use system call rules only when absolutely necessary since these affect performance. The more rules, the bigger the performance hit. The performance can be helped, however, by combining system calls into one rule whenever possible.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000458-GPOS-00203, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000463-GPOS-00207, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215, SRG-OS-000474-GPOS-00219, SRG-OS-000466-GPOS-00210, SRG-OS-000064-GPOS-00033","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000130","CCI-000135","CCI-000169","CCI-002884","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"2579","uuid":"1bb4e88f-9986-4f66-ad2f-c2cf4c5059ab","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: DBEEFCF7DBAC1E4EF1178D3CA6BF41D965BE573F\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'OL 9 must audit all uses of the setxattr, fsetxattr, lsetxattr, removexattr, fremovexattr, and lremovexattr system calls.' is not present or not in use on this the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271537","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271537","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271537","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-271537r1092494_rule","rule_id":"SV-271537","rule_version":"OL09-00-000550","rule_title":"OL 9 must audit all uses of the chage command.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to generate audit records upon successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the chage command by adding or updating the following rule in \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/chage -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-chage\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured to audit the execution of the chage command with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep chage\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/chage -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-chage\n\nIf the command does not return a line or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nWhen a user logs on, the auid is set to the uid of the account being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to -1. The auid representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals 4294967295. The audit system interprets -1, 4294967295, and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each system call made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use system call rules only when absolutely necessary since these affect performance. The more rules, the bigger the performance hit. The performance can be helped, however, by combining system calls into one rule whenever possible.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000468-GPOS-00212, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000130","CCI-000135","CCI-000169","CCI-002884","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"5630","uuid":"d2d7381d-224e-4f55-b71e-58dfa7500a62","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 918061270A8D00C4311BB374C2264D41D0174319\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must audit all uses of the chage command.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271538","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271538","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271538","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-271538r1092496_rule","rule_id":"SV-271538","rule_version":"OL09-00-000555","rule_title":"OL 9 must audit all uses of the chcon command.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to generate audit records upon successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the chcon command by adding or updating the following rule in \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/chcon -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured to audit the execution of the chcon command with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep chcon\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/chcon -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n\nIf the command does not return a line or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nWhen a user logs on, the auid is set to the uid of the account that is being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to -1. The auid representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals 4294967295. The audit system interprets -1, 4294967295, and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each system call made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use system call rules only when absolutely necessary since these affect performance. The more rules, the bigger the performance hit. The performance can be helped, however, by combining system calls into one rule whenever possible.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000468-GPOS-00212, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215, SRG-OS-000463-GPOS-00207, SRG-OS-000465-GPOS-00209","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000130","CCI-000135","CCI-000169","CCI-002884","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"2598","uuid":"bc08cebf-39d7-412c-9755-591d1e6275d1","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: EBB3283DCB3ECA8A853AA339D27C89F749B227D5\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must audit all uses of the chcon command.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271539","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271539","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271539","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-271539r1092498_rule","rule_id":"SV-271539","rule_version":"OL09-00-000560","rule_title":"OL 9 must audit all uses of the setfacl command.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to generate audit records upon successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the setfacl command by adding or updating the following rule in \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/setfacl -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured to audit the execution of the setfacl command with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep setfacl\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/setfacl -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n\nIf the command does not return a line or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nWhen a user logs on, the auid is set to the uid of the account being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to -1. The auid representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals 4294967295. The audit system interprets -1, 4294967295, and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each system call made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use system call rules only when absolutely necessary since these affect performance. The more rules, the bigger the performance hit. The performance can be helped, however, by combining system calls into one rule whenever possible.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000130","CCI-000135","CCI-000169","CCI-002884","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"8946","uuid":"6bbe4c7c-a8c3-46b8-b29c-2a8bb3263d42","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 294F73EDE94EA34C25E03E36A08B2CC0E13F05DD\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'OL 9 must audit all uses of the setfacl command.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271540","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271540","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271540","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-271540r1092500_rule","rule_id":"SV-271540","rule_version":"OL09-00-000565","rule_title":"OL 9 must audit all uses of the chsh command.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to generate audit records upon successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the chsh command by adding or updating the following rule in \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/chsh -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k priv_cmd\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured to audit the execution of the chsh command with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep chsh\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/chsh -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k priv_cmd\n\nIf the command does not return a line or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nWhen a user logs on, the auid is set to the uid of the account being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to -1. The auid representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals 4294967295. The audit system interprets -1, 4294967295, and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each system call made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use system call rules only when absolutely necessary since these affect performance. The more rules, the bigger the performance hit. The performance can be helped, however, by combining system calls into one rule whenever possible.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000130","CCI-000135","CCI-000169","CCI-002884","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"8379","uuid":"9f90e847-270a-4f3e-9e42-61e1dfc7e4c6","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 7D648E955B306860EC2EAC5B283AF835F0CF2E76\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'OL 9 must audit all uses of the chsh command.' is not present or not in use on this the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271541","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271541","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271541","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-271541r1092502_rule","rule_id":"SV-271541","rule_version":"OL09-00-000570","rule_title":"OL 9 must audit all uses of the crontab command.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to generate audit records upon successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the crontab command by adding or updating the following rule in \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/crontab -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-crontab\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured to audit the execution of the crontab command with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep crontab\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/crontab -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-crontab\n\nIf the command does not return a line or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nWhen a user logs on, the auid is set to the uid of the account being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to -1. The auid representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals 4294967295. The audit system interprets -1, 4294967295, and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each system call made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use system call rules only when absolutely necessary since these affect performance. The more rules, the bigger the performance hit. The performance can be helped, however, by combining system calls into one rule whenever possible.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000130","CCI-000135","CCI-000169","CCI-002884","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"9015","uuid":"3514e27a-68f1-4d5d-93a7-23422af93f81","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 176EBFC628C4AFB0F4B4A4B6DB255E78F5720285\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'OL 9 must audit all uses of the crontab command.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271542","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271542","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271542","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-271542r1092504_rule","rule_id":"SV-271542","rule_version":"OL09-00-000575","rule_title":"OL 9 must audit all uses of the gpasswd command.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to generate audit records upon successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the gpasswd command by adding or updating the following rule in \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/gpasswd -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-gpasswd\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured to audit the execution of the gpasswd command with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep gpasswd\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/gpasswd -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-gpasswd\n\nIf the command does not return a line or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nWhen a user logs on, the auid is set to the uid of the account being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to -1. The auid representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals 4294967295. The audit system interprets -1, 4294967295, and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each system call made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use system call rules only when absolutely necessary since these affect performance. The more rules, the bigger the performance hit. The performance can be helped, however, by combining system calls into one rule whenever possible.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000130","CCI-000135","CCI-000169","CCI-002884","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"7371","uuid":"5e01b9f8-ca6e-49ef-8395-a2637cc2876c","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: BC42C12B3066A71B3E72E17F939F7F19F516D347\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must audit all uses of the gpasswd command.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271543","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271543","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271543","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-271543r1092506_rule","rule_id":"SV-271543","rule_version":"OL09-00-000580","rule_title":"OL 9 must audit all uses of the newgrp command.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to generate audit records upon successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the newgrp command by adding or updating the following rule in \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/newgrp -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k priv_cmd\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured to audit the execution of the newgrp command with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep newgrp\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/newgrp -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k priv_cmd\n\nIf the command does not return a line or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nWhen a user logs on, the auid is set to the uid of the account that is being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to -1. The auid representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals 4294967295. The audit system interprets -1, 4294967295, and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each system call made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use system call rules only when absolutely necessary since these affect performance. The more rules, the bigger the performance hit. The performance can be helped, however, by combining system calls into one rule whenever possible.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000130","CCI-000135","CCI-000169","CCI-002884","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"4360","uuid":"af7d481c-9a29-4506-912d-0c7ca5e48c0e","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 269F13AFC24BA192E6A1B9883828722C57584438\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must audit all uses of the newgrp command.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271544","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271544","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271544","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-271544r1092508_rule","rule_id":"SV-271544","rule_version":"OL09-00-000585","rule_title":"OL 9 must audit all uses of the pam_timestamp_check command.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to generate audit records upon successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the pam_timestamp_check command by adding