ix_chkpwd command.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271552","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271552","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271552","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-271552r1092524_rule","rule_id":"SV-271552","rule_version":"OL09-00-000625","rule_title":"OL 9 must audit all uses of the userhelper command.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to generate audit records upon successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the userhelper command by adding or updating the following rule in \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/sbin/userhelper -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-unix-update\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured to audit the execution of the userhelper command with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep userhelper\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/sbin/userhelper -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-unix-update\n\nIf the command does not return a line or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit record specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nWhen a user logs on, the auid is set to the uid of the account being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to -1. The auid representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals 4294967295. The audit system interprets -1, 4294967295, and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each system call made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use system call rules only when absolutely necessary since these affect performance. The more rules, the bigger the performance hit. The performance can be helped, however, by combining system calls into one rule whenever possible.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000130","CCI-000135","CCI-000169","CCI-002884","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"4514","uuid":"4e701b54-026b-4790-88e0-7c9854946542","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 87EB29814786D9C095673029E052F84FD7ABD6B7\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must audit all uses of the userhelper command.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271553","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271553","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271553","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-271553r1092526_rule","rule_id":"SV-271553","rule_version":"OL09-00-000630","rule_title":"OL 9 must audit all uses of the mount command.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to generate audit records upon successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the mount command by adding or updating the following rule in \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/mount -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-mount\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured to audit the execution of the mount command with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep /usr/bin/mount\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/mount -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-mount\n\nIf the command does not return a line or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nWhen a user logs on, the auid is set to the uid of the account that is being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to -1. The auid representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals 4294967295. The audit system interprets -1, 4294967295, and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each system call made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use system call rules only when absolutely necessary since these affect performance. The more rules, the bigger the performance hit. The performance can be helped, however, by combining system calls into one rule whenever possible.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000130","CCI-000135","CCI-000169","CCI-002884","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"1810","uuid":"be0bbc5c-2280-4b46-aac5-caa331f1a4b5","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: AFFEAA17CB6B68ABAFBE58CF72C421E4FA645410\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must audit all uses of the mount command.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271554","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271554","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271554","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-271554r1092528_rule","rule_id":"SV-271554","rule_version":"OL09-00-000635","rule_title":"OL 9 must audit all uses of the truncate, ftruncate, creat, open, openat, and open_by_handle_at system calls.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to generate an audit event for any successful/unsuccessful use of the truncate, ftruncate, creat, open, openat, and open_by_handle_at system calls by adding or updating the following rules in the \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\" file:\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S truncate,ftruncate,creat,open,openat,open_by_handle_at -F exit=-EPERM -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_access\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S truncate,ftruncate,creat,open,openat,open_by_handle_at -F exit=-EPERM -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_access\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S truncate,ftruncate,creat,open,openat,open_by_handle_at -F exit=-EACCES -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_access\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S truncate,ftruncate,creat,open,openat,open_by_handle_at -F exit=-EACCES -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_access\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured to audit successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the truncate, ftruncate, creat, open, openat, and open_by_handle_at system calls with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep 'open\\|truncate\\|creat' \n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S truncate,ftruncate,creat,open,openat,open_by_handle_at -F exit=-EPERM -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_access\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S truncate,ftruncate,creat,open,openat,open_by_handle_at -F exit=-EPERM -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_access\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S truncate,ftruncate,creat,open,openat,open_by_handle_at -F exit=-EACCES -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_access\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S truncate,ftruncate,creat,open,openat,open_by_handle_at -F exit=-EACCES -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_access\n\nIf the output does not produce rules containing \"-F exit=-EPERM\", this is a finding.\n\nIf the output does not produce rules containing \"-F exit=-EACCES\", this is a finding.\n\nIf the command does not return an audit rule for truncate, ftruncate, creat, open, openat, and open_by_handle_at or any of the lines returned are commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nWhen a user logs on, the auid is set to the uid of the account being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to -1. The auid representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals 4294967295. The audit system interprets -1, 4294967295, and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each system call made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use system call rules only when absolutely necessary since these affect performance. The more rules, the bigger the performance hit. The performance can be helped, however, by combining system calls into one rule whenever possible.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215, SRG-OS-000064-GPOS-00033, SRG-OS-000458-GPOS-00203, SRG-OS-000461-GPOS-00205","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000130","CCI-000135","CCI-000169","CCI-002884","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"7497","uuid":"0fbf20b5-5370-4deb-b15c-c5088509f1f7","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 9A2A309A1B4A144478FDC91EF946D35E9B439EA9\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must audit all uses of the truncate, ftruncate, creat, open, openat, and open_by_handle_at system calls.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271555","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271555","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271555","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-271555r1092530_rule","rule_id":"SV-271555","rule_version":"OL09-00-000640","rule_title":"OL 9 must audit all uses of the chmod, fchmod, and fchmodat system calls.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to generate audit records upon successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the chmod, fchmod, and fchmodat system calls.\n\nAdd or update the following rules in \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S chmod,fchmod,fchmodat -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S chmod,fchmod,fchmodat -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured to audit the execution of the chmod, fchmod, and fchmodat system calls with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep chmod\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S chmod,fchmod,fchmodat -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S chmod,fchmod,fchmodat -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n\nIf both the \"b32\" and \"b64\" audit rules are not defined for the chmod, fchmod, and fchmodat system calls, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nWhen a user logs on, the auid is set to the uid of the account being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to -1. The auid representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals 4294967295. The audit system interprets -1, 4294967295, and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each system call made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use system call rules only when absolutely necessary since these affect performance. The more rules, the bigger the performance hit. The performance can be helped, however, by combining system calls into one rule whenever possible.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215, SRG-OS-000064-GPOS-00033, SRG-OS-000466-GPOS-00210, SRG-OS-000458-GPOS-00203","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000130","CCI-000135","CCI-000169","CCI-002884","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"5669","uuid":"65c80172-d5ec-4022-bcfc-861b19be81e7","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: B790734BA0666D42B5C89E9E4BF56C689CAA79F2\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must audit all uses of the chmod, fchmod, and fchmodat system calls.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271556","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271556","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271556","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-271556r1092532_rule","rule_id":"SV-271556","rule_version":"OL09-00-000645","rule_title":"OL 9 must audit all uses of the chown, fchown, fchownat, and lchown system calls.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to generate audit records upon successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the chown, fchown, fchownat, and lchown system calls.\n\nAdd or update the following rules in \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S chown,fchown,fchownat,lchown -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S chown,fchown,fchownat,lchown -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured to audit the execution of the chown, fchown, fchownat, and lchown system calls with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep chown\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S chown,fchown,fchownat,lchown -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S chown,fchown,fchownat,lchown -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n\nIf both the \"b32\" and \"b64\" audit rules are not defined for the chown, fchown, fchownat, and lchown system calls, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nWhen a user logs on, the auid is set to the uid of the account being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to -1. The auid representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals 4294967295. The audit system interprets -1, 4294967295, and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each system call made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use system call rules only when absolutely necessary since these affect performance. The more rules, the bigger the performance hit. The performance can be helped, however, by combining system calls into one rule whenever possible.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215, SRG-OS-000064-GPOS-00033, SRG-OS-000466-GPOS-00210, SRG-OS-000458-GPOS-00203, SRG-OS-000474-GPOS-00219","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000130","CCI-000135","CCI-000169","CCI-002884","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"4715","uuid":"1c60e94c-aefb-4ecc-ab81-2647525c34f3","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: D3956A334E64F090C1F88595BB795DEB1368BF46\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'OL 9 must audit all uses of the chown, fchown, fchownat, and lchown system calls.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271557","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271557","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271557","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-271557r1092534_rule","rule_id":"SV-271557","rule_version":"OL09-00-000650","rule_title":"OL 9 must audit all uses of the semanage command.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to generate audit records upon successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the semanage command by adding or updating the following rule in \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/sbin/semanage -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-unix-update\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured to audit the execution of the semanage command with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep semanage\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/sbin/semanage -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-unix-update\n\nIf the command does not return a line or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nWhen a user logs on, the auid is set to the uid of the account being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to -1. The auid representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals 4294967295. The audit system interprets -1, 4294967295, and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each system call made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use system call rules only when absolutely necessary since these affect performance. The more rules, the bigger the performance hit. The performance can be helped, however, by combining system calls into one rule whenever possible.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215, SRG-OS-000463-GPOS-00207, SRG-OS-000465-GPOS-00209","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000130","CCI-000135","CCI-000169","CCI-002884","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"6711","uuid":"f0347480-8bd9-49b1-8fe9-c9ac2fc136ee","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 5651254ADB8EA70F9D42D2A740443287935E517F\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must audit all uses of the semanage command.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271558","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271558","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271558","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-271558r1092536_rule","rule_id":"SV-271558","rule_version":"OL09-00-000655","rule_title":"OL 9 must audit all uses of the setfiles command.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to generate audit records upon successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the setfiles command by adding or updating the following rule in \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/sbin/setfiles -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-unix-update\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured to audit the execution of the setfiles command with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep setfiles\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/sbin/setfiles -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-unix-update\n\nIf the command does not return a line or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nWhen a user logs on, the auid is set to the uid of the account being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to -1. The auid representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals 4294967295. The audit system interprets -1, 4294967295, and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each system call made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use system call rules only when absolutely necessary since these affect performance. The more rules, the bigger the performance hit. The performance can be helped, however, by combining system calls into one rule whenever possible.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215, SRG-OS-000463-GPOS-00207, SRG-OS-000465-GPOS-00209","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000130","CCI-000135","CCI-000169","CCI-002884","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"2123","uuid":"0639492a-ae52-484d-a3f4-9db81eea5813","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 6A293F813E8C26FB3A4CAB0C26A658DDB4A68E76\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must audit all uses of the setfiles command.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271559","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271559","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271559","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-271559r1092538_rule","rule_id":"SV-271559","rule_version":"OL09-00-000660","rule_title":"OL 9 must audit all uses of the setsebool command.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to generate an audit event for any successful/unsuccessful use of the setsebool command by adding or updating the following rules in the \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\" file:\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/sbin/setsebool -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -F key=privileged \n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured to audit the execution of the setsebool command with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep setsebool\n -a always,exit -F path=/usr/sbin/setsebool -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -F key=privileged \n\nIf the command does not return a line or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nWhen a user logs on, the auid is set to the uid of the account being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to -1. The auid representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals 4294967295. The audit system interprets -1, 4294967295, and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each system call made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use system call rules only when absolutely necessary since these affect performance. The more rules, the bigger the performance hit. The performance can be helped, however, by combining system calls into one rule whenever possible.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215, SRG-OS-000463-GPOS-00207, SRG-OS-000465-GPOS-00209","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000130","CCI-000135","CCI-000169","CCI-002884","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"8565","uuid":"57ee7209-4ee8-4396-8be2-966872e992d4","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: DF1437E60AF1A22C9F58680ACDA7ADF7DF91FA4C\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'OL 9 must audit all uses of the setsebool command.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271560","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271560","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271560","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-271560r1092540_rule","rule_id":"SV-271560","rule_version":"OL09-00-000665","rule_title":"OL 9 must audit all uses of the chacl command.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to generate audit records upon successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the chacl command by adding or updating the following rule in \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/chacl -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured to audit the execution of the chacl command with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep chacl\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/chacl -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n\nIf the command does not return a line or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nWhen a user logs on, the auid is set to the uid of the account being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to -1. The auid representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals 4294967295. The audit system interprets -1, 4294967295, and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each system call made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use system call rules only when absolutely necessary since these affect performance. The more rules, the bigger the performance hit. The performance can be helped, however, by combining system calls into one rule whenever possible.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215, SRG-OS-000466-GPOS-00210","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000130","CCI-000135","CCI-000169","CCI-002884","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"3499","uuid":"3e39b8c5-b62e-4ad7-a970-f6848856febb","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 91148AF48F1A986F3844C9B872B7E746E128AD17\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must audit all uses of the chacl command.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271561","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271561","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271561","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-271561r1092542_rule","rule_id":"SV-271561","rule_version":"OL09-00-000670","rule_title":"OL 9 must audit all uses of the sudo command.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to generate audit records upon successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the sudo command by adding or updating the following rule in \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/sudo -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k priv_cmd\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured to audit the execution of the sudo command with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep /usr/bin/sudo\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/sudo -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k priv_cmd\n\nIf the command does not return a line or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit record specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nWhen a user logs on, the auid is set to the uid of the account being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to -1. The auid representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals 4294967295. The audit system interprets -1, 4294967295, and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each system call made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use system call rules only when absolutely necessary since these affect performance. The more rules, the bigger the performance hit. The performance can be helped, however, by combining system calls into one rule whenever possible.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215, SRG-OS-000466-GPOS-00210","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000130","CCI-000135","CCI-000169","CCI-002884","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"1010","uuid":"0a0e738c-28a9-472d-a530-a9a18b3779fe","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 4CCFE18A8482EC0842E08294C4B82B077E344433\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'OL 9 must audit all uses of the sudo command.' is not present or not in use on this the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271562","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271562","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271562","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-271562r1092544_rule","rule_id":"SV-271562","rule_version":"OL09-00-000675","rule_title":"OL 9 must audit all uses of the usermod command.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to generate audit records upon successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the usermod command by adding or updating the following rule in \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/sbin/usermod -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-usermod\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured to audit the execution of the usermod command with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep usermod\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/sbin/usermod -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-usermod\n\nIf the command does not return a line or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit record specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nWhen a user logs on, the auid is set to the uid of the account being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to -1. The auid representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals 4294967295. The audit system interprets -1, 4294967295, and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each system call made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use system call rules only when absolutely necessary since these affect performance. The more rules, the bigger the performance hit. The performance can be helped, however, by combining system calls into one rule whenever possible.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215, SRG-OS-000466-GPOS-00210","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000130","CCI-000135","CCI-000169","CCI-002884","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"5594","uuid":"bc6042aa-faec-4f10-bb6b-b6c91c3d9b93","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 3BCCF2DC0691F0E917CD4BCCC5DB88B4F3A9D5D8\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must audit all uses of the usermod command.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271563","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271563","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271563","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-271563r1092546_rule","rule_id":"SV-271563","rule_version":"OL09-00-000680","rule_title":"OL 9 must audit all uses of the rename, unlink, rmdir, renameat, and unlinkat system calls.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to generate an audit event for any successful/unsuccessful use of the rename, unlink, rmdir, renameat, and unlinkat system calls by adding or updating the following rules in the \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\" file:\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S rename,unlink,rmdir,renameat,unlinkat -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k delete\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S rename,unlink,rmdir,renameat,unlinkat -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k delete\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured to audit successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the rename, unlink, rmdir, renameat, and unlinkat system calls with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep 'rename\\|unlink\\|rmdir'\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S rename,unlink,rmdir,renameat,unlinkat -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k delete\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S rename,unlink,rmdir,renameat,unlinkat -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k delete\n\nIf the command does not return an audit rule for rename, unlink, rmdir, renameat, and unlinkat or any of the lines returned are commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nWhen a user logs on, the auid is set to the uid of the account being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to -1. The auid representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals 4294967295. The audit system interprets -1, 4294967295, and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each system call made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use system call rules only when absolutely necessary since these affect performance. The more rules, the bigger the performance hit. The performance can be helped, however, by combining system calls into one rule whenever possible.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215, SRG-OS-000466-GPOS-00210, SRG-OS-000467-GPOS-00211, SRG-OS-000468-GPOS-00212","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000130","CCI-000135","CCI-000169","CCI-002884","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"2084","uuid":"bbf8b687-a12d-4014-8099-fd3a5f2e6565","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 36C1DE7A5AFB932F99B3E3135C99BEEC96EC1E61\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must audit all uses of the rename, unlink, rmdir, renameat, and unlinkat system calls.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271564","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271564","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271564","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-271564r1092548_rule","rule_id":"SV-271564","rule_version":"OL09-00-000685","rule_title":"OL 9 must audit all uses of the delete_module system call.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to generate an audit event for any successful/unsuccessful use of the delete_module system call by adding or updating the following rules in the \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\" file:\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S delete_module -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k module_chng\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S delete_module -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k module_chng\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured to audit the execution of the delete_module system call with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep delete_module\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S delete_module -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k module_chng\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S delete_module -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k module_chng\n\nIf both the \"b32\" and \"b64\" audit rules are not defined for the delete_module system call, or any of the lines returned are commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nWhen a user logs on, the auid is set to the uid of the account being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to -1. The auid representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals 4294967295. The audit system interprets -1, 4294967295, and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each system call made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use system call rules only when absolutely necessary since these affect performance. The more rules, the bigger the performance hit. The performance can be helped, however, by combining system calls into one rule whenever possible.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00216, SRG-OS-000477-GPOS-00222","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000130","CCI-000135","CCI-000169","CCI-002884","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"9724","uuid":"95e341fd-f7ed-4c7c-8597-5bea895ffae5","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: BD0A736AC12ACC3E9D75C5BB384F96AF4613EE12\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must audit all uses of the delete_module system call.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271565","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271565","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271565","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-271565r1092550_rule","rule_id":"SV-271565","rule_version":"OL09-00-000690","rule_title":"OL 9 must audit all uses of the init_module and finit_module system calls.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to generate an audit event for any successful/unsuccessful use of the init_module and finit_module system calls by adding or updating the following rules in the \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\" file:\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S init_module,finit_module -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k module_chng\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S init_module,finit_module -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k module_chng\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured to audit the execution of the init_module and finit_module system calls with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep init_module\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S init_module,finit_module -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k module_chng\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S init_module,finit_module -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k module_chng\n\nIf both the \"b32\" and \"b64\" audit rules are not defined for the init_module and finit_module system calls, or any of the lines returned are commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nWhen a user logs on, the auid is set to the uid of the account being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to -1. The auid representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals 4294967295. The audit system interprets -1, 4294967295, and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each system call made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use system call rules only when absolutely necessary since these affect performance. The more rules, the bigger the performance hit. The performance can be helped, however, by combining system calls into one rule whenever possible.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00216, SRG-OS-000477-GPOS-00222","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000130","CCI-000135","CCI-000169","CCI-002884","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"3134","uuid":"f837bec8-d6f1-4a96-a633-ea3f634a257e","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 7BD4F6B402BD8FB7AEB4490532BFF2A10254BE99\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'OL 9 must audit all uses of the init_module and finit_module system calls.' is not present or not in use on this the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271566","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271566","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271566","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-271566r1092552_rule","rule_id":"SV-271566","rule_version":"OL09-00-000695","rule_title":"OL 9 must audit all uses of the kmod command.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to generate audit records upon successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the kmod command by adding or updating the following rule in \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/kmod -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k modules\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured to audit the execution of the kmod command with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep kmod\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/kmod -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k modules\n\nIf the command does not return a line or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nWhen a user logs on, the auid is set to the uid of the account being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to -1. The auid representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals 4294967295. The audit system interprets -1, 4294967295, and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each system call made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use system call rules only when absolutely necessary since these affect performance. The more rules, the bigger the performance hit. The performance can be helped, however, by combining system calls into one rule whenever possible.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00216, SRG-OS-000477-GPOS-00222","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000130","CCI-000135","CCI-000169","CCI-002884","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"2285","uuid":"cd790817-3443-4be7-97f0-50e9498dcaa0","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: AAA9D814EA3C74CF8C751DDCA61AC049E36CB4C6\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must audit all uses of the kmod command.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271567","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271567","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271567","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-271567r1092554_rule","rule_id":"SV-271567","rule_version":"OL09-00-000700","rule_title":"OL 9 must generate audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events that affect /var/log/lastlog.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to generate audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events that affect /var/log/lastlog.\n\nAdd or update the following file system rule to \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-w /var/log/lastlog -p wa -k logins\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 generates audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events that affect /var/log/lastlog with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep /var/log/lastlog\n-w /var/log/lastlog -p wa -k logins\n\nIf the command does not return a line or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215, SRG-OS-000473-GPOS-00218, SRG-OS-000470-GPOS-00214","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000130","CCI-000135","CCI-000169","CCI-002884","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"9512","uuid":"6d7e5016-1034-40e6-a2a6-d4856c4883d8","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 11929993E81F282CED5DA552B121A5D32B050615\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'OL 9 must generate audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events that affect /var/log/lastlog.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271568","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271568","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271568","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-271568r1092556_rule","rule_id":"SV-271568","rule_version":"OL09-00-000705","rule_title":"OL 9 must audit all uses of umount system calls.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to generate audit records upon successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the umount command by adding or updating the following rules in \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/umount -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-mount\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured to audit the execution of the umount command with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep umount\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/umount -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-mount\n\nIf the command does not return an audit rule for umount or any of the lines returned are commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nWhen a user logs on, the auid is set to the uid of the account being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to -1. The auid representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals 4294967295. The audit system interprets -1, 4294967295, and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each system call made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use system call rules only when absolutely necessary since these affect performance. The more rules, the bigger the performance hit. The performance can be helped, however, by combining system calls into one rule whenever possible.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000130","CCI-000169","CCI-002884","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"9931","uuid":"64e5ab1d-e4cf-4854-a4e5-04390b1a2eb1","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 50C4BDCE55C72814C7F4D175021F8812EF1D977E\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must audit all uses of umount system calls.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271569","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271569","title":"SRG-OS-000256-GPOS-00097","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271569","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000256-GPOS-00097","rule_id_src":"SV-271569r1155308_rule","rule_id":"SV-271569","rule_version":"OL09-00-000710","rule_title":"OL 9 must use cryptographic mechanisms to protect the integrity of audit tools.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to protect the integrity of the audit tools.\n\nAdd or update the following lines to /etc/aide.conf:\n \n/usr/sbin/auditctl p+i+n+u+g+s+b+acl+xattrs+sha512\n/usr/sbin/auditd p+i+n+u+g+s+b+acl+xattrs+sha512\n/usr/sbin/ausearch p+i+n+u+g+s+b+acl+xattrs+sha512\n/usr/sbin/aureport p+i+n+u+g+s+b+acl+xattrs+sha512\n/usr/sbin/autrace p+i+n+u+g+s+b+acl+xattrs+sha512\n/usr/sbin/augenrules p+i+n+u+g+s+b+acl+xattrs+sha512","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify OL 9 uses cryptographic mechanisms to protect the integrity of the audit tools with the following command:\n\n$ sudo cat /etc/aide.conf | grep /usr/sbin/au\n/usr/sbin/auditctl p+i+n+u+g+s+b+acl+xattrs+sha512\n/usr/sbin/auditd p+i+n+u+g+s+b+acl+xattrs+sha512\n/usr/sbin/ausearch p+i+n+u+g+s+b+acl+xattrs+sha512\n/usr/sbin/aureport p+i+n+u+g+s+b+acl+xattrs+sha512\n/usr/sbin/autrace p+i+n+u+g+s+b+acl+xattrs+sha512\n/usr/sbin/augenrules p+i+n+u+g+s+b+acl+xattrs+sha512\n \nIf AIDE is not installed, ask the system administrator (SA) how file integrity checks are performed on the system.\n\nIf any of the audit tools listed above do not have a corresponding line, ask the SA to indicate what cryptographic mechanisms are being used to protect the integrity of the audit tools. If there is no evidence of integrity protection, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Protecting the integrity of the tools used for auditing purposes is a critical step toward ensuring the integrity of audit information. Audit information includes all information (e.g., audit records, audit settings, and audit reports) needed to successfully audit information system activity.\n\nAudit tools include, but are not limited to, vendor-provided and open-source audit tools needed to successfully view and manipulate audit information system activity and records. Audit tools include custom queries and report generators.\n\nIt is not uncommon for attackers to replace the audit tools or inject code into the existing tools to provide the capability to hide or erase system activity from the audit logs.\n\nTo address this risk, audit tools must be cryptographically signed to provide the capability to identify when the audit tools have been modified, manipulated, or replaced. An example is a checksum hash of the file or files.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000256-GPOS-00097, SRG-OS-000257-GPOS-00098, SRG-OS-000258-GPOS-00099, SRG-OS-000278-GPOS-00108","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001493","CCI-001494","CCI-001495","CCI-001496"],"reference_identifier":"8290","uuid":"3a6417ea-a218-480a-b112-cedd452fd78c","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: F0AF52426BE96F7D60761E05DEE5F9925CD0F5A9\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must use cryptographic mechanisms to protect the integrity of audit tools.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271570","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271570","title":"SRG-OS-000326-GPOS-00126","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271570","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000326-GPOS-00126","rule_id_src":"SV-271570r1092558_rule","rule_id":"SV-271570","rule_version":"OL09-00-000715","rule_title":"OL 9 must audit uses of the execve system call.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to audit the execution of the execve system call.\n\nAdd or update the following file system rules to \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S execve -C uid!=euid -F euid=0 -k execpriv \n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S execve -C uid!=euid -F euid=0 -k execpriv\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S execve -C gid!=egid -F egid=0 -k execpriv \n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S execve -C gid!=egid -F egid=0 -k execpriv \n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart\n\nNote: Users must reboot to view above results with command \"auditctl -l | grep execve\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured to audit the execution of the execve system call with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep execve\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S execve -C uid!=euid -F euid=0 -k execpriv \n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S execve -C uid!=euid -F euid=0 -k execpriv\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S execve -C gid!=egid -F egid=0 -k execpriv \n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S execve -C gid!=egid -F egid=0 -k execpriv\n\nIf the command does not return all lines or the lines are commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Misuse of privileged functions, either intentionally or unintentionally by authorized users, or by unauthorized external entities that have compromised information system accounts, is a serious and ongoing concern and can have significant adverse impacts on organizations. Auditing the use of privileged functions is one way to detect such misuse and identify the risk from insider threats and the advanced persistent threat.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000326-GPOS-00126, SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127, SRG-OS-000755-GPOS-00220","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002233","CCI-002234","CCI-004188"],"reference_identifier":"1786","uuid":"b0d4b7fd-91ec-4678-94fb-fe40b34bf5e2","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: CB92FAE93D97A11DC8E0AF565302386EDD04CBE8\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'OL 9 must audit uses of the execve system call.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271571","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271571","title":"SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271571","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172","rule_id_src":"SV-271571r1092560_rule","rule_id":"SV-271571","rule_version":"OL09-00-000720","rule_title":"OL 9 must generate audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events that affect /var/log/faillock.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to generate audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events that affect /var/log/faillock.\n\nAdd or update the following file system rule to \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-w /var/log/faillock -p wa -k logins\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 generates audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events that affect /var/log/faillock with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep /var/log/faillock\n-w /var/log/faillock -p wa -k logins\n\nIf the command does not return a line or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000470-GPOS-00214, SRG-OS-000473-GPOS-00218","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002884","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"7615","uuid":"205a0903-5a48-4fd8-9c5e-3e8856b5a9f7","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: DE9183829A556AD86D8E165C647D7792600861B5\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must generate audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events that affect /var/log/faillock.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271572","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271572","title":"SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271572","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172","rule_id_src":"SV-271572r1092562_rule","rule_id":"SV-271572","rule_version":"OL09-00-000725","rule_title":"OL 9 must generate audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events that affect /var/log/tallylog.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to generate audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events that affect /var/log/tallylog.\n\nAdd or update the following file system rule to \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-w /var/log/tallylog -p wa -k logins\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 generates audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events that affect /var/log/tallylog with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep /var/log/tallylog\n-w\u00a0/var/log/tallylog\u00a0-p\u00a0wa\u00a0-k\u00a0logins\n\nIf the command does not return a line or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000470-GPOS-00214, SRG-OS-000473-GPOS-00218","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002884","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"1750","uuid":"b1116103-ca1d-4855-921d-9f304f701ad2","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 43B266EEB4EA0B3F450B0615B2EF63257D4CA06E\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must generate audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events that affect /var/log/tallylog.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271573","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271573","title":"SRG-OS-000477-GPOS-00222","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271573","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000477-GPOS-00222","rule_id_src":"SV-271573r1092564_rule","rule_id":"SV-271573","rule_version":"OL09-00-000730","rule_title":"OL 9 must be configured so that successful/unsuccessful uses of the init command generate an audit record.","fix_text":"Configure the audit system to generate an audit event for any successful/unsuccessful uses of the init command by adding or updating the following rule in the \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\" file:\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/sbin/init -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-init\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured to audit the execution of the init command with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep init\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/sbin/init -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-init\n\nIf the command does not return a line or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Misuse of the init command may cause availability issues for the system.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"4662","uuid":"ea574ba5-6177-4735-966e-5272dbce51fb","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-271574","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271574","title":"SRG-OS-000477-GPOS-00222","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271574","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000477-GPOS-00222","rule_id_src":"SV-271574r1092566_rule","rule_id":"SV-271574","rule_version":"OL09-00-000735","rule_title":"OL 9 must be configured so that successful/unsuccessful uses of the poweroff command generate an audit record.","fix_text":"Configure the audit system to generate an audit event for any successful/unsuccessful uses of the poweroff command by adding or updating the following rule in the \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\" file:\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/sbin/poweroff -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-poweroff\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured to audit the execution of the poweroff command with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep poweroff\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/sbin/poweroff -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-poweroff\n\nIf the command does not return a line or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Misuse of the poweroff command may cause availability issues for the system.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"4151","uuid":"a93bc1ba-a889-4f15-a65d-39c87e22ddea","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: B90DB693D444554182173A56A19545F761B70A33\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must be configured so that successful/unsuccessful uses of the poweroff command generate an audit record.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271575","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271575","title":"SRG-OS-000477-GPOS-00222","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271575","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000477-GPOS-00222","rule_id_src":"SV-271575r1092568_rule","rule_id":"SV-271575","rule_version":"OL09-00-000740","rule_title":"OL 9 must be configured so that successful/unsuccessful uses of the reboot command generate an audit record.","fix_text":"Configure the audit system to generate an audit event for any successful/unsuccessful uses of the reboot command by adding or updating the following rule in the \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\" file:\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/sbin/reboot -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-reboot\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured to audit the execution of the reboot command with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep reboot\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/sbin/reboot -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-reboot\n\nIf the command does not return a line or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Misuse of the reboot command may cause availability issues for the system.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"3059","uuid":"703aba9f-ce45-48e2-b4b9-95d875968e74","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: B557D9541ADC6B0F47D0F1E7E9647C755997CED5\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must be configured so that successful/unsuccessful uses of the reboot command generate an audit record.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271576","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271576","title":"SRG-OS-000477-GPOS-00222","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271576","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000477-GPOS-00222","rule_id_src":"SV-271576r1092570_rule","rule_id":"SV-271576","rule_version":"OL09-00-000745","rule_title":"OL 9 must be configured so that successful/unsuccessful uses of the shutdown command generate an audit record.","fix_text":"Configure the audit system to generate an audit event for any successful/unsuccessful uses of the shutdown command by adding or updating the following rule in the \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\" file:\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/sbin/shutdown -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-shutdown\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured to audit the execution of the shutdown command with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep shutdown\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/sbin/shutdown -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-shutdown\n\nIf the command does not return a line or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Misuse of the shutdown command may cause availability issues for the system.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"3112","uuid":"a67fa698-307e-45f5-a1d4-f5311c70eab5","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 369D9C7B28728CE29048F3A6EA044C8E8DA0F477\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must be configured so that successful/unsuccessful uses of the shutdown command generate an audit record.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271577","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271577","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271577","severity":"low","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-271577r1091443_rule","rule_id":"SV-271577","rule_version":"OL09-00-000750","rule_title":"OL 9 must enable auditing of processes that start prior to the audit daemon.","fix_text":"Enable auditing of processes that start prior to the audit daemon with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grubby --update-kernel=ALL --args=\"audit=1\"\n\nAdd or modify the following line in \"/etc/default/grub\" to ensure the configuration survives kernel updates:\n\nGRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX=\"audit=1\"","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured to enable auditing of processes that start prior to the audit daemon.\n\nCheck that the current GRUB 2 configuration enables auditing:\n\n$ sudo grubby --info=ALL | grep audit\nargs=\"ro crashkernel=auto resume=/dev/mapper/ol-swap rd.lvm.lv=ol/root rd.lvm.lv=ol/swap rhgb quiet fips=1 audit=1 audit_backlog_limit=8192 pti=on \n\nIf \"audit\" is not set to \"1\" or is missing, this is a finding.\n\nCheck that auditing is enabled by default to persist through kernel updates: \n\n$ sudo grep audit /etc/default/grub\nGRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX=\"audit=1\"\n\nIf \"audit\" is not set to \"1\", is missing, or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without the capability to generate audit records, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nIf auditing is enabled late in the startup process, the actions of some startup processes may not be audited. Some audit systems also maintain state information only available if auditing is enabled before a given process is created.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215, SRG-OS-000473-GPOS-00218, SRG-OS-000254-GPOS-00095","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000130","CCI-000135","CCI-000169","CCI-002884","CCI-000172","CCI-001464"],"reference_identifier":"3463","uuid":"4a8999a9-1449-4f59-b3e1-f1f74ff7e1df","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 7C948CF05AA0DB3903E517466051AF47D8061406\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'OL 9 must enable auditing of processes that start prior to the audit daemon.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271578","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271578","title":"SRG-OS-000039-GPOS-00017","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271578","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000039-GPOS-00017","rule_id_src":"SV-271578r1092572_rule","rule_id":"SV-271578","rule_version":"OL09-00-000755","rule_title":"OL 9 must label all offloaded audit logs before sending them to the central log server.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to label all offloaded audit logs before sending them to the central log server.\n\nEdit the /etc/audit/auditd.conf file and add or update the \"name_format\" option:\n\nname_format = hostname\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 Audit Daemon is configured to label all offloaded audit logs, with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep name_format /etc/audit/auditd.conf\nname_format = hostname\n\nIf the \"name_format\" option is not \"hostname\", \"fqd\", or \"numeric\", or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Enriched logging is needed to determine who, what, and when events occur on a system. Without this, determining root cause of an event will be much more difficult.\n\nWhen audit logs are not labeled before they are sent to a central log server, the audit data will not be able to be analyzed and tied back to the correct system.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000039-GPOS-00017, SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133, SRG-OS-000479-GPOS-00224","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000132","CCI-001851"],"reference_identifier":"7817","uuid":"f399ae95-4faf-40bd-84c0-66f357021c9b","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: DD9E912ED643C99E4A66A047EB379491C4BFDD2C\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must label all offloaded audit logs before sending them to the central log server.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271579","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271579","title":"SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271579","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031","rule_id_src":"SV-271579r1091449_rule","rule_id":"SV-271579","rule_version":"OL09-00-000760","rule_title":"OL 9 audit system must take appropriate action when an error writing to the audit storage volume occurs.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to shut down by default upon audit failure (unless availability is an overriding concern).\n\nAdd or update the following line (depending on configuration \"disk_error_action\" can be set to \"SYSLOG\" or \"SINGLE\" depending on configuration) in \"/etc/audit/auditd.conf\" file:\n\ndisk_error_action = HALT\n\nIf availability has been determined to be more important, and this decision is documented with the information system security officer (ISSO), configure the operating system to notify SA staff and ISSO staff in the event of an audit processing failure by setting the \"disk_error_action\" to \"SYSLOG\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 takes the appropriate action when an audit processing failure occurs.\n\nCheck that OL 9 takes the appropriate action when an audit processing failure occurs with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep disk_error_action /etc/audit/auditd.conf\ndisk_error_action = HALT\n\nIf the value of the \"disk_error_action\" option is not \"SYSLOG\", \"SINGLE\", or \"HALT\", or the line is commented out, ask the system administrator (SA) to indicate how the system takes appropriate action when an audit process failure occurs. If there is no evidence of appropriate action, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"It is critical that when the operating system is at risk of failing to process audit logs as required, it takes action to mitigate the failure. Audit processing failures include software/hardware errors; failures in the audit capturing mechanisms; and audit storage capacity being reached or exceeded. Responses to audit failure depend upon the nature of the failure mode.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000169"],"reference_identifier":"8298","uuid":"c5928ef0-337b-4002-a843-b91bed4f28aa","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: CE4DA6C5F31A89FFB3D121B7C070A526EB7FA3BD\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 audit system must take appropriate action when an error writing to the audit storage volume occurs.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271580","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271580","title":"SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271580","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031","rule_id_src":"SV-271580r1091452_rule","rule_id":"SV-271580","rule_version":"OL09-00-000765","rule_title":"OL 9 audit system must take appropriate action when the audit storage volume is full.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to shut down by default upon audit failure (unless availability is an overriding concern).\n\nAdd or update the following line (depending on configuration \"disk_full_action\" can be set to \"SYSLOG\" or \"SINGLE\" depending on configuration) in \"/etc/audit/auditd.conf\" file:\n\ndisk_full_action = HALT\n\nIf availability has been determined to be more important, and this decision is documented with the information system security officer (ISSO), configure the operating system to notify SA staff and ISSO staff in the event of an audit processing failure by setting the \"disk_full_action\" to \"SYSLOG\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 takes the appropriate action when the audit storage volume is full. \n\nCheck that OL 9 takes the appropriate action when the audit storage volume is full with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep disk_full_action /etc/audit/auditd.conf\ndisk_full_action = HALT\n\nIf the value of the \"disk_full_action\" option is not \"SYSLOG\", \"SINGLE\", or \"HALT\", or the line is commented out, ask the system administrator (SA) to indicate how the system takes appropriate action when an audit storage volume is full. If there is no evidence of appropriate action, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"It is critical that when the operating system is at risk of failing to process audit logs as required, it takes action to mitigate the failure. Audit processing failures include software/hardware errors; failures in the audit capturing mechanisms; and audit storage capacity being reached or exceeded. Responses to audit failure depend upon the nature of the failure mode.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000169"],"reference_identifier":"9444","uuid":"bc956056-de2b-432d-b8d1-32b660463e0b","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 74B007B4FC3302A79A2F4D50016AC2846D8DD44C\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 audit system must take appropriate action when the audit storage volume is full.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271581","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271581","title":"SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271581","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031","rule_id_src":"SV-271581r1091455_rule","rule_id":"SV-271581","rule_version":"OL09-00-000770","rule_title":"OL 9 audit system must take appropriate action when the audit files have reached maximum size.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to rotate the audit log when it reaches maximum size.\n\nAdd or update the following line in \"/etc/audit/auditd.conf\" file:\n\nmax_log_file_action = ROTATE","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 takes the appropriate action when the audit files have reached maximum size with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep max_log_file_action /etc/audit/auditd.conf\nmax_log_file_action = ROTATE\n\nIf the value of the \"max_log_file_action\" option is not \"ROTATE\", \"SINGLE\", or the line is commented out, ask the system administrator (SA)to indicate how the system takes appropriate action when an audit storage volume is full. If there is no evidence of appropriate action, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"It is critical that when the operating system is at risk of failing to process audit logs as required, it takes action to mitigate the failure. Audit processing failures include software/hardware errors; failures in the audit capturing mechanisms; and audit storage capacity being reached or exceeded. Responses to audit failure depend upon the nature of the failure mode.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000169"],"reference_identifier":"7241","uuid":"9540296c-cead-407d-a64c-01cc608aa56b","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 1184982AB2F6FB5DA861FDA4B28F6A7EEE6734C0\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 audit system must take appropriate action when the audit files have reached maximum size.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271582","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271582","title":"SRG-OS-000051-GPOS-00024","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271582","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000051-GPOS-00024","rule_id_src":"SV-271582r1092574_rule","rule_id":"SV-271582","rule_version":"OL09-00-000775","rule_title":"OL 9 must periodically flush audit records to disk to prevent the loss of audit records.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to flush audit to disk by adding or updating the following configuration in \"/etc/audit/auditd.conf\":\n\nfreq = 100\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured to flush audit records to disk after every 100 records with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep freq /etc/audit/auditd.conf \nfreq = 100 \n\nIf \"freq\" isn't set to a value of \"100\" or greater, the value is missing, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If option \"freq\" is not set to a value that requires audit records being written to disk after a threshold number is reached, then audit records may be lost.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000154"],"reference_identifier":"2062","uuid":"17b2a1c3-3ab6-4d54-b1e4-c43c795fc02d","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: DF642E8A8AFB738C967120ACAEC6627547A1CC18\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must periodically flush audit records to disk to prevent the loss of audit records.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271583","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271583","title":"SRG-OS-000057-GPOS-00027","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271583","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000057-GPOS-00027","rule_id_src":"SV-271583r1091461_rule","rule_id":"SV-271583","rule_version":"OL09-00-000785","rule_title":"OL 9 audit logs must be group-owned by root or by a restricted logging group to prevent unauthorized read access.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 audit logs to be group-owned by \"root\" or a restricted logging group.\n\nChange the group of the directory of \"/var/log/audit\" to be owned by a correct group.\n\nIdentify the group that is configured to own audit log:\n\n$ sudo grep -P '^[ ]*log_group[ ]+=.*$' /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\nChange the ownership to that group:\n\n$ sudo chgrp ${GROUP} /var/log/audit","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 audit logs are group-owned by \"root\" or a restricted logging group. \n\nFirst determine if a group other than \"root\" has been assigned to the audit logs with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep log_group /etc/audit/auditd.conf\nlog_group = root\n\nThen determine where the audit logs are stored with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -iw log_file /etc/audit/auditd.conf\nlog_file = /var/log/audit/audit.log\n\nThen, using the location of the audit log file, determine if the audit log is group-owned by \"root\" using the following command:\n\n$ sudo stat -c \"%G %n\" /var/log/audit/audit.log\nroot /var/log/audit/audit.log\n\nIf the audit log is not group-owned by \"root\" or the configured alternative logging group, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Unauthorized disclosure of audit records can reveal system and configuration data to attackers, thus compromising its confidentiality.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000057-GPOS-00027, SRG-OS-000058-GPOS-00028, SRG-OS-000059-GPOS-00029, SRG-OS-000206-GPOS-00084","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000162","CCI-000163","CCI-000164","CCI-001314"],"reference_identifier":"5734","uuid":"eed132ed-b340-45cb-af10-f21ea2b5de1c","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 9C395C546A12FAB8076C0945C632D132F1782F59\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 audit logs must be group-owned by root or by a restricted logging group to prevent unauthorized read access.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271584","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271584","title":"SRG-OS-000057-GPOS-00027","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271584","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000057-GPOS-00027","rule_id_src":"SV-271584r1091464_rule","rule_id":"SV-271584","rule_version":"OL09-00-000790","rule_title":"OL 9 audit log directory must be owned by root to prevent unauthorized read access.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to protect the audit log from unauthorized read access by setting the correct owner as \"root\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo chown root /var/log/audit","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 audit logs directory is owned by \"root\". \n\nFirst determine where the audit logs are stored with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -iw log_file /etc/audit/auditd.conf\nlog_file = /var/log/audit/audit.log\n\nThen using the location of the audit log file, determine if the audit log directory is owned by \"root\" using the following command:\n\n$ sudo ls -ld /var/log/audit\ndrwx------ 2 root root 23 Jun 11 11:56 /var/log/audit\n\nIf the audit log directory is not owned by \"root\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Unauthorized disclosure of audit records can reveal system and configuration data to attackers, thus compromising its confidentiality.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000057-GPOS-00027, SRG-OS-000058-GPOS-00028, SRG-OS-000059-GPOS-00029, SRG-OS-000206-GPOS-00084","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000162","CCI-000163","CCI-000164","CCI-001314"],"reference_identifier":"4088","uuid":"518f5fd0-d484-4ded-8cd8-5557a10390bf","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 10AF61535113CDA11BCA66CFA54C2DAAF3E47CC0\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'OL 9 audit log directory must be owned by root to prevent unauthorized read access.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271585","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271585","title":"SRG-OS-000057-GPOS-00027","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271585","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000057-GPOS-00027","rule_id_src":"SV-271585r1091467_rule","rule_id":"SV-271585","rule_version":"OL09-00-000795","rule_title":"OL 9 audit logs file must have mode 0600 or less permissive to prevent unauthorized access to the audit log.","fix_text":"Configure the audit logs to have a mode of \"0600\" with the following command:\n\nReplace \"[audit_log_file]\" to the correct audit log path, by default this location is \"/var/log/audit/audit.log\".\n\n$ sudo chmod 0600 /var/log/audit/[audit_log_file]\n\nCheck the group that owns the system audit logs:\n\n$ sudo grep -m 1 -q ^log_group /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\nIf the log_group is not defined or it is set to root, configure the permissions the following way:\n\n$ sudo chmod 0640 $log_file\n$ sudo chmod 0440 $log_file.*\n\nOtherwise, configure the permissions the following way:\n\n$ sudo chmod 0600 $log_file\n$ sudo chmod 0400 $log_file.*","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 audit logs have a mode of \"0600\". \n\nFirst determine where the audit logs are stored with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -iw log_file /etc/audit/auditd.conf\nlog_file = /var/log/audit/audit.log\n\nThen using the location of the audit log file, determine if the audit log files as a mode of \"0640\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo ls -la /var/log/audit/*.log\nrw-------. 2 root root 237923 Jun 11 11:56 /var/log/audit/audit.log\n\nIf the audit logs have a mode more permissive than \"0600\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Only authorized personnel should be aware of errors and the details of the errors. Error messages are an indicator of an organization's operational state or can identify the OL 9 system or platform. Additionally, Personally Identifiable Information (PII) and operational information must not be revealed through error messages to unauthorized personnel or their designated representatives.\n\nThe structure and content of error messages must be carefully considered by the organization and development team. The extent to which the information system is able to identify and handle error conditions is guided by organizational policy and operational requirements.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000057-GPOS-00027, SRG-OS-000058-GPOS-00028, SRG-OS-000059-GPOS-00029, SRG-OS-000206-GPOS-00084","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000162","CCI-000163","CCI-000164","CCI-001314"],"reference_identifier":"7448","uuid":"d2cb84a6-a272-436d-92bb-ee243efeaf96","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: D9583B8413C77EE923384E9B65F11F7056F700A5\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 audit logs file must have mode 0600 or less permissive to prevent unauthorized access to the audit log.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271586","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271586","title":"SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271586","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031","rule_id_src":"SV-271586r1092576_rule","rule_id":"SV-271586","rule_version":"OL09-00-000800","rule_title":"OL 9 audit system must audit local events.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to generate audit records for local events by adding or updating the following line in \"/etc/audit/auditd.conf\":\n\nlocal_events = yes \n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 audit system is configured to audit local events with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep local_events /etc/audit/auditd.conf \nlocal_events = yes \n\nIf \"local_events\" isn't set to \"yes\", if the command does not return a line, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without establishing what type of events occurred, the source of events, where events occurred, and the outcome of events, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events leading up to an outage or attack.\n\nIf option \"local_events\" isn't set to \"yes\" only events from network will be aggregated.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000169"],"reference_identifier":"6517","uuid":"7cffdfba-3824-4b8f-b09e-f5ce73f1f1c1","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 80686BB00A24027282BDC48839EF660BDD77230E\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'OL 9 audit system must audit local events.' is not present or not in use on this the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271587","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271587","title":"SRG-OS-000063-GPOS-00032","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271587","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000063-GPOS-00032","rule_id_src":"SV-271587r1091473_rule","rule_id":"SV-271587","rule_version":"OL09-00-000805","rule_title":"OL 9 must allow only the information system security manager (ISSM) (or individuals or roles appointed by the ISSM) to select which auditable events are to be audited.","fix_text":"Configure the files in directory \"/etc/audit/rules.d/\" and the \"/etc/audit/auditd.conf\" file to have a mode of \"0640\" with the following commands:\n\n$ sudo chmod 0640 /etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\n$ sudo chmod 0640 /etc/audit/rules.d/[customrulesfile].rules\n$ sudo chmod 0640 /etc/audit/auditd.conf","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 sets files in directories \"/etc/audit/rules.d/\" and \"/etc/audit/auditd.conf\" files to have a mode of \"0640\" or less permissive with the following command:\n\n$ sudo stat -c \"%a %n\"  /etc/audit/rules.d/*.rules\n\n$ sudo sh -c 'stat -c \"%a %n\" /etc/audit/rules.d/*.rules'\n600 /etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules \n\nIf the files in the \"/etc/audit/rules.d/\" directory or the \"/etc/audit/auditd.conf\" file have a mode more permissive than \"0640\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without the capability to restrict the roles and individuals that can select which events are audited, unauthorized personnel may be able to prevent the auditing of critical events. Misconfigured audits may degrade the system's performance by overwhelming the audit log. Misconfigured audits may also make it more difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000171"],"reference_identifier":"7514","uuid":"1bd179cf-bbce-427e-b720-6ab7d59bf75d","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 380EF7B547CA43F9F71CBC59962FF9586330826D\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'OL 9 must allow only the information system security manager (ISSM) (or individuals or roles appointed by the ISSM) to select which auditable events are to be audited.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271588","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271588","title":"SRG-OS-000063-GPOS-00032","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271588","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000063-GPOS-00032","rule_id_src":"SV-271588r1091476_rule","rule_id":"SV-271588","rule_version":"OL09-00-000810","rule_title":"OL 9 /etc/audit/auditd.conf file must have 0640 or less permissive to prevent unauthorized access.","fix_text":"Configure the /etc/audit/auditd.conf file to have a mode of 0640 with the command:\n\n$ sudo chmod 0640 /etc/audit/auditd.conf","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 sets the mode of /etc/audit/auditd.conf with the command:\n\n$ sudo stat -c \"%a %n\" /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n640 /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\nIf \"/etc/audit/auditd.conf\" does not have a mode of \"0640\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without the capability to restrict the roles and individuals that can select which events are audited, unauthorized personnel may be able to prevent the auditing of critical events. Misconfigured audits may degrade the system's performance by overwhelming the audit log. Misconfigured audits may also make it more difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000171"],"reference_identifier":"2448","uuid":"81962f90-2459-4aef-8dc6-1c24713b6ccb","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 51352F8E5F68B146AF2B8A900D010925A8BC5FA9\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 /etc/audit/auditd.conf file must have 0640 or less permissive to prevent unauthorized access.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271589","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271589","title":"SRG-OS-000046-GPOS-00022","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271589","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000046-GPOS-00022","rule_id_src":"SV-271589r1091479_rule","rule_id":"SV-271589","rule_version":"OL09-00-000815","rule_title":"OL 9 must forward mail from postmaster to the root account using a postfix alias.","fix_text":"Configure a valid email address as an alias for the root account.\n\nAppend the following line to \"/etc/aliases\":\n\npostmaster: root\n\nThen, run the following command:\n\n$ sudo newaliases","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 administrators are notified in the event of an audit processing failure.\n\nCheck that the \"/etc/aliases\" file has a defined value for \"root\".\n\n$ grep \"postmaster:\\s*root$\" /etc/aliases\n\nIf the command does not return a line, or the line is commented out, ask the system administrator to indicate how they and the information systems security officer (ISSO) are notified of an audit process failure. If there is no evidence of the proper personnel being notified of an audit processing failure, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"It is critical for the appropriate personnel to be aware if a system is at risk of failing to process audit logs as required. Without this notification, the security personnel may be unaware of an impending failure of the audit capability, and system operation may be adversely affected.\n\nAudit processing failures include software/hardware errors, failures in the audit capturing mechanisms, and audit storage capacity being reached or exceeded.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000139"],"reference_identifier":"8893","uuid":"f0dad509-590d-4815-b19a-3378a9951ed2","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 64AC972F1D0F9A7E0A5BEA5369B5A97E1CA4FEC8\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must forward mail from postmaster to the root account using a postfix alias.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271590","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271590","title":"SRG-OS-000046-GPOS-00022","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271590","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000046-GPOS-00022","rule_id_src":"SV-271590r1091482_rule","rule_id":"SV-271590","rule_version":"OL09-00-000820","rule_title":"OL 9 must take appropriate action when a critical audit processing failure occurs.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to shut down when auditing failures occur.\n\nAdd the following line to the bottom of the /etc/audit/audit.rules file:\n\n-f 2","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 audit service is configured to panic on a critical error with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep \"\\-f\" /etc/audit/audit.rules \n-f 2\n\nIf the value for \"-f\" is not \"2\", and availability is not documented as an overriding concern, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"It is critical for the appropriate personnel to be aware if a system is at risk of failing to process audit logs as required. Without this notification, the security personnel may be unaware of an impending failure of the audit capability, and system operation may be adversely affected.\n\nAudit processing failures include software/hardware errors, failures in the audit capturing mechanisms, and audit storage capacity being reached or exceeded.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000046-GPOS-00022, SRG-OS-000343-GPOS-00135","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000139","CCI-000140"],"reference_identifier":"3343","uuid":"5e751a83-e1c6-4317-82be-2eea755ce19d","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 8D15E1CEF121521A8A01EBF20A6BC18848F003A1\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must take appropriate action when a critical audit processing failure occurs.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271591","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271591","title":"SRG-OS-000046-GPOS-00022","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271591","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000046-GPOS-00022","rule_id_src":"SV-271591r1092578_rule","rule_id":"SV-271591","rule_version":"OL09-00-000825","rule_title":"The OL 9 system administrator (SA) and/or information system security officer (ISSO) (at a minimum) must be alerted of an audit processing failure event.","fix_text":"Configure the auditd service to notify the SA and ISSO in the event of an audit processing failure.\n\nEdit the following line in \"/etc/audit/auditd.conf\" to ensure that administrators are notified via email for those situations:\n\naction_mail_acct = root\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured to notify the SA and/or ISSO (at a minimum) in the event of an audit processing failure with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep action_mail_acct /etc/audit/auditd.conf\naction_mail_acct = root\n\nIf the value of the \"action_mail_acct\" keyword is not set to \"root\" and/or other accounts for security personnel, the \"action_mail_acct\" keyword is missing, or the retuned line is commented out, ask the SA to indicate how they and the ISSO are notified of an audit process failure. If there is no evidence of the proper personnel being notified of an audit processing failure, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"It is critical for the appropriate personnel to be aware if a system is at risk of failing to process audit logs as required. Without this notification, the security personnel may be unaware of an impending failure of the audit capability, and system operation may be adversely affected.\n\nAudit processing failures include software/hardware errors, failures in the audit capturing mechanisms, and audit storage capacity being reached or exceeded.\n\nThis requirement applies to each audit data storage repository (i.e., distinct information system component where audit records are stored), the centralized audit storage capacity of organizations (i.e., all audit data storage repositories combined), or both.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000046-GPOS-00022, SRG-OS-000343-GPOS-00134","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000139","CCI-001855"],"reference_identifier":"1548","uuid":"618a7bad-47ea-40fe-a639-12375ef01071","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 7D9221AEBA3275A2560E32645F298728E4520FBB\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'The OL 9 system administrator (SA) and/or information system security officer (ISSO) (at a minimum) must be alerted of an audit processing failure event.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271592","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271592","title":"SRG-OS-000254-GPOS-00095","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271592","severity":"low","group_title":"SRG-OS-000254-GPOS-00095","rule_id_src":"SV-271592r1091488_rule","rule_id":"SV-271592","rule_version":"OL09-00-000830","rule_title":"OL 9 must allocate an audit_backlog_limit of sufficient size to capture processes that start prior to the audit daemon.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to allocate sufficient audit_backlog_limit to capture processes that start prior to the audit daemon with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grubby --update-kernel=ALL --args=audit_backlog_limit=8192","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 allocates a sufficient audit_backlog_limit to capture processes that start prior to the audit daemon with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grubby --info=ALL | grep args | grep -v 'audit_backlog_limit=8192' \n\nIf the command returns any outputs, and audit_backlog_limit is less than \"8192\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without the capability to generate audit records, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nIf auditing is enabled late in the startup process, the actions of some startup processes may not be audited. Some audit systems also maintain state information only available if auditing is enabled before a given process is created.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nAllocating an audit_backlog_limit of sufficient size is critical in maintaining a stable boot process. With an insufficient limit allocated, the system is susceptible to boot failures and crashes.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000254-GPOS-00095, SRG-OS-000341-GPOS-00132","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001464","CCI-001849"],"reference_identifier":"4606","uuid":"09e2f822-d708-470a-ad5a-df402c906046","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 77137B442BBD600D1937ACA90BDED577FC6CCDB3\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'OL 9 must allocate an audit_backlog_limit of sufficient size to capture processes that start prior to the audit daemon.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271593","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271593","title":"SRG-OS-000255-GPOS-00096","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271593","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000255-GPOS-00096","rule_id_src":"SV-271593r1092580_rule","rule_id":"SV-271593","rule_version":"OL09-00-000835","rule_title":"OL 9 must produce audit records containing information to establish the identity of any individual or process associated with the event.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to produce audit records containing information to establish the identity of any individual or process associated with the event.\n\nEdit the /etc/audit/auditd.conf file and add or update the \"log_format\" option:\n\nlog_format = ENRICHED\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 audit system is configured to resolve audit information before writing to disk, with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep log_format /etc/audit/auditd.conf\nlog_format = ENRICHED\n\nIf the \"log_format\" option is not \"ENRICHED\", or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without establishing what type of events occurred, the source of events, where events occurred, and the outcome of events, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events leading up to an outage or attack.\n\nAudit record content that may be necessary to satisfy this requirement includes, for example, time stamps, source and destination addresses, user/process identifiers, event descriptions, success/fail indications, filenames involved, and access control or flow control rules invoked.\n\nEnriched logging aids in making sense of who, what, and when events occur on a system. Without this, determining root cause of an event will be much more difficult.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001487"],"reference_identifier":"6501","uuid":"fc6dd658-54b6-4a56-bf73-838d5366a87a","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 0A9DBAF689638B506B73764AB304B346908EE238\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must produce audit records containing information to establish the identity of any individual or process associated with the event.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271594","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271594","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271594","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-271594r1155314_rule","rule_id":"SV-271594","rule_version":"OL09-00-000840","rule_title":"OL 9 must be configured so that successful/unsuccessful uses of the umount system call generate an audit record.","fix_text":"Configure the audit system to generate an audit event for any successful/unsuccessful use of the umount system call by adding or updating the following rules in \"/etc/audit/audit.rules\" and adding the following rules to \"/etc/audit/rules.d/perm_mod.rules\" or updating the existing rules in files in the \"/etc/audit/rules.d/\" directory:\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S umount -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod -a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S umount -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify OL 9 is configured to audit the execution of the \"umount\" command with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep umount\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S umount -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=-1 -F key=privileged-umount\n\nIf the command does not return an audit rule for \"umount\" or any of the lines returned are commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The changing of file permissions could indicate that a user is attempting to gain access to information that would otherwise be disallowed. Auditing DAC modifications can facilitate the identification of patterns of abuse among both authorized and unauthorized users.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000130","CCI-000169","CCI-002884","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"8837","uuid":"411eb7ee-7a79-4ecd-8c8e-90fe124aa5e6","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 2E78101459E7B1591F1B662DCD74357E142C3425\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must be configured so that successful/unsuccessful uses of the umount system call generate an audit record.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271595","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271595","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271595","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-271595r1155316_rule","rule_id":"SV-271595","rule_version":"OL09-00-000845","rule_title":"OL 9 must be configured so that successful/unsuccessful uses of the umount2 system call generate an audit record.","fix_text":"Configure the audit system to generate an audit event for any successful/unsuccessful use of the umount2 system call by adding the following rules to a rules file in /etc/audit/rules.d/ directory: (Example /etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules)\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S umount2 -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S umount2 -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify OL 9 generates an audit record for all uses of the umount2 system call with the following commands:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep umount2\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S umount2 -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=-1 -F key=privileged-umount\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S umount2 -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=-1 -F key=privileged-umount\n\nIf the command does not return an audit rule for \"umount2\" or any of the lines returned are commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The changing of file permissions could indicate that a user is attempting to gain access to information that would otherwise be disallowed. Auditing discretionary access control (DAC) modifications can facilitate the identification of patterns of abuse among both authorized and unauthorized users.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000130","CCI-000169","CCI-002884","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"1571","uuid":"be2f6a92-1651-4164-b59b-26cfeaa610fd","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 3E12A87D1855FDE3DF0418EBADE5B09FEF9462DE\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must be configured so that successful/unsuccessful uses of the umount2 system call generate an audit record.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271596","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271596","title":"SRG-OS-000341-GPOS-00132","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271596","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000341-GPOS-00132","rule_id_src":"SV-271596r1091500_rule","rule_id":"SV-271596","rule_version":"OL09-00-000850","rule_title":"OL 9 must allocate audit record storage capacity to store at least one week's worth of audit records.","fix_text":"Allocate enough storage capacity for at least one week of audit records when audit records are not immediately sent to a central audit record storage facility.\n\nIf audit records are stored on a partition made specifically for audit records, resize the partition with sufficient space to contain one week of audit records.\n\nIf audit records are not stored on a partition made specifically for audit records, a new partition with sufficient space will need be to be created.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 allocates audit record storage capacity to store at least one week of audit records when audit records are not immediately sent to a central audit record storage facility.\n\nNote: The partition size needed to capture a week of audit records is based on the activity level of the system and the total storage capacity available. Typically 10GB of storage space for audit records should be sufficient.\n\nDetermine which partition the audit records are being written to with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep log_file /etc/audit/auditd.conf\nlog_file = /var/log/audit/audit.log \n\nCheck the size of the partition that audit records are written to with the following command and verify whether it is sufficiently large:\n\n # df -h /var/log/audit/\n/dev/sda2 24G 10.4G 13.6G 43% /var/log/audit \n\nIf the audit record partition is not allocated for sufficient storage capacity, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"To ensure OL 9 systems have a sufficient storage capacity in which to write the audit logs, OL 9 needs to be able to allocate audit record storage capacity.\n\nThe task of allocating audit record storage capacity is usually performed during initial installation of OL 9.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000341-GPOS-00132, SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001849","CCI-001851"],"reference_identifier":"2930","uuid":"93243140-6b20-49aa-99b7-677a94ed629a","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 7383FA389AE32CE4CAA3030BF5E3FA287C1ED832\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must allocate audit record storage capacity to store at least one week's worth of audit records.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271597","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271597","title":"SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271597","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133","rule_id_src":"SV-271597r1092586_rule","rule_id":"SV-271597","rule_version":"OL09-00-000855","rule_title":"OL 9 must be configured to offload audit records onto a different system from the system being audited via syslog.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to offload audit records onto a different system from the system being audited via syslog.\n\nEdit the /etc/audit/plugins.d/syslog.conf file and add or update the \"active\" option:\n\nactive = yes\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured use the audisp-remote syslog service with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep active /etc/audit/plugins.d/syslog.conf \nactive = yes\n\nIf the \"active\" keyword does not have a value of \"yes\", the line is commented out, or the line is missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The auditd service does not include the ability to send audit records to a centralized server for management directly. However, it can use a plug-in for audit event multiplexor (audispd) to pass audit records to the local syslog server.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133, SRG-OS-000479-GPOS-00224","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001851"],"reference_identifier":"6703","uuid":"99b13919-7d35-4583-ba24-5f0f2565aa54","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: BAEA11CD72E74DD8851BE08578CEC01AF3441CBB\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must be configured to offload audit records onto a different system from the system being audited via syslog.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271598","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271598","title":"SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271598","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133","rule_id_src":"SV-271598r1092588_rule","rule_id":"SV-271598","rule_version":"OL09-00-000860","rule_title":"OL 9 must take appropriate action when the internal event queue is full.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to take appropriate action when the internal event queue is full.\n\nEdit the /etc/audit/auditd.conf file and add or update the \"overflow_action\" option:\n\noverflow_action = syslog\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 audit system is configured to take an appropriate action when the internal event queue is full:\n\n$ sudo grep -i overflow_action /etc/audit/auditd.conf \noverflow_action = syslog\n\nIf the value of the \"overflow_action\" option is not set to \"syslog\", \"single\", \"halt\" or the line is commented out, ask the system administrator (SA) to indicate how the audit logs are offloaded to a different system or media.\n\nIf there is no evidence that the transfer of the audit logs being offloaded to another system or media takes appropriate action if the internal event queue becomes full, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The audit system should have an action setup in the event the internal event queue becomes full so that no data is lost. Information stored in one location is vulnerable to accidental or incidental deletion or alteration.\n\nOffloading is a common process in information systems with limited audit storage capacity.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133, SRG-OS-000479-GPOS-00224","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001851"],"reference_identifier":"9289","uuid":"70fef38f-50dd-46f4-a53e-2fd797e1405b","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-271599","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271599","title":"SRG-OS-000343-GPOS-00134","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271599","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000343-GPOS-00134","rule_id_src":"SV-271599r1134856_rule","rule_id":"SV-271599","rule_version":"OL09-00-000865","rule_title":"OL 9 must take action when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 75 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to initiate an action to notify the SA and ISSO (at a minimum) when allocated audit record storage volume reaches (at most) 75 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity by adding/modifying the following line in the /etc/audit/auditd.conf file:\n\nspace_left  = 25%","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 takes action when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 75 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -w space_left /etc/audit/auditd.conf\nspace_left = 25%\n\nIf the value of the \"space_left\" keyword is not set to 25 percent or greater of the storage volume allocated to audit logs, or if the line is commented out, ask the system administrator (SA) to indicate how the system is providing real-time alerts to the SA and information system security officer (ISSO). \n\nIf the \"space_left\" value is not configured to the value \"25%\" or more, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If security personnel are not notified immediately when storage volume reaches a maximum of 75 percent utilization, they are unable to plan for audit record storage capacity expansion. The notification can be set to trigger at lower utilization thresholds at the ISSO's discretion.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001855"],"reference_identifier":"6206","uuid":"e66881e8-b99d-45d9-a1e3-de1d05b260ab","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: AEFB57AA185E72700F298D139422016EA116B6EB\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'OL 9 must take action when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 75 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271600","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271600","title":"SRG-OS-000343-GPOS-00134","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271600","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000343-GPOS-00134","rule_id_src":"SV-271600r1134858_rule","rule_id":"SV-271600","rule_version":"OL09-00-000870","rule_title":"OL 9 must notify the system administrator (SA) and information system security officer (ISSO) (at a minimum) when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 75 percent utilization.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to initiate an action to notify the SA and ISSO (at a minimum) when allocated audit record storage volume reaches (at most) 75 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity by adding/modifying the following line in the /etc/audit/auditd.conf file:\n\nspace_left_action = email","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 notifies the SA and ISSO (at a minimum) when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 75 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -w space_left_action /etc/audit/auditd.conf\nspace_left_action = email\n\nIf the value of the \"space_left_action\" is not set to \"email\", or if the line is commented out, ask the SA to indicate how the system is providing real-time alerts to the SA and ISSO.\n\nIf there is no evidence that real-time alerts are configured on the system, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If security personnel are not notified immediately when storage volume reaches a maximum of 75 percent utilization, they are unable to plan for audit record storage capacity expansion. The notification can be set to trigger at lower utilization thresholds at the ISSO's discretion.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001855"],"reference_identifier":"1502","uuid":"e5e2b7c9-ff2a-4bdb-8355-a44ea0e291a3","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 18F9E6DD909AC1ABEFDFAC19C6BCFE61FCDF008B\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'OL 9 must notify the system administrator (SA) and information system security officer (ISSO) (at a minimum) when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 75 percent utilization.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271601","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271601","title":"SRG-OS-000343-GPOS-00134","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271601","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000343-GPOS-00134","rule_id_src":"SV-271601r1091515_rule","rule_id":"SV-271601","rule_version":"OL09-00-000875","rule_title":"OL 9 must take action when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 95 percent of the audit record storage capacity.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to initiate an action when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 95 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity by adding/modifying the following line in the /etc/audit/auditd.conf file.\n\nadmin_space_left  = 5%","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 takes action when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 95 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -w admin_space_left /etc/audit/auditd.conf\nadmin_space_left = 5%\n\nIf the value of the \"admin_space_left\" keyword is not set to 5 percent of the storage volume allocated to audit logs, or if the line is commented out, ask the system administrator (SA) to indicate how the system is taking action if the allocated storage is about to reach capacity. If the \"space_left\" value is not configured to the correct value, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If action is not taken when storage volume reaches 95 percent utilization, the auditing system may fail when the storage volume reaches capacity.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001855"],"reference_identifier":"3627","uuid":"fb21497f-961f-49d1-8a49-b5c150c23b06","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: B650D6A59F23A13E9D8354F60C7122CBA6D355D4\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'OL 9 must take action when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 95 percent of the audit record storage capacity.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271602","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271602","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271602","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271602r1092590_rule","rule_id":"SV-271602","rule_version":"OL09-00-000880","rule_title":"OL 9 must write audit records to disk.","fix_text":"Configure the audit system to write log files to the disk.\n\nEdit the /etc/audit/auditd.conf file and add or update the \"write_logs\" option to \"yes\":\n\nwrite_logs = yes \n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 audit system is configured to write logs to the disk with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep write_logs /etc/audit/auditd.conf \nwrite_logs = yes \n\nIf \"write_logs\" does not have a value of \"yes\", the line is commented out, or the line is missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Audit data should be synchronously written to disk to ensure log integrity. This setting ensures that all audit event data is written disk.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2528","uuid":"83477fa5-b332-4358-a2ed-fdd1265c26f1","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: A0A8FD8CDE165433D455B1CB8E7DF6897456EEC9\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must write audit records to disk.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271603","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271603","title":"SRG-OS-000343-GPOS-00134","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271603","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000343-GPOS-00134","rule_id_src":"SV-271603r1092592_rule","rule_id":"SV-271603","rule_version":"OL09-00-000885","rule_title":"OL 9 must act when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 95 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity.","fix_text":"Configure the auditd service to take action in the event of allocated audit record storage volume reaches 95 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity.\n\nEdit the following line in \"/etc/audit/auditd.conf\" to ensure that the system is forced into single user mode in the event the audit record storage volume is about to reach maximum capacity:\n\nadmin_space_left_action = single \n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for changes to take effect.\n\nRestart auditd:\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured to take action in the event of allocated audit record storage volume reaches 95 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep admin_space_left_action /etc/audit/auditd.conf\nadmin_space_left_action = single\n\nIf the value of the \"admin_space_left_action\" is not set to \"single\", or if the line is commented out, ask the system administrator (SA) to indicate how the system is providing real-time alerts to the SA and information system security officer (ISSO).\n\nIf there is no evidence that real-time alerts are configured on the system, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If action is not taken when storage volume reaches 95 percent utilization, the auditing system may fail when the storage volume reaches capacity.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001855"],"reference_identifier":"9157","uuid":"92105569-6291-4003-ae3c-33045e3e988a","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: E47BACE2E9C9A19BBDC8040DEF2091590A9AD3D8\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must act when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 95 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271604","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271604","title":"SRG-OS-000066-GPOS-00034","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271604","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000066-GPOS-00034","rule_id_src":"SV-271604r1091524_rule","rule_id":"SV-271604","rule_version":"OL09-00-000900","rule_title":"OL 9, for PKI-based authentication, must validate certificates by constructing a certification path (which includes status information) to an accepted trust anchor.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9, for PKI-based authentication, to validate certificates by constructing a certification path (which includes status information) to an accepted trust anchor.\n\nObtain a valid copy of the DOD root CA file from the PKI CA certificate bundle from cyber.mil and copy the DOD_PKE_CA_chain.pem into the following file:\n/etc/sssd/pki/sssd_auth_ca_db.pem","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 for PKI-based authentication has valid certificates by constructing a certification path (which includes status information) to an accepted trust anchor.\n\nCheck that the system has a valid DOD root CA installed with the following command:\n\n$ sudo openssl x509 -text -in /etc/sssd/pki/sssd_auth_ca_db.pem\n\nExample output:\n\nCertificate:\n    Data:\n        Version: 3 (0x2)\n        Serial Number: 1 (0x1)\n        Signature Algorithm: sha256WithRSAEncryption\n        Issuer: C = US, O = U.S. Government, OU = DOD, OU = PKI, CN = DOD Root CA 3\n        Validity\n        Not Before: Mar 20 18:46:41 2012 GMT\n        Not After: Dec 30 18:46:41 2029 GMT\n        Subject: C = US, O = U.S. Government, OU = DOD, OU = PKI, CN = DOD Root CA 3\n        Subject Public Key Info:\n            Public Key Algorithm: rsaEncryption\n\nIf the root CA file is not a DOD-issued certificate with a valid date and installed in the \"/etc/sssd/pki/sssd_auth_ca_db.pem\" location, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without path validation, an informed trust decision by the relying party cannot be made when presented with any certificate not already explicitly trusted.\n\nA trust anchor is an authoritative entity represented via a public key and associated data. It is used in the context of public key infrastructures, X.509 digital certificates, and DNSSEC.\n\nWhen there is a chain of trust, usually the top entity to be trusted becomes the trust anchor; it can be, for example, a certification authority (CA). A certification path starts with the subject certificate and proceeds through a number of intermediate certificates up to a trusted root certificate, typically issued by a trusted CA.\n\nThis requirement verifies that a certification path to an accepted trust anchor is used for certificate validation and that the path includes status information. Path validation is necessary for a relying party to make an informed trust decision when presented with any certificate not already explicitly trusted. Status information for certification paths includes certificate revocation lists or online certificate status protocol responses. Validation of the certificate status information is out of scope for this requirement.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000066-GPOS-00034, SRG-OS-000384-GPOS-00167, SRG-OS-000775-GPOS-00230","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000185","CCI-004068","CCI-004909"],"reference_identifier":"3745","uuid":"c91b18d2-c1d2-4b74-8b2f-33cdc85e6839","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 810F497AE4625C20995F034C8B64F544CAD79F65\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9, for PKI-based authentication, must validate certificates by constructing a certification path (which includes status information) to an accepted trust anchor.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271605","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271605","title":"SRG-OS-000067-GPOS-00035","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271605","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000067-GPOS-00035","rule_id_src":"SV-271605r1091527_rule","rule_id":"SV-271605","rule_version":"OL09-00-000905","rule_title":"OL 9, for PKI-based authentication, must enforce authorized access to the corresponding private key.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9, for PKI-based authentication, to enforce authorized access to the corresponding private key.\n\nCreate a new private and public key pair that uses a passcode with the following command:\n\n$ sudo ssh-keygen -n [passphrase]","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 SSH private key files have a passcode.\n\nFor each private key stored on the system, use the following command:\n\n$ sudo ssh-keygen -y -f /path/to/file\n\nIf the contents of the key are displayed, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If the private key is discovered, an attacker can use the key to authenticate as an authorized user and gain access to the network infrastructure.\n\nThe cornerstone of the PKI is the private key used to encrypt or digitally sign information.\n\nIf the private key is stolen, this will lead to the compromise of the authentication and nonrepudiation gained through PKI because the attacker can use the private key to digitally sign documents and pretend to be the authorized user.\n\nBoth the holders of a digital certificate and the issuing authority must protect the computers, storage devices, or whatever they use to keep the private keys.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000186"],"reference_identifier":"2134","uuid":"d1e9304c-7f8d-4008-9655-9e1f7cc5bf14","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: AE071D9AF68329390A60729797C2C96A9B7567F4\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9, for PKI-based authentication, must enforce authorized access to the corresponding private key.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271606","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271606","title":"SRG-OS-000068-GPOS-00036","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271606","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000068-GPOS-00036","rule_id_src":"SV-271606r1091530_rule","rule_id":"SV-271606","rule_version":"OL09-00-000910","rule_title":"OL 9 must map the authenticated identity to the user or group account for PKI-based authentication.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to map the authenticated identity to the user or group account by adding or modifying the certmap section of the \"/etc/sssd/sssd.conf\" file based on the following example:\n\n[certmap/testing.test/rule_name]\nmatchrule = .*EDIPI@mil\nmaprule = (userCertificate;binary={cert!bin})\ndmains = testing.test\n\nThe \"sssd\" service must be restarted for the changes to take effect. To restart the \"sssd\" service, run the following command:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart sssd.service","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 maps the authenticated identity to the certificate of the user or group to the corresponding user or group in the \"sssd.conf\" file with the following command:\n\n$ sudo cat /etc/sssd/sssd.conf \n[certmap/testing.test/rule_name]\nmatchrule =<SAN>.*EDIPI@mil\nmaprule = (userCertificate;binary={cert!bin})\ndomains = testing.test\n\nIf the certmap section does not exist, ask the system administrator (SA) to indicate how certificates are mapped to accounts. If there is no evidence of certificate mapping, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without mapping the certificate used to authenticate to the user account, the ability to determine the identity of the individual user or group will not be available for forensic analysis.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000187"],"reference_identifier":"6878","uuid":"d6971347-118b-44f3-b372-9d81a8a84b2d","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 0D4D3B5BB05DEB107D77C624C7379302382F9598\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must map the authenticated identity to the user or group account for PKI-based authentication.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271607","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271607","title":"SRG-OS-000375-GPOS-00160","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271607","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000375-GPOS-00160","rule_id_src":"SV-271607r1091533_rule","rule_id":"SV-271607","rule_version":"OL09-00-000925","rule_title":"OL 9 must enable certificate-based smart card authentication.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to enable certificate-based smart card authentication.\n\nEdit the file \"/etc/sssd/sssd.conf\" and add or edit the following line:\n\npam_cert_auth = True","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 has smart cards enabled in System Security Services Daemon (SSSD) if smart cards are used for MFA with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep pam_cert_auth /etc/sssd/sssd.conf\npam_cert_auth = True \n\nIf \"pam_cert_auth\" is not set to \"True\", the line is commented out, or the line is missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without the use of multifactor authentication (MFA), the ease of access to privileged functions is greatly increased. Multifactor authentication requires using two or more factors to achieve authentication. A privileged account is defined as an information system account with authorizations of a privileged user. The DOD Common Access Card (CAC) with DOD-approved PKI is an example of multifactor authentication.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000375-GPOS-00160, SRG-OS-000105-GPOS-00052","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004046","CCI-000765"],"reference_identifier":"2607","uuid":"76b7d025-1b5c-48b3-a307-ff0e9aba22d9","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 9668BFC1CE7F3438F537320840F4A21C5383CE0E\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'OL 9 must enable certificate-based smart card authentication.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271608","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271608","title":"SRG-OS-000375-GPOS-00160","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271608","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000375-GPOS-00160","rule_id_src":"SV-271608r1091536_rule","rule_id":"SV-271608","rule_version":"OL09-00-000930","rule_title":"OL 9 must implement certificate status checking for multifactor authentication (MFA).","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to implement certificate status checking for MFA.\n\nReview the \"/etc/sssd/conf.d/certificate_verification.conf\" file to determine if the system is configured to prevent OCSP or certificate verification.\n\nAdd the following line to the \"/etc/sssd/conf.d/certificate_verification.conf\" file:\n\ncertificate_verification = ocsp_dgst=sha512\n\nSet the correct ownership and permissions on the \"/etc/sssd/conf.d/certificate_verification.conf\" file by running these commands:\n\n$ sudo chown root:root \"/etc/sssd/conf.d/certificate_verification.conf\"\n$ sudo chmod 600 \"/etc/sssd/conf.d/certificate_verification.conf\"\n\nThe \"sssd\" service must be restarted for the changes to take effect. To restart the \"sssd\" service, run the following command:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart sssd.service","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 implements Online Certificate Status Protocol (OCSP) and is using the proper digest value on the system with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep certificate_verification /etc/sssd/sssd.conf /etc/sssd/conf.d/*.conf | grep -v \"^#\"\ncertificate_verification = ocsp_dgst=sha512\n\nIf the certificate_verification line is missing from the [sssd] section, or is missing \"ocsp_dgst=sha512\", ask the administrator to indicate what type of multifactor authentication is being used and how the system implements certificate status checking. If there is no evidence of certificate status checking being used, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Using an authentication device, such as a DOD Common Access Card (CAC) or token that is separate from the information system, ensures that even if the information system is compromised, credentials stored on the authentication device will not be affected.\n\nMultifactor solutions that require devices separate from information systems gaining access include, for example, hardware tokens providing time-based or challenge-response authenticators and smart cards such as the U.S. Government Personal Identity Verification (PIV) card and the DOD CAC.\n\nOL 9 includes multiple options for configuring certificate status checking, but for this requirement focuses on the System Security Services Daemon (SSSD). By default, SSSD performs Online Certificate Status Protocol (OCSP) checking and certificate verification using a sha256 digest function.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000375-GPOS-00160, SRG-OS-000377-GPOS-00162","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004046","CCI-001954"],"reference_identifier":"3942","uuid":"54effb8b-81c8-49fc-8f02-806e2603b0a3","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: CD27948E23A33EF37FB273DFD1172444D83C98CC\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must implement certificate status checking for multifactor authentication (MFA).' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271609","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271609","title":"SRG-OS-000383-GPOS-00166","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271609","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000383-GPOS-00166","rule_id_src":"SV-271609r1091539_rule","rule_id":"SV-271609","rule_version":"OL09-00-000935","rule_title":"OL 9 must prohibit the use of cached authenticators after one day.","fix_text":"Configure the SSSD to prohibit the use of cached authentications after one day.\n\nAdd or change the following line in \"/etc/sssd/sssd.conf\" just below the line [pam]:\n\noffline_credentials_expiration = 1","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Note: If smart card authentication is not being used on the system, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nVerify that OL 9's System Security Services Daemon (SSSD) prohibits the use of cached authentications after one day.\n\nCheck that SSSD allows cached authentications with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep cache_credentials /etc/sssd/sssd.conf\ncache_credentials = true\n\nIf \"cache_credentials\" is set to \"false\" or missing from the configuration file, this is not a finding and no further checks are required.\n\nIf \"cache_credentials\" is set to \"true\", check that SSSD prohibits the use of cached authentications after one day with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep offline_credentials_expiration  /etc/sssd/sssd.conf\noffline_credentials_expiration = 1\n\nIf \"offline_credentials_expiration\" is not set to a value of \"1\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If cached authentication information is out-of-date, the validity of the authentication information may be questionable.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002007"],"reference_identifier":"4982","uuid":"fc838810-bf73-47a0-be9e-0907e22bdf54","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: EAA7FBE35F06E9713BE921CF133CCF98A1E33C12\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must prohibit the use of cached authenticators after one day.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271610","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271610","title":"SRG-OS-000104-GPOS-00051","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271610","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000104-GPOS-00051","rule_id_src":"SV-271610r1091542_rule","rule_id":"SV-271610","rule_version":"OL09-00-000940","rule_title":"OL 9 must use the CAC smart card driver.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to load the CAC driver.\n\nAdd or modify the following line in the \"/etc/opensc.conf\" file:\n\ncard_drivers = cac;","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 loads the CAC driver with the following command:\n\n$ grep card_drivers /etc/opensc.conf\ncard_drivers = cac; \n\nIf \"cac\" is not listed as a card driver, or there is no line returned for \"card_drivers\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Smart card login provides two-factor authentication stronger than that provided by a username and password combination. Smart cards leverage public key infrastructure to provide and verify credentials. Configuring the smart card driver in use by the organization helps to prevent users from using unauthorized smart cards.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000104-GPOS-00051, SRG-OS-000106-GPOS-00053, SRG-OS-000107-GPOS-00054, SRG-OS-000109-GPOS-00056, SRG-OS-000108-GPOS-00055, SRG-OS-000112-GPOS-00057, SRG-OS-000113-GPOS-00058","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000764","CCI-000766","CCI-000765","CCI-004045","CCI-001941"],"reference_identifier":"1630","uuid":"05e5b0af-658e-4a95-aa54-cf1783ef42bb","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 0FB04EC4B135D3AA154FEE73BA3BC3B4527D2D98\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must use the CAC smart card driver.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271611","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271611","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271611","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271611r1091545_rule","rule_id":"SV-271611","rule_version":"OL09-00-001000","rule_title":"OL 9 must ensure the password complexity module is enabled in the system-auth file.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to use \"pwquality\" to enforce password complexity rules.\n\nAdd the following line to the \"/etc/pam.d/system-auth\" file(or modify the line to have the required value):\n\npassword required pam_pwquality.so","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 uses \"pwquality\" to enforce the password complexity rules in the system-auth file with the following command:\n\n$ cat /etc/pam.d/system-auth | grep pam_pwquality\npassword required pam_pwquality.so \n\nIf the command does not return a line containing the value \"pam_pwquality.so\", or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Enabling PAM password complexity permits enforcement of strong passwords and consequently makes the system less prone to dictionary attacks.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"4291","uuid":"168fe504-95b9-401d-a5c1-f5afb459071e","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 74193FE6A7DE6F2E395633E88FDEFB91D76A314F\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must ensure the password complexity module is enabled in the system-auth file.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271612","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271612","title":"SRG-OS-000069-GPOS-00037","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271612","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000069-GPOS-00037","rule_id_src":"SV-271612r1091548_rule","rule_id":"SV-271612","rule_version":"OL09-00-001001","rule_title":"OL 9 must ensure the password complexity module in the system-auth file is configured for three retries or less.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to limit the \"pwquality\" retry option to \"3\".\n\nAdd the following line to the \"/etc/pam.d/system-auth\" file (or modify the line to have the required value):\n\npassword required pam_pwquality.so retry=3","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured to limit the \"pwquality\" retry option to \"3\". \n\nCheck for the use of the \"pwquality\" retry option in the system-auth file with the following command:\n\n$ grep pam_pwquality /etc/pam.d/system-auth \npassword required pam_pwquality.so retry=3\n\nIf the value of \"retry\" is set to \"0\" or greater than \"3\", or is missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks. \"pwquality\" enforces complex password construction configuration and has the ability to limit brute-force attacks on the system.\n\nOL 9 uses \"pwquality\" as a mechanism to enforce password complexity. This is set in both:\n/etc/pam.d/password-auth\n/etc/pam.d/system-auth\n\nBy limiting the number of attempts to meet the pwquality module complexity requirements before returning with an error, the system will audit abnormal attempts at password changes.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004066"],"reference_identifier":"6064","uuid":"a3064013-7831-49d3-a063-1e6eee7517aa","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 1B9EFCA05B01AE521D7CD189E0E796EE5838B4CD\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must ensure the password complexity module in the system-auth file is configured for three retries or less.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271613","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271613","title":"SRG-OS-000069-GPOS-00037","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271613","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000069-GPOS-00037","rule_id_src":"SV-271613r1091551_rule","rule_id":"SV-271613","rule_version":"OL09-00-001005","rule_title":"OL 9 must enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one uppercase character be used.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one uppercase character is used by setting the \"ucredit\" option.\n\nAdd the following line to /etc/security/pwquality.conf (or modify the line to have the required value):\n\nucredit = -1","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 enforces password complexity by requiring at least one uppercase character.\n\nCheck the value for \"ucredit\" with the following command:\n\n$ grep ucredit /etc/security/pwquality.conf /etc/security/pwquality.conf.d/*.conf \nucredit = -1 \n\nIf the value of \"ucredit\" is a positive number or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks. Password complexity is one factor of several that determines how long it takes to crack a password. The more complex the password, the greater the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised. Requiring a minimum number of uppercase characters makes password guessing attacks more difficult by ensuring a larger search space.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004066"],"reference_identifier":"8493","uuid":"e902020b-d578-4caa-aac6-2e19b4d91a6f","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 790C37C7ED1438AB4D2699B3E55C8A4EA644366D\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one uppercase character be used.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271614","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271614","title":"SRG-OS-000069-GPOS-00037","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271614","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000069-GPOS-00037","rule_id_src":"SV-271614r1091554_rule","rule_id":"SV-271614","rule_version":"OL09-00-001010","rule_title":"OL 9 must ensure the password complexity module is enabled in the password-auth file.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to use \"pwquality\" to enforce password complexity rules.\n\nAdd the following line to the \"/etc/pam.d/password-auth\" file (or modify the line to have the required value):\n\npassword required pam_pwquality.so","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 uses \"pwquality\" to enforce the password complexity rules in the password-auth file with the following command:\n\n$  grep pam_pwquality /etc/pam.d/password-auth | grep pam_pwquality\npassword required pam_pwquality.so \n\nIf the command does not return a line containing the value \"pam_pwquality.so\", or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Enabling PAM password complexity permits enforcement of strong passwords and consequently makes the system less prone to dictionary attacks.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000069-GPOS-00037, SRG-OS-000070-GPOS-00038","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004066"],"reference_identifier":"1705","uuid":"641ebc48-ddf8-4973-a90c-8b75d88d9cb0","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: A1354806B2F71494BC90401936228ECC89E04320\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must ensure the password complexity module is enabled in the password-auth file.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271615","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271615","title":"SRG-OS-000070-GPOS-00038","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271615","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000070-GPOS-00038","rule_id_src":"SV-271615r1091557_rule","rule_id":"SV-271615","rule_version":"OL09-00-001015","rule_title":"OL 9 must enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one lowercase character be used.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to enforce password complexity by requiring at least one lowercase character is used by setting the \"lcredit\" option.\n\nAdd the following line to \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" (or modify the line to have the required value):\n\nlcredit = -1","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 enforces password complexity by requiring at least one lowercase character.\n\nCheck the value for \"lcredit\" with the following command:\n\n$ grep lcredit /etc/security/pwquality.conf /etc/security/pwquality.conf.d/*.conf \n/etc/security/pwquality.conf:lcredit = -1 \n\nIf the value of \"lcredit\" is a positive number or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks. \n\nPassword complexity is one factor of several that determines how long it takes to crack a password. The more complex the password, the greater the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised. Requiring a minimum number of lowercase characters makes password guessing attacks more difficult by ensuring a larger search space.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004066"],"reference_identifier":"7072","uuid":"d21ec0c9-671b-42b8-9ce7-17aa616db524","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: B59D2569D0F4DDA929967326773567E261A6675D\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'OL 9 must enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one lowercase character be used.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271616","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271616","title":"SRG-OS-000071-GPOS-00039","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271616","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000071-GPOS-00039","rule_id_src":"SV-271616r1091560_rule","rule_id":"SV-271616","rule_version":"OL09-00-001020","rule_title":"OL 9 must enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one numeric character be used.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to enforce password complexity by requiring at least one numeric character is used by setting the \"dcredit\" option.\n\nAdd the following line to \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" (or modify the line to have the required value):\n\ndcredit = -1","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 enforces password complexity by requiring at least one numeric character.\n\nCheck the value for \"dcredit\" with the following command:\n\n$ grep dcredit /etc/security/pwquality.conf /etc/security/pwquality.conf.d/*.conf\n/etc/security/pwquality.conf:dcredit = -1 \n\nIf the value of \"dcredit\" is a positive number or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks.\n\nPassword complexity is one factor of several that determines how long it takes to crack a password. The more complex the password, the greater the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised. Requiring digits makes password guessing attacks more difficult by ensuring a larger search space.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004066"],"reference_identifier":"7272","uuid":"1c461a62-80c4-4be1-a7f1-26382c920210","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: AC5FBC0B9145C0B96ADE719AFC0BA2BB07334850\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one numeric character be used.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271617","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271617","title":"SRG-OS-000072-GPOS-00040","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271617","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000072-GPOS-00040","rule_id_src":"SV-271617r1091563_rule","rule_id":"SV-271617","rule_version":"OL09-00-001025","rule_title":"OL 9 must require the change of at least eight characters when passwords are changed.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to require the change of at least eight of the total number of characters when passwords are changed by setting the \"difok\" option.\n\nAdd the following line to \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" (or modify the line to have the required value):\n\ndifok = 8","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 requires the change of at least eight characters when passwords are changed.\n\nVerify the value of the \"difok\" option in \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" with the following command:\n\n$ grep difok /etc/security/pwquality.conf /etc/security/pwquality.conf.d/*.conf \ndifok = 8\n \nIf the value of \"difok\" is set to less than \"8\", or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks. \n\nPassword complexity is one factor of several that determines how long it takes to crack a password. The more complex the password, the greater the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised. Requiring a minimum number of different characters during password changes ensures that newly changed passwords will not resemble previously compromised ones. Note that passwords changed on compromised systems will still be compromised.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004066"],"reference_identifier":"8787","uuid":"8a457e0b-848d-43f6-818d-764d4e9204ad","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: FF3E35B7C3F7E2F16A7B23627424DBDC16AF28F5\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'OL 9 must require the change of at least eight characters when passwords are changed.' is not present or not in use on this the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271618","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271618","title":"SRG-OS-000072-GPOS-00040","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271618","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000072-GPOS-00040","rule_id_src":"SV-271618r1091566_rule","rule_id":"SV-271618","rule_version":"OL09-00-001030","rule_title":"OL 9 must require the maximum number of repeating characters of the same character class be limited to four when passwords are changed.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to require the change of the number of repeating characters of the same character class when passwords are changed by setting the \"maxclassrepeat\" option.\n\nAdd the following line to \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" conf (or modify the line to have the required value):\n\nmaxclassrepeat = 4","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 requires the maximum number of repeating characters of the same character class be limited to four when passwords are changed.\n\nVerify the value of the \"maxclassrepeat\" option in \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" with the following command:\n\n$ grep maxclassrepeat /etc/security/pwquality.conf /etc/security/pwquality.conf.d/*.conf \nmaxclassrepeat = 4\n\nIf the value of \"maxclassrepeat\" is set to \"0\", more than \"4\", or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks.\n\nPassword complexity is one factor of several that determines how long it takes to crack a password. The more complex a password, the greater the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004066"],"reference_identifier":"5605","uuid":"71557fed-a751-4646-95aa-0d0fe76961bf","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 81E3C0EF6E914325F5E988ECCDD579328166EEE2\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must require the maximum number of repeating characters of the same character class be limited to four when passwords are changed.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271619","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271619","title":"SRG-OS-000072-GPOS-00040","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271619","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000072-GPOS-00040","rule_id_src":"SV-271619r1091569_rule","rule_id":"SV-271619","rule_version":"OL09-00-001035","rule_title":"OL 9 must require the maximum number of repeating characters be limited to three when passwords are changed.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to require the change of the number of repeating consecutive characters when passwords are changed by setting the \"maxrepeat\" option.\n\nAdd the following line to \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" (or modify the line to have the required value):\n\nmaxrepeat = 3","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 requires the maximum number of repeating characters be limited to three when passwords are changed.\n\nVerify the value of the \"maxrepeat\" option in \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" with the following command:\n\n$ grep maxrepeat /etc/security/pwquality.conf /etc/security/pwquality.conf.d/*.conf \nmaxrepeat = 3\n\nIf the value of \"maxrepeat\" is set to more than \"3\", or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks.\n\nPassword complexity is one factor of several that determines how long it takes to crack a password. The more complex a password, the greater the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004066"],"reference_identifier":"8972","uuid":"7c877cae-7c72-4b98-93dd-ca4f5867ff4d","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 9B4C8184658B546816F87EBAFB0FCEE58D8A185F\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must require the maximum number of repeating characters be limited to three when passwords are changed.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271620","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271620","title":"SRG-OS-000072-GPOS-00040","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271620","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000072-GPOS-00040","rule_id_src":"SV-271620r1091572_rule","rule_id":"SV-271620","rule_version":"OL09-00-001040","rule_title":"OL 9 must require the change of at least four character classes when passwords are changed.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to require the change of at least four character classes when passwords are changed by setting the \"minclass\" option.\n\nAdd the following line to \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" (or modify the line to have the required value):\n\nminclass = 4","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 requires the change of at least four character classes when passwords are changed.\n\nVerify the value of the \"minclass\" option in \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" with the following command:\n\n$ grep minclass /etc/security/pwquality.conf /etc/security/pwquality.conf.d/*.conf \nminclass = 4\n\nIf the value of \"minclass\" is set to less than \"4\", or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks.\n\nPassword complexity is one factor of several that determines how long it takes to crack a password. The more complex a password, the greater the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004066"],"reference_identifier":"5483","uuid":"70ae29b3-e180-4da0-8b91-bd3d3e963c54","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 446D1B55692CE7BAEDF185316AD9CBE093272A44\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must require the change of at least four character classes when passwords are changed.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271621","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271621","title":"SRG-OS-000072-GPOS-00040","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271621","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000072-GPOS-00040","rule_id_src":"SV-271621r1091575_rule","rule_id":"SV-271621","rule_version":"OL09-00-001045","rule_title":"OL 9 must enforce password complexity rules for the root account.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to enforce password complexity on the root account.\n\nAdd or update the following line in /etc/security/pwquality.conf:\n\nenforce_for_root","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 enforces password complexity rules for the root account.\n\nCheck if root user is required to use complex passwords with the following command:\n\n$ grep enforce_for_root /etc/security/pwquality.conf /etc/security/pwquality.conf.d/*.conf\n/etc/security/pwquality.conf:enforce_for_root\n\nIf \"enforce_for_root\" is commented or missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks.\n\nPassword complexity is one factor of several that determines how long it takes to crack a password. The more complex the password, the greater the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000072-GPOS-00040, SRG-OS-000071-GPOS-00039, SRG-OS-000070-GPOS-00038, SRG-OS-000266-GPOS-00101, SRG-OS-000078-GPOS-00046, SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00225, SRG-OS-000069-GPOS-00037","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004066"],"reference_identifier":"5649","uuid":"a0ac8646-9808-4a58-b639-9c10d91fd31f","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 4E6D5805507FC210DFF4BD00757B28745A29D3DB\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must enforce password complexity rules for the root account.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271622","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271622","title":"SRG-OS-000073-GPOS-00041","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271622","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000073-GPOS-00041","rule_id_src":"SV-271622r1091578_rule","rule_id":"SV-271622","rule_version":"OL09-00-001050","rule_title":"OL 9 must be configured so that user and group account administration utilities are configured to store only encrypted representations of passwords.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to use the SHA-512 algorithm for password hashing.\n\nAdd or change the following line in the \"[default]\" section of \"/etc/libuser.conf\" file:\n\ncrypt_style = sha512","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 user and group account administration utilities are configured to store only encrypted representations of passwords with the following command:\n\n# grep crypt /etc/libuser.conf \ncrypt_style = sha512\n\nIf the \"crypt_style\" variable is not set to \"sha512\", is not in the defaults section, is commented out, or does not exist, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Passwords need to be protected at all times, and encryption is the standard method for protecting passwords. If passwords are not encrypted, they can be plainly read (i.e., clear text) and easily compromised. Passwords that are encrypted with a weak algorithm are no more protected than if they are kept in plain text.\n\nThis setting ensures user and group account administration utilities are configured to store only encrypted representations of passwords. Additionally, the \"crypt_style\" configuration option ensures the use of a strong hashing algorithm that makes password cracking attacks more difficult.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004062"],"reference_identifier":"5031","uuid":"102eb56c-cbd8-4d42-a31a-f071ce3f8f08","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: A14224D335C3677719749B448AD42A9ABF37A6A4\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'OL 9 must be configured so that user and group account administration utilities are configured to store only encrypted representations of passwords.' is not present or not in use on this the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271623","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271623","title":"SRG-OS-000073-GPOS-00041","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271623","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000073-GPOS-00041","rule_id_src":"SV-271623r1091581_rule","rule_id":"SV-271623","rule_version":"OL09-00-001055","rule_title":"OL 9 must be configured to use the shadow file to store only encrypted representations of passwords.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to store only SHA-512 encrypted representations of passwords.\n\nAdd or update the following line in the \"/etc/login.defs\" file:\n\nENCRYPT_METHOD SHA512","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 shadow file is configured to store only encrypted representations of passwords with a hash value of \"SHA512\" with the following command:\n\n# grep -i encrypt_method /etc/login.defs\nENCRYPT_METHOD SHA512\n\nIf \"ENCRYPT_METHOD\" does not have a value of \"SHA512\", or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Passwords need to be protected at all times, and encryption is the standard method for protecting passwords. If passwords are not encrypted, they can be plainly read (i.e., clear text) and easily compromised. Passwords that are encrypted with a weak algorithm are no more protected than if they are kept in plain text.\n\nThis setting ensures user and group account administration utilities are configured to store only encrypted representations of passwords. Additionally, the \"crypt_style\" configuration option ensures the use of a strong hashing algorithm that makes password cracking attacks more difficult.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004062"],"reference_identifier":"4775","uuid":"893739ca-bba1-4ce6-a480-6655e3de4cfd","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: DDA757704E2B42076B2E0243E4416570598565A4\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must be configured to use the shadow file to store only encrypted representations of passwords.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271624","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271624","title":"SRG-OS-000073-GPOS-00041","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271624","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000073-GPOS-00041","rule_id_src":"SV-271624r1091584_rule","rule_id":"SV-271624","rule_version":"OL09-00-001060","rule_title":"OL 9 pam_unix.so module must be configured in the password-auth file to use a FIPS 140-3 approved cryptographic hashing algorithm for system authentication.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to use a FIPS 140-3 approved cryptographic hashing algorithm for system authentication.\n\nEdit/modify the following line in the \"/etc/pam.d/password-auth\" file to include the sha512 option for pam_unix.so:\n\npassword sufficient pam_unix.so sha512","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 pam_unix.so module is configured to use sha512 in /etc/pam.d/password-auth with the following command:\n\n$ grep \"^password.*pam_unix.so.*sha512\" /etc/pam.d/password-auth\npassword sufficient pam_unix.so sha512\n\nIf \"sha512\" is missing, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Unapproved mechanisms that are used for authentication to the cryptographic module are not verified and therefore, cannot be relied upon to provide confidentiality or integrity, and DOD data may be compromised.\n\nOL 9 systems using encryption are required to use FIPS-compliant mechanisms for authenticating to cryptographic modules. \n\nFIPS 140-3 is the current standard for validating that mechanisms used to access cryptographic modules use authentication that meets DOD requirements. This allows for Security Levels 1, 2, 3, or 4 for use on a general-purpose computing system.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004062"],"reference_identifier":"3451","uuid":"252120ba-a4a5-48a2-9981-a514bb030c12","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 98F42FD0D27405B3E87ED0AA643A6C2C3E04BAC8\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 pam_unix.so module must be configured in the password-auth file to use a FIPS 140-3 approved cryptographic hashing algorithm for system authentication.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271625","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271625","title":"SRG-OS-000073-GPOS-00041","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271625","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000073-GPOS-00041","rule_id_src":"SV-271625r1091587_rule","rule_id":"SV-271625","rule_version":"OL09-00-001065","rule_title":"OL 9 password-auth must be configured to use a sufficient number of hashing rounds.","fix_text":"Configure Oracle Linux 9 to use 100000 hashing rounds for hashing passwords.\n\nAdd or modify the following line in \"/etc/pam.d/password-auth\" and set \"rounds\" to \"100000\".\n\npassword sufficient pam_unix.so sha512 rounds=100000","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 password-auth is configured to use a sufficient number of hashing rounds with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep rounds /etc/pam.d/password-auth\npassword sufficient pam_unix.so sha512 rounds=100000\n\nIf a matching line is not returned or \"rounds\" is less than \"100000\", this a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Passwords need to be protected at all times, and encryption is the standard method for protecting passwords. If passwords are not encrypted, they can be plainly read (i.e., clear text) and easily compromised. Passwords that are encrypted with a weak algorithm are no more protected than if they are kept in plain text.\n\nUsing more hashing rounds makes password cracking attacks more difficult.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000073-GPOS-00041, SRG-OS-000120-GPOS-00061","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004062","CCI-000803"],"reference_identifier":"2736","uuid":"f10a4459-a928-474d-8cef-17081e457487","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 2C3B6A685B4B4E86F32D9AD83CBFB2A2709DDBFC\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 password-auth must be configured to use a sufficient number of hashing rounds.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271626","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271626","title":"SRG-OS-000073-GPOS-00041","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271626","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000073-GPOS-00041","rule_id_src":"SV-271626r1091590_rule","rule_id":"SV-271626","rule_version":"OL09-00-001070","rule_title":"OL 9 system-auth must be configured to use a sufficient number of hashing rounds.","fix_text":"Configure Oracle Linux 9 to use 100000 hashing rounds for hashing passwords.\n\nAdd or modify the following line in \"/etc/pam.d/system-auth\" and set \"rounds\" to 100000.\n\npassword sufficient pam_unix.so sha512 rounds=100000'","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 system-auth is configured to use a sufficient number of hashing rounds with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep rounds /etc/pam.d/system-auth\npassword sufficient pam_unix.so sha512 rounds=100000\n\nIf a matching line is not returned or \"rounds\" is less than 100000, this a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Passwords need to be protected at all times, and encryption is the standard method for protecting passwords. If passwords are not encrypted, they can be plainly read (i.e., clear text) and easily compromised. Passwords that are encrypted with a weak algorithm are no more protected than if they are kept in plain text.\n\nUsing more hashing rounds makes password cracking attacks more difficult.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000073-GPOS-00041, SRG-OS-000120-GPOS-00061","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004062","CCI-000803"],"reference_identifier":"3319","uuid":"6e92ecae-162a-48e9-803b-80c5493cb30e","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 1E400BA533107FE273E9C5B202A44C653FFF69CD\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 system-auth must be configured to use a sufficient number of hashing rounds.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271627","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271627","title":"SRG-OS-000073-GPOS-00041","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271627","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000073-GPOS-00041","rule_id_src":"SV-271627r1091593_rule","rule_id":"SV-271627","rule_version":"OL09-00-001075","rule_title":"OL 9 shadow password suite must be configured to use a sufficient number of hashing rounds.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to encrypt all stored passwords with a strong cryptographic hash.\n\nEdit/modify the following line in the \"/etc/login.defs\" file and set \"SHA_CRYPT_MIN_ROUNDS\" to a value no lower than \"100000\":\n\nSHA_CRYPT_MIN_ROUNDS 100000\nSHA_CRYPT_MAX_ROUNDS 100000","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 has a minimum number of hash rounds configured with the following command:\n\n$ grep -i sha_crypt /etc/login.defs\n\nIf \"SHA_CRYPT_MIN_ROUNDS\" or \"SHA_CRYPT_MAX_ROUNDS\" is less than \"100000\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Passwords need to be protected at all times, and encryption is the standard method for protecting passwords. If passwords are not encrypted, they can be plainly read (i.e., clear text) and easily compromised. Passwords that are encrypted with a weak algorithm are no more protected than if they are kept in plain text.\n\nUsing more hashing rounds makes password cracking attacks more difficult.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000073-GPOS-00041, SRG-OS-000120-GPOS-00061","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004062","CCI-000803"],"reference_identifier":"9012","uuid":"d698b765-0fe2-4e01-92f2-90b2fde09a9b","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 033346B68D4740351BCCECE2C3F972F2446D730B\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 shadow password suite must be configured to use a sufficient number of hashing rounds.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271628","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271628","title":"SRG-OS-000073-GPOS-00041","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271628","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000073-GPOS-00041","rule_id_src":"SV-271628r1091596_rule","rule_id":"SV-271628","rule_version":"OL09-00-001080","rule_title":"OL 9 must employ FIPS 140-3 approved cryptographic hashing algorithms for all stored passwords.","fix_text":"Lock all interactive user accounts not using SHA-512 hashing until the passwords can be regenerated with SHA-512.\n\nTo lock an account:\n\n$ sudo passwd -l [username]","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 interactive user account passwords are using a strong password hash with the following command:\n\n$ sudo cut -d: -f2 /etc/shadow\n$6$kcOnRq/5$NUEYPuyL.wghQwWssXRcLRFiiru7f5JPV6GaJhNC2aK5F3PZpE/BCCtwrxRc/AInKMNX3CdMw11m9STiql12f/ \n\nPassword hashes \"!\" or \"*\" indicate inactive accounts not available for logon and are not evaluated.\n\nIf any interactive user password hash does not begin with \"$6\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The system must use a strong hashing algorithm to store the password.\n\nPasswords need to be protected at all times, and encryption is the standard method for protecting passwords. If passwords are not encrypted, they can be plainly read (i.e., clear text) and easily compromised.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000073-GPOS-00041, SRG-OS-000120-GPOS-00061","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004062","CCI-000803"],"reference_identifier":"9727","uuid":"7b833346-8438-492a-919e-cc9d1aa5d6c0","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: F941181E5E179FF22AD82DF48E70BB9B13F82ED5\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must employ FIPS 140-3 approved cryptographic hashing algorithms for all stored passwords.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271629","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271629","title":"SRG-OS-000075-GPOS-00043","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271629","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000075-GPOS-00043","rule_id_src":"SV-271629r1091599_rule","rule_id":"SV-271629","rule_version":"OL09-00-001085","rule_title":"OL 9 passwords for new users or password changes must have a 24-hour minimum password lifetime restriction in /etc/login.defs.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to enforce 24 hours as the minimum password lifetime.\n\nAdd the following line in \"/etc/login.defs\" (or modify the line to have the required value):\n\nPASS_MIN_DAYS 1","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 enforces a 24-hour minimum password lifetime for new user accounts.\n\nCheck for the value of \"PASS_MIN_DAYS\" in \"/etc/login.defs\" with the following command: \n\n$ grep -i pass_min_days /etc/login.defs\nPASS_MIN_DAYS 1\n\nIf the \"PASS_MIN_DAYS\" parameter value is not \"1\" or greater, or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Enforcing a minimum password lifetime helps to prevent repeated password changes to defeat the password reuse or history enforcement requirement. If users are allowed to immediately and continually change their password, then the password could be repeatedly changed in a short period of time to defeat the organization's policy regarding password reuse.\n\nSetting the minimum password age protects against users cycling back to a favorite password after satisfying the password reuse requirement.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004066"],"reference_identifier":"6089","uuid":"98954313-a707-4437-8b45-bd3edfa06511","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: C980187C52E1091A57C7455638CC3CE1520ED7EB\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'OL 9 passwords for new users or password changes must have a 24-hour minimum password lifetime restriction in /etc/login.defs.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271630","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271630","title":"SRG-OS-000075-GPOS-00043","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271630","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000075-GPOS-00043","rule_id_src":"SV-271630r1091602_rule","rule_id":"SV-271630","rule_version":"OL09-00-001090","rule_title":"OL 9 passwords must have a 24-hour minimum password lifetime restriction in /etc/shadow.","fix_text":"Configure noncompliant accounts to enforce a 24-hour minimum password lifetime:\n\n$ sudo passwd -n 1 [user]","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 has configured the minimum time period between password changes for each user account as 24 hours or greater with the following command:\n\n$ sudo awk -F: '$4 < 1 {print $1 \" \" $4}' /etc/shadow\n\nIf any results are returned that are not associated with a system account, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Enforcing a minimum password lifetime helps to prevent repeated password changes to defeat the password reuse or history enforcement requirement. If users are allowed to immediately and continually change their password, the password could be repeatedly changed in a short period of time to defeat the organization's policy regarding password reuse.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004066"],"reference_identifier":"4070","uuid":"e24c44c9-32dc-4caf-8d49-e5f0b9204e26","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: DF2E54702D1C8AE0E0A534A69F96A0574FD22579\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'OL 9 passwords must have a 24-hour minimum password lifetime restriction in /etc/shadow.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271631","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271631","title":"SRG-OS-000076-GPOS-00044","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271631","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000076-GPOS-00044","rule_id_src":"SV-271631r1091605_rule","rule_id":"SV-271631","rule_version":"OL09-00-001095","rule_title":"OL 9 user account passwords for new users or password changes must have a 60-day maximum password lifetime restriction in /etc/login.defs.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to enforce a 60-day maximum password lifetime.\n\nAdd or modify the following line in the \"/etc/login.defs\" file:\n\nPASS_MAX_DAYS 60","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 enforces a 60-day maximum password lifetime for new user accounts by running the following command:\n\n$ grep -i pass_max_days /etc/login.defs\nPASS_MAX_DAYS 60\n\nIf the \"PASS_MAX_DAYS\" parameter value is greater than \"60\", or commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Any password, no matter how complex, can eventually be cracked; therefore, passwords need to be changed periodically. If the operating system does not limit the lifetime of passwords and force users to change their passwords, there is the risk that the operating system passwords could be compromised.\n\nSetting the password maximum age ensures users are required to periodically change their passwords. Requiring shorter password lifetimes increases the risk of users writing down the password in a convenient location subject to physical compromise.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004066"],"reference_identifier":"8789","uuid":"2a621778-b2f9-4f62-b9b8-067e88872051","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 833939220534E2A3D6C45B5B44830FC612857E4B\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 user account passwords for new users or password changes must have a 60-day maximum password lifetime restriction in /etc/login.defs.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271632","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271632","title":"SRG-OS-000076-GPOS-00044","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271632","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000076-GPOS-00044","rule_id_src":"SV-271632r1091608_rule","rule_id":"SV-271632","rule_version":"OL09-00-001100","rule_title":"OL 9 user account passwords must have a 60-day maximum password lifetime restriction.","fix_text":"Configure noncompliant accounts to enforce a 60-day maximum password lifetime restriction.\n\npasswd -x 60 [user]","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 user account passwords have a 60-day maximum password lifetime restriction with the following commands:\n\n$ sudo awk -F: '$5 > 60 {print $1 \"\" \"\" $5}' /etc/shadow\n\n$ sudo awk -F: '$5 <= 0 {print $1 \"\" \"\" $5}' /etc/shadow\n\nIf any results are returned that are not associated with a system account, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Any password, no matter how complex, can eventually be cracked; therefore, passwords need to be changed periodically. If OL 9 does not limit the lifetime of passwords and force users to change their passwords, there is the risk that OL 9 passwords could be compromised.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004066"],"reference_identifier":"9728","uuid":"50697104-3f79-4da6-b331-42ed1e93d3ba","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 0A0E7B6612CD7DEE14F12F5449D89F3555D80C89\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'OL 9 user account passwords must have a 60-day maximum password lifetime restriction.' is not present or not in use on this the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271633","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271633","title":"SRG-OS-000078-GPOS-00046","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271633","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000078-GPOS-00046","rule_id_src":"SV-271633r1091611_rule","rule_id":"SV-271633","rule_version":"OL09-00-001105","rule_title":"OL 9 passwords must be created with a minimum of 15 characters.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to enforce a minimum 15-character password length.\n\nAdd the following line to \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" (or modify the line to have the required value):\n\nminlen = 15","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 enforces a minimum 15-character password length with the following command:\n\n$ grep minlen /etc/security/pwquality.conf /etc/security/pwquality.conf.d/*.conf \nminlen = 15\n\nIf the command does not return a \"minlen\" value of \"15\" or greater, does not return a line, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The shorter the password, the lower the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised.\n\nPassword complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks. Password length is one factor of several that helps to determine strength and how long it takes to crack a password. Use of more characters in a password helps to increase exponentially the time and/or resources required to compromise the password.\n\nOL 9 uses \"pwquality\" as a mechanism to enforce password complexity. Configurations are set in the \"etc/security/pwquality.conf\" file.\n\nThe \"minlen\", sometimes noted as minimum length, acts as a \"score\" of complexity based on the credit components of the \"pwquality\" module. By setting the credit components to a negative value, not only will those components be required, but they will not count toward the total \"score\" of \"minlen\". This will enable \"minlen\" to require a 15-character minimum.\n\nThe DOD minimum password requirement is 15 characters.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004066"],"reference_identifier":"5110","uuid":"a0787d11-46f7-403b-a684-4185693e1e83","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: BE4B950C2A7C113D55D7A224961184214BEADA49\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 passwords must be created with a minimum of 15 characters.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271634","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271634","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271634","severity":"high","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271634r1091614_rule","rule_id":"SV-271634","rule_version":"OL09-00-001110","rule_title":"OL 9 must not allow blank or null passwords.","fix_text":"Remove any instances of the \"nullok\" option in the \"/etc/pam.d/password-auth\" and \"/etc/pam.d/system-auth\" files to prevent logons with empty passwords.\n\nNote: Manual changes to the listed file may be overwritten by the \"authselect\" program.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 does not allow null passwords with the following command:\n\n$ grep -i nullok /etc/pam.d/system-auth /etc/pam.d/password-auth\n\nIf output is produced, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If an account has an empty password, anyone could log in and run commands with the privileges of that account. Accounts with empty passwords should never be used in operational environments.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"8382","uuid":"e99d0fee-28c9-4873-b640-25b9b0cc3245","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: DFCC93CBE1B26327E4C4A303334EB17819057816\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must not allow blank or null passwords.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271635","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271635","title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271635","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","rule_id_src":"SV-271635r1137691_rule","rule_id":"SV-271635","rule_version":"OL09-00-001115","rule_title":"OL 9 must require a boot loader superuser password.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to require a grub bootloader password for the grub superuser account.\n\nGenerate an encrypted grub2 password for the grub superuser account with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grub2-setpassword\nEnter password:\nConfirm password:","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 requires a boot loader superuser password with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep \"superusers\" /etc/grub2.cfg \npassword_pbkdf2  superusers-account   ${GRUB2_PASSWORD}  \n\nTo verify the boot loader superuser account password has been set, and the password encrypted, run the following command:\n\n$ sudo cat /boot/grub2/user.cfg \nGRUB2_PASSWORD=grub.pbkdf2.sha512.10000.C4E08AC72FBFF7E837FD267BFAD7AEB3D42DDC\n2C99F2A94DD5E2E75C2DC331B719FE55D9411745F82D1B6CFD9E927D61925F9BBDD1CFAA0080E0\n916F7AB46E0D.1302284FCCC52CD73BA3671C6C12C26FF50BA873293B24EE2A96EE3B57963E6D7\n0C83964B473EC8F93B07FE749AA6710269E904A9B08A6BBACB00A2D242AD828 \n\nIf a \"GRUB2_PASSWORD\" is not set, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"To mitigate the risk of unauthorized access to sensitive information by entities that have been issued certificates by DOD-approved PKIs, all DOD systems (e.g., web servers and web portals) must be properly configured to incorporate access control methods that do not rely solely on the possession of a certificate for access. Successful authentication must not automatically give an entity access to an asset or security boundary. Authorization procedures and controls must be implemented to ensure each authenticated entity also has a validated and current authorization. Authorization is the process of determining whether an entity, once authenticated, is permitted to access a specific asset. Information systems use access control policies and enforcement mechanisms to implement this requirement.\n\nPassword protection on the boot loader configuration ensures users with physical access cannot trivially alter important bootloader settings. These include which kernel to use, and whether to enter single-user mode.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000213"],"reference_identifier":"2861","uuid":"d39d6a8e-f09f-42b4-83c0-466b55e9a4ce","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 75D65A967E6B6199531AF0491B232C8ECAE49B2A\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'OL 9 must require a boot loader superuser password.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271636","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271636","title":"SRG-OS-000266-GPOS-00101","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271636","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000266-GPOS-00101","rule_id_src":"SV-271636r1091620_rule","rule_id":"SV-271636","rule_version":"OL09-00-001120","rule_title":"OL 9 must enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one special character be used.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to enforce password complexity by requiring at least one special character be used by setting the \"ocredit\" option.\n\nAdd the following line to \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" (or modify the line to have the required value):\n\nocredit = -1","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 enforces password complexity by requiring at least one special character with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep ocredit /etc/security/pwquality.conf /etc/security/pwquality.conf.d/*.conf \nocredit = -1 \n\nIf the value of \"ocredit\" is a positive number or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks. Password complexity is one factor of several that determines how long it takes to crack a password. The more complex the password, the greater the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised. OL 9 uses \"pwquality\" as a mechanism to enforce password complexity. Note that to require special characters without degrading the \"minlen\" value, the credit value must be expressed as a negative number in \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\".","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004066"],"reference_identifier":"4473","uuid":"7dcbb9fb-ff6e-43f0-ac83-277d57572344","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 6DB677753816023034C3C2A4A0060AA649C44700\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'OL 9 must enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one special character be used.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271637","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271637","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00225","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271637","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00225","rule_id_src":"SV-271637r1091623_rule","rule_id":"SV-271637","rule_version":"OL09-00-001125","rule_title":"OL 9 must prevent the use of dictionary words for passwords.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to prevent the use of dictionary words for passwords.\n\nAdd or update the following line in the \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" file or a configuration file in the /etc/pwquality.conf.d/ directory to contain the \"dictcheck\" parameter:\n\ndictcheck=1","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 prevents the use of dictionary words for passwords with the following command:\n\n$ grep dictcheck /etc/security/pwquality.conf /etc/pwquality.conf.d/*.conf \n/etc/security/pwquality.conf:dictcheck=1 \n\nIf \"dictcheck\" does not have a value other than \"0\", or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks. If OL 9 allows the user to select passwords based on dictionary words, this increases the chances of password compromise by increasing the opportunity for successful guesses, and brute-force attacks.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"8959","uuid":"2df3847d-3885-4f8d-a2bb-fec8f1c3c0e5","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-271638","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271638","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271638","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271638r1091626_rule","rule_id":"SV-271638","rule_version":"OL09-00-001130","rule_title":"OL 9 must not have accounts configured with blank or null passwords.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 so that all accounts have a password or lock the account with the following commands:\n\nPerform a password reset:\n\n$ sudo passwd [username] \n\nTo lock an account:\n\n$ sudo passwd -l [username]","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 does not have accounts configured with blank or null passwords with the following command:\n\n$ sudo awk -F: '!$2 {print $1}' /etc/shadow\n\nIf the command returns any results, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If an account has an empty password, anyone could log in and run commands with the privileges of that account. Accounts with empty passwords should never be used in operational environments.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"9614","uuid":"05c6645b-6534-4200-8b08-08b127ad547f","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-271639","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271639","title":"SRG-OS-000114-GPOS-00059","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271639","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000114-GPOS-00059","rule_id_src":"SV-271639r1091629_rule","rule_id":"SV-271639","rule_version":"OL09-00-002000","rule_title":"OL 9 file system automount function must be disabled unless required.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to disable and mask the ability to automount devices.\n\nThe autofs service can be disabled and masked with the following command:\n\n$ sudo systemctl mask --now autofs.service","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 file system automount function has been disabled and masked with the following command:\n\n$ systemctl is-enabled  autofs\nmasked\n\nIf the returned value is not \"masked\" and is not documented as operational requirement with the information system security officer (ISSO), this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"An authentication process resists replay attacks if it is impractical to achieve a successful authentication by recording and replaying a previous authentication message.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000114-GPOS-00059, SRG-OS-000378-GPOS-00163","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000778","CCI-001958"],"reference_identifier":"3892","uuid":"050cb67c-bc6b-4159-ab8e-7c18d1547da2","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 83AF6407156B47EF0DBC37658D1248B1B15B18CF\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 file system automount function must be disabled unless required.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271641","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271641","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271641","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271641r1091635_rule","rule_id":"SV-271641","rule_version":"OL09-00-002011","rule_title":"OL 9 must prevent special devices on file systems that are imported via Network File System (NFS).","fix_text":"Update each NFS mounted file system to use the \"nodev\" option on file systems that are being imported via NFS.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If no NFS mounts are configured, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nVerify that OL 9 has the \"nodev\" option configured for all NFS mounts with the following command:\n\n$ cat /etc/fstab | grep nfs\n192.168.22.2:/mnt/export /data nfs4 rw,nosuid,nodev,noexec,sync,soft,sec=krb5:krb5i:krb5p\n\nIf the system is mounting file systems via NFS and the \"nodev\" option is missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The \"nodev\" mount option causes the system to not interpret character or block special devices. Executing character or block special devices from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for nonprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"6072","uuid":"087a4fe8-c6d6-4f79-a9da-05e07119d84d","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: DB0183A3C5A622D277EC7ABCAC19040604200E22\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must prevent special devices on file systems that are imported via Network File System (NFS).' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271642","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271642","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271642","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271642r1092593_rule","rule_id":"SV-271642","rule_version":"OL09-00-002012","rule_title":"OL 9 must prevent code from being executed on file systems that are imported via Network File System (NFS).","fix_text":"Update each NFS mounted file system to use the \"noexec\" option on file systems that are being imported via NFS.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If no NFS mounts are configured, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nVerify that OL 9 has the \"noexec\" option configured for all NFS mounts with the following command:\n\n$ cat /etc/fstab | grep nfs\n192.168.22.2:/mnt/export /data nfs4 rw,nosuid,nodev,noexec,sync,soft,sec=krb5:krb5i:krb5p\n\nIf the system is mounting file systems via NFS and the \"noexec\" option is missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The \"noexec\" mount option causes the system not to execute binary files. This option must be used for mounting any file system not containing approved binary as they may be incompatible. Executing files from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for nonprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"5722","uuid":"476a957f-84e4-462c-b3b3-f95f411c9218","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: F83FD565E5B67C58405C44816AD063F9A1CFA4FF\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'OL 9 must prevent code from being executed on file systems that are imported via Network File System (NFS).' is not present or not in use on this the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271643","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271643","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271643","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271643r1091641_rule","rule_id":"SV-271643","rule_version":"OL09-00-002013","rule_title":"OL 9 must prevent files with the setuid and setgid bit set from being executed on file systems that are imported via Network File System (NFS).","fix_text":"Update each NFS mounted file system to use the \"nosuid\" option on file systems that are being imported via NFS.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If no NFS mounts are configured, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nVerify that OL 9 has the \"nosuid\" option configured for all NFS mounts with the following command:\n\n$ cat /etc/fstab | grep nfs\n192.168.22.2:/mnt/export /data nfs4 rw,nosuid,nodev,noexec,sync,soft,sec=krb5:krb5i:krb5p\n\nIf the system is mounting file systems via NFS and the \"nosuid\" option is missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The \"nosuid\" mount option causes the system not to execute \"setuid\" and \"setgid\" files with owner privileges. This option must be used for mounting any file system not containing approved \"setuid\" and \"setguid\" files. Executing files from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for nonprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2587","uuid":"2a46f18f-5158-405a-afd6-dc39dcd73f74","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: F2750A2BB9FBF3018249176944D05AA7CE09A703\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must prevent files with the setuid and setgid bit set from being executed on file systems that are imported via Network File System (NFS).' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271644","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271644","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271644","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271644r1091644_rule","rule_id":"SV-271644","rule_version":"OL09-00-002020","rule_title":"OL 9 must prevent code from being executed on file systems that are used with removable media.","fix_text":"Configure the \"/etc/fstab\" to use the \"noexec\" option on file systems that are associated with removable media.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 file systems that are used for removable media are mounted with the \"noexec\" option with the following command:\n\n$ more /etc/fstab\nUUID=2bc871e4-e2a3-4f29-9ece-3be60c835222 /mnt/usbflash vfat noauto,owner,ro,nosuid,nodev,noexec 0 0\n\nIf a file system found in \"/etc/fstab\" refers to removable media and it does not have the \"noexec\" option set, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The \"noexec\" mount option causes the system not to execute binary files. This option must be used for mounting any file system not containing approved binary files, as they may be incompatible. Executing files from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for nonprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"3626","uuid":"67d2a3ab-bee2-4147-990f-3fefc7d86f4c","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 6B6107DB583316D28DD134F4101BD1DD4E1D9374\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must prevent code from being executed on file systems that are used with removable media.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271645","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271645","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271645","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271645r1091647_rule","rule_id":"SV-271645","rule_version":"OL09-00-002021","rule_title":"OL 9 must prevent special devices on file systems that are used with removable media.","fix_text":"Configure the \"/etc/fstab\" to use the \"nodev\" option on file systems that are associated with removable media.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 file systems that are used for removable media are mounted with the \"nodev\" option with the following command:\n\n$ more /etc/fstab\nUUID=2bc871e4-e2a3-4f29-9ece-3be60c835222 /mnt/usbflash vfat noauto,owner,ro,nosuid,nodev,noexec 0 0\n\nIf a file system found in \"/etc/fstab\" refers to removable media and it does not have the \"nodev\" option set, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The \"nodev\" mount option causes the system not to interpret character or block special devices. Executing character or blocking special devices from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for nonprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"7185","uuid":"af7893a5-2ec4-4da4-9b75-3529aa276018","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: F2E9EB3BACF2280839C1B178100DB8AD2F9759D7\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must prevent special devices on file systems that are used with removable media.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271646","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271646","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271646","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271646r1091650_rule","rule_id":"SV-271646","rule_version":"OL09-00-002022","rule_title":"OL 9 must prevent files with the setuid and setgid bit set from being executed on file systems that are used with removable media.","fix_text":"Configure the \"/etc/fstab\" to use the \"nosuid\" option on file systems that are associated with removable media.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 file systems that are used for removable media are mounted with the \"nosuid\" option with the following command:\n\n$ more /etc/fstab\nUUID=2bc871e4-e2a3-4f29-9ece-3be60c835222 /mnt/usbflash vfat noauto,owner,ro,nosuid,nodev,noexec 0 0\n\nIf a file system found in \"/etc/fstab\" refers to removable media and it does not have the \"nosuid\" option set, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The \"nosuid\" mount option causes the system not to execute \"setuid\" and \"setgid\" files with owner privileges. This option must be used for mounting any file system not containing approved \"setuid\" and \"setguid\" files. Executing files from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for nonprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"7298","uuid":"79c22b5e-72ad-4b05-bd30-34523a27e25a","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: BC4ACADDEBEFA33152D12DE128F96FAB78F27035\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must prevent files with the setuid and setgid bit set from being executed on file systems that are used with removable media.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271647","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271647","title":"SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271647","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154","rule_id_src":"SV-271647r1091653_rule","rule_id":"SV-271647","rule_version":"OL09-00-002030","rule_title":"OL 9 must mount /boot with the nodev option.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to mount /boot with the nodev option.\n\nModify \"/etc/fstab\" to use the \"nodev\" option on the \"/boot\" directory.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured to mount /boot with the nodev option.\n\nVerify that the \"/boot\" mount point has the \"nodev\" option is with the following command:\n\n$ mount | grep '\\s/boot\\s'\n/dev/sda1 on /boot type xfs (rw,nodev,relatime,seclabel,attr2)\n\nIf the \"/boot\" file system does not have the \"nodev\" option set, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The only legitimate location for device files is the \"/dev\" directory located on the root partition. The only exception to this is chroot jails.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001764"],"reference_identifier":"1096","uuid":"9c7079b3-79de-4355-b076-a03f4f5e10e0","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 372DA8629515311D4F09B0E0FA673C8FB01A7D00\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must mount /boot with the nodev option.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271648","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271648","title":"SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271648","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154","rule_id_src":"SV-271648r1091656_rule","rule_id":"SV-271648","rule_version":"OL09-00-002031","rule_title":"OL 9 must prevent files with the setuid and setgid bit set from being executed on the /boot directory.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to prevent files with the setuid and setgid bit set from being executed on the /boot directory.\n\nModify \"/etc/fstab\" to use the \"nosuid\" option on the \"/boot\" directory.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured to mount /boot with the nosuid option.\n\nVerify that the /boot directory is mounted with the \"nosuid\" option with the following command:\n\n$ mount | grep '\\s/boot\\s'\n/dev/sda1 on /boot type xfs (rw,nosuid,relatime,seclabe,attr2,inode64,noquota)\n\nIf the /boot file system does not have the \"nosuid\" option set, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The \"nosuid\" mount option causes the system not to execute \"setuid\" and \"setgid\" files with owner privileges. This option must be used for mounting any file system not containing approved \"setuid\" and \"setguid\" files. Executing files from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for nonprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001764"],"reference_identifier":"9122","uuid":"7fd38da7-4262-4a8d-9700-865c3b644415","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 51E17FDA435F00FF97E1475F94C0BC0C9FB41ECD\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must prevent files with the setuid and setgid bit set from being executed on the /boot directory.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271649","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271649","title":"SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271649","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154","rule_id_src":"SV-271649r1184198_rule","rule_id":"SV-271649","rule_version":"OL09-00-002032","rule_title":"OL 9 must prevent files with the setuid and setgid bit set from being executed on the /boot/efi directory.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to prevent files with the setuid and setgid bit set from being executed on the /boot/efi directory.\n\nModify \"/etc/fstab\" to use the \"nosuid\" option on the \"/boot/efi\" directory.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify OL 9 /boot/efi directory is mounted with the \"nosuid\" option with the following command:\n\n$ mount | grep '\\s/boot/efi\\s'\n/dev/sda1 on /boot/efi type vfat (rw,nosuid,relatime,fmask=0077,dmask=0077,codepage=437,iocharset=ascii,shortname=winnt,errors=remount-ro)\n\nIf the /boot/efi file system does not have the \"nosuid\" option set, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The \"nosuid\" mount option causes the system not to execute \"setuid\" and \"setgid\" files with owner privileges. This option must be used for mounting any file system not containing approved \"setuid\" and \"setguid\" files. Executing files from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for nonprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001764"],"reference_identifier":"3801","uuid":"ee602f46-c1e2-4ddd-b186-b5f9cbec8ce3","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: D9A56B8594A4584DF9E83EABD3427D843BC37A58\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must prevent files with the setuid and setgid bit set from being executed on the /boot/efi directory.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271650","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271650","title":"SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271650","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154","rule_id_src":"SV-271650r1091662_rule","rule_id":"SV-271650","rule_version":"OL09-00-002040","rule_title":"OL 9 must mount /dev/shm with the nodev option.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to mount /dev/shm with the nodev option.\n\nModify \"/etc/fstab\" to use the \"nodev\" option on the \"/dev/shm\" file system.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured to mount /dev/shm with the nodev option.\n\nVerify \"/dev/shm\" is mounted with the \"nodev\" option with the following command:\n\n$ mount | grep /dev/shm\ntmpfs on /dev/shm type tmpfs (rw,nodev,nosuid,noexec,seclabel)\n\nIf the /dev/shm file system is mounted without the \"nodev\" option, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The nodev mount option causes the system to not interpret character or block special devices. Executing character or block special devices from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for nonprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.\n\nThe only legitimate location for device files is the \"/dev\" directory located on the root partition, with the exception of chroot jails if implemented.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001764"],"reference_identifier":"5365","uuid":"1d5f1785-db49-4a27-a0e3-f977905a0ef4","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 945BCB5F9B02D1D4353A66757EDA6539F2EE92CE\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'OL 9 must mount /dev/shm with the nodev option.' is not present or not in use on this the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271651","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271651","title":"SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271651","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154","rule_id_src":"SV-271651r1091665_rule","rule_id":"SV-271651","rule_version":"OL09-00-002041","rule_title":"OL 9 must mount /dev/shm with the noexec option.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to mount /dev/shm with the noexec option.\n\nModify \"/etc/fstab\" to use the \"noexec\" option on the \"/dev/shm\" file system.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured to mount /dev/shm with the noexec option.\n\nVerify \"/dev/shm\" is mounted with the \"noexec\" option with the following command:\n\n$ mount | grep /dev/shm\ntmpfs on /dev/shm type tmpfs (rw,nodev,nosuid,noexec,seclabel)\n\nIf the /dev/shm file system is mounted without the \"noexec\" option, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UN