errides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: D333A1F4FD85EC1B549B2FA7A7FB8293D77DA135\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 /var/log/messages file must be owned by root.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271823","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271823","title":"SRG-OS-000206-GPOS-00084","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271823","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000206-GPOS-00084","rule_id_src":"SV-271823r1092181_rule","rule_id":"SV-271823","rule_version":"OL09-00-002565","rule_title":"OL 9 /var/log/messages file must have mode 0640 or less permissive.","fix_text":"Configure the \"/var/log/messages\" file to have a mode of \"0640\" by running the following command:\n\n$ sudo chmod 0640 /var/log/messages","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 configures the \"/var/log/messages\" file to have a mode of \"0640\" or less permissive with the following command:\n\n$ ls -la /var/log/messages\nrw-------. 1 root root 564223 July 11 11:34 /var/log/messages\n\nIf \"/var/log/messages\" does not have a mode of \"0640\" or less permissive, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Only authorized personnel should be aware of errors and the details of the errors. Error messages are an indicator of an organization's operational state or can identify the OL 9 system or platform. Additionally, personally identifiable information (PII) and operational information must not be revealed through error messages to unauthorized personnel or their designated representatives.\n\nThe structure and content of error messages must be carefully considered by the organization and development team. The extent to which the information system is able to identify and handle error conditions is guided by organizational policy and operational requirements.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001314"],"reference_identifier":"2783","uuid":"dac4b46b-ff0d-4dd2-9557-d7d8de50a096","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 884E14CD695020A4C9058198125F7E0FB402C318\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 /var/log/messages file must have mode 0640 or less permissive.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271824","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271824","title":"SRG-OS-000256-GPOS-00097","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271824","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000256-GPOS-00097","rule_id_src":"SV-271824r1092184_rule","rule_id":"SV-271824","rule_version":"OL09-00-002570","rule_title":"OL 9 audit tools must be group-owned by root.","fix_text":"Configure the audit tools to be group-owned by \"root\" by running the following command:\n\n$ sudo chgrp root [audit_tool]\n\nReplace \"[audit_tool]\" with each audit tool not group-owned by \"root\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 audit tools are group owned by \"root\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo stat -c \"%G %n\" /sbin/auditctl /sbin/aureport /sbin/ausearch /sbin/autrace /sbin/auditd /sbin/rsyslogd /sbin/augenrules\nroot /sbin/auditctl\nroot /sbin/aureport\nroot /sbin/ausearch\nroot /sbin/autrace\nroot /sbin/auditd\nroot /sbin/rsyslogd\nroot /sbin/augenrules\n\nIf any audit tools do not have a group owner of \"root\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Protecting audit information also includes identifying and protecting the tools used to view and manipulate log data; therefore, protecting audit tools is necessary to prevent unauthorized operation on audit information.\n\nOL 9 systems providing tools to interface with audit information will leverage user permissions and roles identifying the user accessing the tools, and the corresponding rights the user enjoys, to make access decisions regarding the access to audit tools.\n\nAudit tools include, but are not limited to, vendor-provided and open source audit tools needed to successfully view and manipulate audit information system activity and records. Audit tools include custom queries and report generators.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001493"],"reference_identifier":"3384","uuid":"35ac406b-323b-451e-90c4-1157f16d43f6","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 9A4416C838A9996D4584B6AFDE778919258A55C9\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 audit tools must be group-owned by root.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271825","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271825","title":"SRG-OS-000256-GPOS-00097","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271825","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000256-GPOS-00097","rule_id_src":"SV-271825r1092187_rule","rule_id":"SV-271825","rule_version":"OL09-00-002571","rule_title":"OL 9 audit tools must be owned by root.","fix_text":"Configure the audit tools to be owned by \"root\" by running the following command:\n\n$ sudo chown root [audit_tool]\n\nReplace \"[audit_tool]\" with each audit tool not owned by \"root\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 audit tools are owned by \"root\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo stat -c \"%U %n\" /sbin/auditctl /sbin/aureport /sbin/ausearch /sbin/autrace /sbin/auditd /sbin/rsyslogd /sbin/augenrules\nroot /sbin/auditctl\nroot /sbin/aureport\nroot /sbin/ausearch\nroot /sbin/autrace\nroot /sbin/auditd\nroot /sbin/rsyslogd\nroot /sbin/augenrules\n\nIf any audit tools do not have an owner of \"root\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Protecting audit information also includes identifying and protecting the tools used to view and manipulate log data. Therefore, protecting audit tools is necessary to prevent unauthorized operation on audit information.\n\nOL 9 systems providing tools to interface with audit information will leverage user permissions and roles identifying the user accessing the tools, and the corresponding rights the user enjoys, to make access decisions regarding the access to audit tools.\n\nAudit tools include, but are not limited to, vendor-provided and open source audit tools needed to successfully view and manipulate audit information system activity and records. Audit tools include custom queries and report generators.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001493"],"reference_identifier":"9982","uuid":"bea58e02-6b1d-47e9-bba3-ccdcf17fb4ad","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: BC4EC882F557C824ED0EE1EEFCDC9649D89AD82B\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 audit tools must be owned by root.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271826","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271826","title":"SRG-OS-000256-GPOS-00097","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271826","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000256-GPOS-00097","rule_id_src":"SV-271826r1092190_rule","rule_id":"SV-271826","rule_version":"OL09-00-002572","rule_title":"OL 9 audit tools must have a mode of 0755 or less permissive.","fix_text":"Configure the audit tools to have a mode of \"0755\" by running the following command:\n\n$ sudo chmod 0755 [audit_tool]\n\nReplace \"[audit_tool]\" with each audit tool that has a more permissive mode than 0755.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 audit tools have a mode of \"0755\" or less with the following command:\n\n$ stat -c \"%a %n\" /sbin/auditctl /sbin/aureport /sbin/ausearch /sbin/autrace /sbin/auditd /sbin/rsyslogd /sbin/augenrules\n755 /sbin/auditctl\n755 /sbin/aureport\n755 /sbin/ausearch\n750 /sbin/autrace\n755 /sbin/auditd\n755 /sbin/rsyslogd\n755 /sbin/augenrules\n\nIf any of the audit tool files have a mode more permissive than \"0755\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Protecting audit information also includes identifying and protecting the tools used to view and manipulate log data. Therefore, protecting audit tools is necessary to prevent unauthorized operation on audit information.\n\nOL 9 systems providing tools to interface with audit information will leverage user permissions and roles identifying the user accessing the tools, and the corresponding rights the user enjoys, to make access decisions regarding the access to audit tools.\n\nAudit tools include, but are not limited to, vendor-provided and open source audit tools needed to successfully view and manipulate audit information system activity and records. Audit tools include custom queries and report generators.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001493"],"reference_identifier":"5126","uuid":"06ef9c44-388d-442d-9329-a1a9e1937a61","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 0AF6BF92B00097DCF288C185F39517E53F09524F\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 audit tools must have a mode of 0755 or less permissive.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271827","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271827","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271827","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271827r1092193_rule","rule_id":"SV-271827","rule_version":"OL09-00-002580","rule_title":"OL 9 cron configuration directories must have a mode of 0700 or less permissive.","fix_text":"Configure any OL 9 cron configuration directory with a mode more permissive than \"0700\" as follows:\n\n$ sudo chmod 0700 [cron configuration directory]","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 configures permissions of the cron directories with the following command:\n\n$ find /etc/cron* -type d | xargs stat -c \"%a %n\"\n700 /etc/cron.d\n700 /etc/cron.daily\n700 /etc/cron.hourly\n700 /etc/cron.monthly\n700 /etc/cron.weekly\n\nIf any cron configuration directory is more permissive than \"700\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Service configuration files enable or disable features of their respective services that if configured incorrectly can lead to insecure and vulnerable configurations. Therefore, service configuration files should have the correct access rights to prevent unauthorized changes.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"3111","uuid":"f58a8d27-adf4-41d4-90fb-014670fcb30e","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: AC1DFABCB0144628207C111F5E929093457AE427\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 cron configuration directories must have a mode of 0700 or less permissive.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271828","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271828","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271828","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271828r1092196_rule","rule_id":"SV-271828","rule_version":"OL09-00-002581","rule_title":"OL 9 cron configuration files directory must be group-owned by root.","fix_text":"Configure any cron configuration not group-owned by root with the following command:\n\n$ sudo chgrp root [cron config file]","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 configures group ownership of all cron configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ stat -c \"%G %n\" /etc/cron*\nroot /etc/cron.d\nroot /etc/cron.daily\nroot /etc/cron.deny\nroot /etc/cron.hourly\nroot /etc/cron.monthly\nroot /etc/crontab\nroot /etc/cron.weekly\n\nIf any crontab is not group owned by root, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Service configuration files enable or disable features of their respective services that if configured incorrectly can lead to insecure and vulnerable configurations; therefore, service configuration files should be owned by the correct group to prevent unauthorized changes.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"6299","uuid":"f723e6d8-98dc-41cb-ab2b-6448f4ed9521","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: FAEC50A06FD31832650A64D1407B63D1070848E7\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'OL 9 cron configuration files directory must be group-owned by root.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271829","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271829","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271829","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271829r1092199_rule","rule_id":"SV-271829","rule_version":"OL09-00-002582","rule_title":"OL 9 cron configuration files directory must be owned by root.","fix_text":"Configure any cron configuration not owned by root with the following command:\n\n$ sudo chown root [cron config file]","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 configures ownership of all cron configuration files with the command:\n\n$ stat -c \"%U %n\" /etc/cron*\nroot /etc/cron.d\nroot /etc/cron.daily\nroot /etc/cron.deny\nroot /etc/cron.hourly\nroot /etc/cron.monthly\nroot /etc/crontab\nroot /etc/cron.weekly\n\nIf any crontab is not owned by root, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Service configuration files enable or disable features of their respective services that if configured incorrectly can lead to insecure and vulnerable configurations; therefore, service configuration files must be owned by the correct group to prevent unauthorized changes.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"5702","uuid":"51c84a58-dbe2-4604-a691-388de5ee9b24","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: DB6C5A7DAA7DAC8ADAE7316C17C3568FF0EAC357\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 cron configuration files directory must be owned by root.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271830","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271830","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271830","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271830r1092202_rule","rule_id":"SV-271830","rule_version":"OL09-00-002583","rule_title":"OL 9 /etc/crontab file must have mode 0600.","fix_text":"Configure the OL 9 file /etc/crontab with mode 600.\n\n$ sudo chmod 0600 /etc/crontab","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 configures permissions of /etc/crontab with the following command:\n\n$ stat -c \"%a %n\" /etc/crontab\n0600\n\nIf /etc/crontab does not have a mode of \"0600\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Service configuration files enable or disable features of their respective services that if configured incorrectly can lead to insecure and vulnerable configurations; therefore, service configuration files must have the correct access rights to prevent unauthorized changes.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"9810","uuid":"075542c8-00b6-4dbf-94f0-6a4a7722c56f","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 97368260025E57FC6E172D9118B32BD52AFFD999\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 /etc/crontab file must have mode 0600.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271831","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271831","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271831","severity":"high","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271831r1092205_rule","rule_id":"SV-271831","rule_version":"OL09-00-003000","rule_title":"OL 9 must be configured so that the root account is the only account having unrestricted access to the system.","fix_text":"Change the UID of any account on the system, other than root, that has a UID of \"0\". \n\nIf the account is associated with system commands or applications, the UID should be changed to one greater than \"0\" but less than \"1000\". Otherwise, assign a UID of greater than \"1000\" that has not already been assigned.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 configures only the \"root\" account to have a UID \"0\" assignment with the following command:\n\n$ awk -F: '$3 == 0 {print $1}' /etc/passwd\nroot\n\nIf any accounts other than \"root\" have a UID of \"0\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"An account has root authority if it has a user identifier (UID) of \"0\". Multiple accounts with a UID of \"0\" afford more opportunity for potential intruders to guess a password for a privileged account. Proper configuration of sudo is recommended to afford multiple system administrators access to root privileges in an accountable manner.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2968","uuid":"da2e80a1-f708-4ddd-ac21-6e7d84794218","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 5A6BB82FAEB4E1B9EBC6BED9BC9449D11FE270E3\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'OL 9 must be configured so that the root account is the only account having unrestricted access to the system.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271832","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271832","title":"SRG-OS-000104-GPOS-00051","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271832","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000104-GPOS-00051","rule_id_src":"SV-271832r1092208_rule","rule_id":"SV-271832","rule_version":"OL09-00-003001","rule_title":"OL 9 duplicate User IDs (UIDs) must not exist for interactive users.","fix_text":"Edit the file \"/etc/passwd\" and provide each interactive user account that has a duplicate UID with a unique UID.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 contains no duplicate UIDs for interactive users with the following command:\n\n$ sudo awk -F \":\" 'list[$3]++{print $1, $3}' /etc/passwd \n\nIf output is produced and the accounts listed are interactive user accounts, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"To ensure accountability and prevent unauthenticated access, interactive users must be identified and authenticated to prevent potential misuse and compromise of the system.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000104-GPOS-00051, SRG-OS-000121-GPOS-00062, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000764","CCI-000804","CCI-000135"],"reference_identifier":"7602","uuid":"91d86016-9bfc-40e8-ae6d-f10bee8d10f1","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 1C4688D266F79CA68AF3C3538CF81C7BA57F3961\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 duplicate User IDs (UIDs) must not exist for interactive users.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271833","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271833","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271833","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271833r1092607_rule","rule_id":"SV-271833","rule_version":"OL09-00-003002","rule_title":"OL 9 local interactive users must have a home directory assigned in the /etc/passwd file.","fix_text":"Create and assign home directories to all local interactive users on OL 9 that currently do not have a home directory assigned.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 configures interactive users on the system have a home directory assigned with the following command:\n \n$ sudo awk -F: '($3>=1000)&&($7 !~ /nologin/){print $1, $3, $6}' /etc/passwd\nsmithk:x:1000:1000:smithk:/home/smithk:/bin/bash\nscsaustin:x:1001:1001:scsaustin:/home/scsaustin:/bin/bash\ndjohnson:x:1002:1002:djohnson:/home/djohnson:/bin/bash\n\nInspect the output and verify that all interactive users (normally users with a user identifier [UID] greater that 1000) have a home directory defined.\n\nIf users home directory is not defined, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If local interactive users are not assigned a valid home directory, there is no place for the storage and control of files they should own.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"1629","uuid":"460d7521-efd5-442e-bc8e-1bba5f6a6ab2","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: A8E507A0A293EC645C5D0E32C25A2C9B15F044F5\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 local interactive users must have a home directory assigned in the /etc/passwd file.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271834","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271834","title":"SRG-OS-000104-GPOS-00051","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271834","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000104-GPOS-00051","rule_id_src":"SV-271834r1092214_rule","rule_id":"SV-271834","rule_version":"OL09-00-003005","rule_title":"OL 9 interactive users must have a primary group that exists.","fix_text":"Configure the system so that all GIDs are referenced in \"/etc/passwd\" are defined in \"/etc/group\".\n\nEdit the file \"/etc/passwd\" and ensure that every user's GID is a valid GID.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 interactive users have a valid GID.\n\nCheck that the interactive users have a valid GID with the following command:\n \n$ sudo pwck -qr \n \nIf the system has any interactive users with duplicate GIDs, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If a user is assigned the Group Identifier (GID) of a group that does not exist on the system, and a group with the GID is subsequently created, the user may have unintended rights to any files associated with the group.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000764"],"reference_identifier":"2027","uuid":"ff8a06f2-a9bb-437b-ad31-d88c015afbac","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: E1EF00C5A9BC32B54515BF92E97832A98511AB53\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 interactive users must have a primary group that exists.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271835","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271835","title":"SRG-OS-000104-GPOS-00051","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271835","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000104-GPOS-00051","rule_id_src":"SV-271835r1092217_rule","rule_id":"SV-271835","rule_version":"OL09-00-003006","rule_title":"OL 9 groups must have unique Group ID (GID).","fix_text":"Edit the file \"/etc/group\" and provide each group that has a duplicate GID with a unique GID.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 contains no duplicate GIDs for interactive users with the following command:\n \n$  cut -d : -f 3 /etc/group | uniq -d\n \nIf the system has duplicate GIDs, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"To ensure accountability and prevent unauthenticated access, groups must be identified uniquely to prevent potential misuse and compromise of the system.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000764"],"reference_identifier":"7488","uuid":"ed7d784f-059f-4ca5-88f2-59ec420169db","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 07D8106EC75F892C2D786D515BB0B5F0116871B1\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'OL 9 groups must have unique Group ID (GID).' is not present or not in use on this the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271836","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271836","title":"SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271836","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005","rule_id_src":"SV-271836r1092637_rule","rule_id":"SV-271836","rule_version":"OL09-00-003010","rule_title":"OL 9 must configure SELinux context type to allow the use of a nondefault faillock tally directory.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to allow the use of a nondefault faillock tally directory while SELinux enforces a targeted policy.\n\nCreate a nondefault faillock tally directory (if it does not already exist) with the following example:\n\n$ sudo mkdir /var/log/faillock\n\nUpdate the /etc/selinux/targeted/contexts/files/file_contexts.local with \"faillog_t\" context type for the nondefault faillock tally directory with the following command:\n\n$ sudo semanage fcontext -a -t faillog_t \"/var/log/faillock(/.*)?\"\n\nUpdate the context type of the nondefault faillock directory/subdirectories and files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo restorecon -R -v /var/log/faillock","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Note: If the system does not have SELinux enabled and enforcing a targeted policy, or if the pam_faillock module is not configured for use, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nVerify that OL 9 configures the SELinux context type to allow the use of a nondefault faillock tally directory.\n\nVerify the location of the nondefault tally directory for the pam_faillock module with the following command:\n\n$ grep 'dir =' /etc/security/faillock.conf\ndir = /var/log/faillock\n\nCheck the security context type of the nondefault tally directory with the following command:\n\n$ ls -Zd /var/log/faillock\nunconfined_u:object_r:faillog_t:s0 /var/log/faillock\n\nIf the security context type of the nondefault tally directory is not \"faillog_t\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Not having the correct SELinux context on the faillock directory may lead to unauthorized access to the directory.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000044"],"reference_identifier":"9879","uuid":"5597564b-44f4-40d9-8f76-9979fea767ca","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 6C1FBDB4B3018CE0948FE8DC1073A6903729D9B7\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must configure SELinux context type to allow the use of a nondefault faillock tally directory.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271837","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271837","title":"SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271837","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005","rule_id_src":"SV-271837r1092223_rule","rule_id":"SV-271837","rule_version":"OL09-00-003011","rule_title":"OL 9 must configure the use of the pam_faillock.so module in the /etc/pam.d/system-auth file.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to include the use of the pam_faillock.so module in the /etc/pam.d/system-auth file.\n\nAdd/modify the appropriate sections of the \"/etc/pam.d/system-auth\" file to match the following lines:\nNote: The \"preauth\" line must be listed before pam_unix.so.\n\nauth required pam_faillock.so preauth\nauth required pam_faillock.so authfail\naccount required pam_faillock.so","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 configures the pam_faillock.so module to exist in the \"/etc/pam.d/system-auth\" file with the following command:\n\n$ grep pam_faillock.so /etc/pam.d/system-auth\nauth required pam_faillock.so preauth\nauth required pam_faillock.so authfail\naccount required pam_faillock.so\n\nIf the pam_faillock.so module is not present in the \"/etc/pam.d/system-auth\" file with the \"preauth\" line listed before pam_unix.so, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If the pam_faillock.so module is not loaded, the system will not correctly lockout accounts to prevent password guessing attacks.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000044"],"reference_identifier":"2064","uuid":"7133c507-380a-4fd0-b60c-764acfff98d3","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 3DDFA46B67823358D6F4222EC3F22D01BAC5724B\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must configure the use of the pam_faillock.so module in the /etc/pam.d/system-auth file.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271838","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271838","title":"SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271838","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005","rule_id_src":"SV-271838r1092226_rule","rule_id":"SV-271838","rule_version":"OL09-00-003012","rule_title":"OL 9 must configure the use of the pam_faillock.so module in the /etc/pam.d/password-auth file.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to include the use of the pam_faillock.so module in the /etc/pam.d/password-auth file.\n\nAdd/modify the appropriate sections of the \"/etc/pam.d/password-auth\" file to match the following lines:\nNote: The \"preauth\" line must be listed before pam_unix.so.\n\nauth required pam_faillock.so preauth\nauth required pam_faillock.so authfail\naccount required pam_faillock.so","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 configures the pam_faillock.so module to exist in the \"/etc/pam.d/password-auth\" file with the following command:\n\n$ grep pam_faillock.so /etc/pam.d/password-auth\nauth required pam_faillock.so preauth\nauth required pam_faillock.so authfail\naccount required pam_faillock.so\n\nIf the pam_faillock.so module is not present in the \"/etc/pam.d/password-auth\" file with the \"preauth\" line listed before pam_unix.so, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If the pam_faillock.so module is not loaded, the system will not correctly lockout accounts to prevent password guessing attacks.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000044"],"reference_identifier":"5531","uuid":"3d8eab1d-6c8c-4a68-be7f-3cc63bcf454d","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-271839","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271839","title":"SRG-OS-000329-GPOS-00128","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271839","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000329-GPOS-00128","rule_id_src":"SV-271839r1092229_rule","rule_id":"SV-271839","rule_version":"OL09-00-003020","rule_title":"OL 9 must automatically lock an account when three unsuccessful logon attempts occur.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to lock an account when three unsuccessful logon attempts occur.\n\nAdd/modify the \"/etc/security/faillock.conf\" file to match the following line:\n\ndeny = 3","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured to lock an account after three unsuccessful logon attempts with the command:\n\n$ grep 'deny =' /etc/security/faillock.conf\ndeny = 3\n\nIf the \"deny\" option is not set to \"3\" or less (but not \"0\"), is missing or commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"By limiting the number of failed logon attempts, the risk of unauthorized system access via user password guessing, otherwise known as brute-force attacks, is reduced. Limits are imposed by locking the account.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000329-GPOS-00128, SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002238","CCI-000044"],"reference_identifier":"8399","uuid":"cb2bcb31-c898-4ce5-a4a1-596e42b29b4f","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: AEBFEF4B4B73C135995AECD528B81B5906CFE6AB\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must automatically lock an account when three unsuccessful logon attempts occur.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271840","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271840","title":"SRG-OS-000329-GPOS-00128","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271840","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000329-GPOS-00128","rule_id_src":"SV-271840r1092232_rule","rule_id":"SV-271840","rule_version":"OL09-00-003021","rule_title":"OL 9 must automatically lock the root account until the root account is released by an administrator when three unsuccessful logon attempts occur during a 15-minute time period.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to lock out the \"root\" account after a number of incorrect login attempts using \"pam_faillock.so\", first enable the feature using the following command:\n \n$ sudo authselect enable-feature with-faillock  \n\nThen edit the \"/etc/security/faillock.conf\" file as follows:\n \n  add or uncomment the following line:\n even_deny_root","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured to lock the root account after three unsuccessful logon attempts with the command:\n\n$ grep even_deny_root /etc/security/faillock.conf\neven_deny_root\n\nIf the \"even_deny_root\" option is not set, is missing or commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"By limiting the number of failed logon attempts, the risk of unauthorized system access via user password guessing, also known as brute-forcing, is reduced. Limits are imposed by locking the account.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000329-GPOS-00128, SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002238","CCI-000044"],"reference_identifier":"2439","uuid":"5c1fba8d-65d6-40db-a020-788d6e366824","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 0E71430D37E5CBFF69DF6B99C1697DAFBE6B2649\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must automatically lock the root account until the root account is released by an administrator when three unsuccessful logon attempts occur during a 15-minute time period.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271841","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271841","title":"SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271841","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005","rule_id_src":"SV-271841r1092235_rule","rule_id":"SV-271841","rule_version":"OL09-00-003022","rule_title":"OL 9 must log username information when unsuccessful logon attempts occur.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to log username information when unsuccessful logon attempts occur.\n\nAdd/modify the \"/etc/security/faillock.conf\" file to match the following line:\n\naudit","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 logs username information when unsuccessful logon attempts occur.\n\nVerify the \"/etc/security/faillock.conf\" file is configured to log username information when unsuccessful logon attempts occur with the following command:\n\n$ grep audit /etc/security/faillock.conf\naudit\n\nIf the \"audit\" option is not set, is missing, or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without auditing of these events, it may be harder or impossible to identify what an attacker did after an attack.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000044"],"reference_identifier":"8673","uuid":"e079e25f-86b8-4e75-aa1c-80d5966d7c39","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 35A4206634CAAB4B7CE492D5439110E6E9CBB91C\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must log username information when unsuccessful logon attempts occur.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271842","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271842","title":"SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271842","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005","rule_id_src":"SV-271842r1092238_rule","rule_id":"SV-271842","rule_version":"OL09-00-003023","rule_title":"OL 9 must ensure account lockouts persist.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 maintain the contents of the faillock directory after a reboot.\n\nAdd/modify the \"/etc/security/faillock.conf\" file to match the following line:\n\ndir = /var/log/faillock","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 ensures that account lockouts persist.\n\nVerify the \"/etc/security/faillock.conf\" file is configured use a nondefault faillock directory to ensure contents persist after reboot with the following command:\n\n$ grep 'dir =' /etc/security/faillock.conf\ndir = /var/log/faillock\n\nIf the \"dir\" option is not set to a nondefault documented tally log directory, is missing or commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Having lockouts persist across reboots ensures that account is only unlocked by an administrator. If the lockouts did not persist across reboots, an attacker could simply reboot the system to continue brute force attacks against the accounts on the system.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000044"],"reference_identifier":"2447","uuid":"d94897b4-d4f3-4515-9395-90e675b96efb","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: F23D31C7EBDFFADC9D52865651AF5AABD98E6090\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must ensure account lockouts persist.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271843","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271843","title":"SRG-OS-000123-GPOS-00064","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271843","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000123-GPOS-00064","rule_id_src":"SV-271843r1094969_rule","rule_id":"SV-271843","rule_version":"OL09-00-003030","rule_title":"OL 9 must automatically expire temporary accounts within 72 hours.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to expire temporary accounts after 72 hours with the following command:\n\n$ sudo chage -E $(date -d +3days +%Y-%m-%d) <temporary_account_name>","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 configures temporary accounts to be provisioned with an expiration date of 72 hours.\n\nFor every existing temporary account, run the following command to obtain its account expiration information:\n\n$ chage -l <temporary_account_name> | grep -i \"account expires\"\n\nVerify each of these accounts has an expiration date set within 72 hours. \n\nIf any temporary accounts have no expiration date set or do not expire within 72 hours, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Temporary accounts are privileged or nonprivileged accounts that are established during pressing circumstances, such as new software or hardware configuration or an incident response, where the need for prompt account activation requires bypassing normal account authorization procedures. If any inactive temporary accounts are left enabled on the system and are not either manually removed or automatically expired within 72 hours, the security posture of the system will be degraded and exposed to exploitation by unauthorized users or insider threat actors.\n\nTemporary accounts are different from emergency accounts. Emergency accounts, also known as \"last resort\" or \"break glass\" accounts, are local logon accounts enabled on the system for emergency use by authorized system administrators to manage a system when standard logon methods are failing or not available. Emergency accounts are not subject to manual removal or scheduled expiration requirements.\n\nThe automatic expiration of temporary accounts may be extended as needed by the circumstances, but it must not be extended indefinitely. A documented permanent account should be established for privileged users who need long-term maintenance accounts.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000123-GPOS-00064, SRG-OS-000002-GPOS-00002","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001682","CCI-000016"],"reference_identifier":"7792","uuid":"447fc3e7-a464-4919-80c4-00d9f7d82be1","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: A4E2F6E2B7B257AAE3484A542B7FA79DE4B8336C\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must automatically expire temporary accounts within 72 hours.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271844","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271844","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271844","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271844r1184222_rule","rule_id":"SV-271844","rule_version":"OL09-00-003050","rule_title":"OL 9 local interactive user home directories defined in the /etc/passwd file must exist.","fix_text":"Create home directories to all local interactive users that currently do not have a home directory assigned. Use the following commands to create the user home directory assigned in \"/etc/ passwd\":\n\nNote: The example will be for the user disauser, who has a home directory of \"/home/disauser\", a user identifier (UID) of \"disauser\", and a Group Identifier (GID) of \"users assigned\" in \"/etc/passwd\".\n\n$ sudo mkdir /home/disauser \n$ sudo chown disauser /home/disauser\n$ sudo chgrp users /home/disauser\n$ sudo chmod 0750 /home/disauser","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify OL 9 assigned home directories of all interactive users on the system exist with the following command:\n\n$ sudo pwck -r \n\nThe output should not return any interactive users.\n\nIf users home directory does not exist, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If a local interactive user has a home directory defined that does not exist, the user may be given access to the / directory as the current working directory upon logon. This could create a denial of service because the user would not be able to access their logon configuration files, and it may give them visibility to system files they normally would not be able to access.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"9418","uuid":"6827be25-f11b-41b2-b722-f8002f8ea3b3","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: C9021C93D5D1A32CCD6EB2508F499E905EFFDD3C\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 local interactive user home directories defined in the /etc/passwd file must exist.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271845","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271845","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271845","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271845r1092247_rule","rule_id":"SV-271845","rule_version":"OL09-00-003051","rule_title":"OL 9 system accounts must not have an interactive login shell.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 so that all noninteractive accounts on the system do not have an interactive shell assigned to them.\n\nIf the system account needs a shell assigned for mission operations, document the need with the ISSO.\n\nRun the following command to disable the interactive shell for a specific noninteractive user account:\n\nReplace <user> with the user that has a login shell.\n\n$ sudo usermod --shell /sbin/nologin <user>\n\nDo not perform the steps in this section on the root account. Doing so will cause the system to become inaccessible.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 configures system accounts to not have an interactive login shell with the following command:\n\n$ awk -F: '($3<1000){print $1 \":\" $3 \":\" $7}' /etc/passwd\nroot:0:/bin/bash\nbin:1:/sbin/nologin\ndaemon:2:/sbin/nologin\nadm:3:/sbin/nologin\nlp:4:/sbin/nologin\n\nIdentify the system accounts from this listing that do not have a nologin shell.\n\nIf any system account (other than the root account) has a login shell and it is not documented with the information system security officer (ISSO), this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Ensuring shells are not given to system accounts upon login makes it more difficult for attackers to make use of system accounts.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"5722","uuid":"3985391c-369a-46b8-9821-9fd10a795422","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 5A266E304221CA2479A873AE340C0344525F489D\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 system accounts must not have an interactive login shell.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271846","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271846","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271846","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271846r1092250_rule","rule_id":"SV-271846","rule_version":"OL09-00-003052","rule_title":"OL 9 local interactive user accounts must be assigned a home directory upon creation.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to assign home directories to all new local interactive users by setting the \"CREATE_HOME\" parameter in \"/etc/login.defs\" to \"yes\" as follows.\n\nCREATE_HOME yes","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 local interactive users are assigned a home directory upon creation with the following command:\n\n$ grep -i create_home /etc/login.defs\nCREATE_HOME yes\n\nIf the value for \"CREATE_HOME\" parameter is not set to \"yes\", the line is missing, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If local interactive users are not assigned a valid home directory, there is no place for the storage and control of files they should own.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"4330","uuid":"9c573836-b4ae-41ec-8b56-fff9468d2ef2","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 9618C818F70A6052DC2BDC6F486BBDA51098A290\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'OL 9 local interactive user accounts must be assigned a home directory upon creation.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271847","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271847","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271847","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271847r1092253_rule","rule_id":"SV-271847","rule_version":"OL09-00-003053","rule_title":"OL 9 must be configured so that executable search paths within the initialization files of all local interactive users must only contain paths that resolve to the system default or the users home directory.","fix_text":"Edit the local interactive user initialization files to change any PATH variable statements that reference directories other than their home directory.\n\nIf a local interactive user requires path variables to reference a directory owned by the application, it must be documented with the ISSO.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 local interactive user initialization file executable search path statements do not contain statements that will reference a working directory other than user home directories with the following commands:\n\n$ sudo grep -i path= /home/*/.*\n/home/[localinteractiveuser]/.bash_profile:PATH=$PATH:$HOME/.local/bin:$HOME/bin\n\nIf any local interactive user initialization files have executable search path statements that include directories outside of their home directory and is not documented with the ISSO as an operational requirement, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The executable search path (typically the PATH environment variable) contains a list of directories for the shell to search to find executables. If this path includes the current working directory (other than the users home directory), executables in these directories may be executed instead of system commands.\n\nThis variable is formatted as a colon-separated list of directories. If there is an empty entry, such as a leading or trailing colon or two consecutive colons, this is interpreted as the current working directory. If deviations from the default system search path for the local interactive user are required, they must be documented with the information system security officer (ISSO).","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"6527","uuid":"4db6b6ee-ec66-4a1e-b9ff-bfe7237e9b15","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 5AEC037A131007E78D7C671A9F69D63910FE381E\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'OL 9 must be configured so that executable search paths within the initialization files of all local interactive users must only contain paths that resolve to the system default or the users home directory.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271848","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271848","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271848","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271848r1184224_rule","rule_id":"SV-271848","rule_version":"OL09-00-003060","rule_title":"OL 9 must set the umask value to 077 for all local interactive user accounts.","fix_text":"Remove the umask statement from all local interactive user's initialization files. \n\nIf the account is for an application, the requirement for a umask less restrictive than \"077\" can be documented with the information system security officer, but the user agreement for access to the account must specify that the local interactive user must log on to their account first and then switch the user to the application account with the correct option to gain the account's environment variables.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify OL 9 configures the default umask for all local interactive users to be \"077\".\n\nIdentify the locations of all local interactive user home directories by looking at the \"/etc/passwd\" file.\n\nCheck all local interactive user initialization files for interactive users with the following command:\n\nNote: The example is for a system that is configured to create users home directories in the \"/home\" directory.\n\n$ grep -ri umask /home/\n/home/disauser/.bash_history:grep -i umask /etc/bashrc /etc/csh.cshrc /etc/profile\n/home/disauser/.bash_history:grep -i umask /etc/login.defs\n\nIf any local interactive user initialization files are found to have a umask statement that sets a value less restrictive than \"077\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The umask controls the default access mode assigned to newly created files. A umask of 077 limits new files to mode 600 or less permissive. Although umask can be represented as a four-digit number, the first digit representing special access modes is typically ignored or required to be \"0\". This requirement applies to the globally configured system defaults and the local interactive user defaults for each account on the system.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"4387","uuid":"3091def4-4b8b-470b-9942-8a69aad8e183","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: AA434740602855530D9D2832B84DD9C81E094E85\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'OL 9 must set the umask value to 077 for all local interactive user accounts.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271849","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271849","title":"SRG-OS-000118-GPOS-00060","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271849","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000118-GPOS-00060","rule_id_src":"SV-271849r1092259_rule","rule_id":"SV-271849","rule_version":"OL09-00-003065","rule_title":"OL 9 must disable account identifiers (individuals, groups, roles, and devices) after 35 days of inactivity.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to disable account identifiers after 35 days of inactivity after the password expiration. \n\nRun the following command to change the configuration for useradd:\n\n$ sudo useradd -D -f 35\n\nThe recommendation is 35 days, but a lower value is acceptable.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 account identifiers (individuals, groups, roles, and devices) are disabled after 35 days of inactivity with the following command:\n\nCheck the account inactivity value by performing the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -i inactive /etc/default/useradd\nINACTIVE=35\n\nIf \"INACTIVE\" is set to \"-1\", a value greater than \"35\", or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Inactive identifiers pose a risk to systems and applications because attackers may exploit an inactive identifier and potentially obtain undetected access to the system.\n\nDisabling inactive accounts ensures that accounts which may not have been responsibly removed are not available to attackers who may have compromised their credentials.\n\nOwners of inactive accounts will not notice if unauthorized access to their user account has been obtained.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000118-GPOS-00060, SRG-OS-000590-GPOS-00110","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-003627","CCI-003628"],"reference_identifier":"1191","uuid":"843b0644-c26b-4416-99b6-ca73e090f436","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 1621DABB0895F5762637D2DAA9B55CEFA2214891\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'OL 9 must disable account identifiers (individuals, groups, roles, and devices) after 35 days of inactivity.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271850","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271850","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00226","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271850","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00226","rule_id_src":"SV-271850r1092262_rule","rule_id":"SV-271850","rule_version":"OL09-00-003070","rule_title":"OL 9 must enforce a delay of at least four seconds between logon prompts following a failed logon attempt.","fix_text":"Configure the OL 9 to enforce a delay of at least four seconds between logon prompts following a failed console logon attempt.\n\nModify the \"/etc/login.defs\" file to set the \"FAIL_DELAY\" parameter to 4 or greater:\n\nFAIL_DELAY 4","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 enforces a delay of at least four seconds between console logon prompts following a failed logon attempt with the following command:\n\n$ grep -i fail_delay /etc/login.defs\nFAIL_DELAY 4\n\nIf the value of \"FAIL_DELAY\" is not set to \"4\" or greater, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Increasing the time between a failed authentication attempt and reprompting to enter credentials helps to slow a single-threaded brute force attack.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2497","uuid":"66d27ece-1f14-48be-843e-297f983c39c5","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: AC9D529C1BA04EC94183A9152BE88157CC3EC3C9\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'OL 9 must enforce a delay of at least four seconds between logon prompts following a failed logon attempt.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271851","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271851","title":"SRG-OS-000032-GPOS-00013","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271851","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000032-GPOS-00013","rule_id_src":"SV-271851r1092265_rule","rule_id":"SV-271851","rule_version":"OL09-00-005000","rule_title":"OL 9 remote access methods must be monitored.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 remote access methods to be monitored.\n\nAdd or update the following lines to the \"/etc/rsyslog.conf\" file:\n\nauth.*;authpriv.*;daemon.* /var/log/secure\n\nThe \"rsyslog\" service must be restarted for the changes to take effect with the following command:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart rsyslog.service","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 monitors all remote access methods.\n\nCheck that remote access methods are being logged by running the following command:\n\n$ grep -rE '(auth.\\*|authpriv.\\*|daemon.\\*)' /etc/rsyslog.conf\nauthpriv.*                                              /var/log/secure\n \nIf \"auth.*\", \"authpriv.*\" or \"daemon.*\" are not configured to be logged, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Logging remote access methods can be used to trace the decrease in the risks associated with remote user access management. It can also be used to spot cyberattacks and ensure ongoing compliance with organizational policies surrounding the use of remote access methods.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000067"],"reference_identifier":"8517","uuid":"01963a5d-9eb1-4b6b-9043-7537b4b431cb","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 1BA9F02BD2392126B96B851F85768455A125E86F\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'OL 9 remote access methods must be monitored.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271852","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271852","title":"SRG-OS-000479-GPOS-00224","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271852","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000479-GPOS-00224","rule_id_src":"SV-271852r1184227_rule","rule_id":"SV-271852","rule_version":"OL09-00-005005","rule_title":"OL 9 must be configured to forward audit records via TCP to a different system or media from the system being audited via rsyslog.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to offload audit records onto a different system or media from the system being audited via TCP using rsyslog by specifying the remote logging server in \"/etc/rsyslog.conf\" or \"/etc/rsyslog.d/[customfile].conf\" with the name or IP address of the log aggregation server.  Following are examples of the configuration for the legacy syntax and for the newer Rainer script. Only one should be used.\n\nUsing legacy '@host:port\" syntax example:\n*.* @@[remoteloggingserver]:[port]\n\nUsing Rainer script example:\naction(\n    type=\"omfwd\"\n    target=\"logserver.example.com\"\n    port=\"514\"\n    protocol=\"tcp\"\n    action.resumeRetryCount=\"-1\"\n    queue.type=\"linkedList\"\n    que.size=\"10000\"\n)\n\nNote: The Rainer Script above does not contain the required encryption settings.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify OL 9 audit system offloads audit records onto a different system or media from the system being audited via rsyslog using TCP with the following commands:\n\nTo check for legacy configuration syntax, perform the following:\n$ sudo grep -ir '@@' /etc/rsyslog.conf /etc/rsyslog.d/\n\nTo check for Rainer script syntax, perform the following:\n$ sudo grep -rq 'type=\"omfwd\"' /etc/rsyslog.conf /etc/rsyslog.d/\n\nIf a remote server is not configured, or the line is commented out, ask the system administrator (SA) to indicate how the audit logs are offloaded to a different system or media. \n\nIf there is no evidence that the audit logs are being offloaded to another system or media, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Information stored in one location is vulnerable to accidental or incidental deletion or alteration.\n\nOffloading is a common process in information systems with limited audit storage capacity.\n\nOL 9 installation media provides \"rsyslogd\", a system utility providing support for message logging. Support for both internet and Unix domain sockets enables this utility to support both local and remote logging. Coupling this utility with \"gnutls\" (a secure communications library implementing the SSL, TLS, and DTLS protocols) creates a method to securely encrypt and offload auditing.\n\nRsyslog provides three ways to forward message: the traditional UDP transport, which is extremely lossy but standard; the plain TCP based transport, which loses messages only during certain situations but is widely available; and the RELP transport, which does not lose messages but is currently available only as part of the rsyslogd 3.15.0 and above.\n\nExamples of each configuration:\nUDP *.* @remotesystemname\nTCP *.* @@remotesystemname\nRELP *.* :omrelp:remotesystemname:2514\nNote that a port number was given as there is no standard port for RELP.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000479-GPOS-00224, SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001851"],"reference_identifier":"5665","uuid":"18310037-41c5-4139-8f19-72ceb25341df","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-271853","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271853","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271853","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271853r1092271_rule","rule_id":"SV-271853","rule_version":"OL09-00-005010","rule_title":"OL 9 must use cron logging.","fix_text":"Configure \"rsyslog\" to log all cron messages by adding or updating the following line to \"/etc/rsyslog.conf\" or a configuration file in the /etc/rsyslog.d/ directory:\n\ncron.* /var/log/cron\n\nThe rsyslog daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart rsyslog.service","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 rsyslog is configured to log cron events with the following command:\n\nNote: If another logging package is used, substitute the utility configuration file for \"/etc/rsyslog.conf\" or \"/etc/rsyslog.d/*.conf\" files.\n\n$ grep -s cron /etc/rsyslog.conf /etc/rsyslog.d/*.conf\n/etc/rsyslog.conf:*.info;mail.none;authpriv.none;cron.none                          /var/log/messages\n/etc/rsyslog.conf:cron.*                                                           /var/log/cron             \n\nIf the command does not return a response, check for cron logging all facilities with the following command:\n\n$ grep -s /var/log/messages /etc/rsyslog.conf /etc/rsyslog.d/*.conf\n/etc/rsyslog.conf:*.info;mail.none;authpriv.none;cron.none                          /var/log/messages\n\nIf \"rsyslog\" is not logging messages for the cron facility or all facilities, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Cron logging can be used to trace the successful or unsuccessful execution of cron jobs. It can also be used to spot intrusions into the use of the cron facility by unauthorized and malicious users.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"8666","uuid":"009ca8bd-98a0-4089-aeeb-5a2c971b4ac8","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 1696B07FAB664C24BC3ECA00D4D7BE93BDB17398\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'OL 9 must use cron logging.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271854","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271854","title":"SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271854","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133","rule_id_src":"SV-271854r1092274_rule","rule_id":"SV-271854","rule_version":"OL09-00-005015","rule_title":"OL 9 must authenticate the remote logging server for offloading audit logs via rsyslog.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to authenticate the remote logging server for off-loading audit logs by setting the following option in \"/etc/rsyslog.conf\" or \"/etc/rsyslog.d/[customfile].conf\":\n\n$ActionSendStreamDriverAuthMode x509/name","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 authenticates the remote logging server for off-loading audit logs with the following command:\n\n$ grep -i '$ActionSendStreamDriverAuthMode' /etc/rsyslog.conf /etc/rsyslog.d/*.conf \n /etc/rsyslog.conf:$ActionSendStreamDriverAuthMode x509/name \n\nIf the value of the \"$ActionSendStreamDriverAuthMode\" option is not set to \"x509/name\" or the line is commented out, ask the system administrator (SA) to indicate how the audit logs are offloaded to a different system or media. \n\nIf there is no evidence that the transfer of the audit logs being offloaded to another system or media is encrypted, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Information stored in one location is vulnerable to accidental or incidental deletion or alteration.\n\nOffloading is a common process in information systems with limited audit storage capacity.\n\nOL 9 installation media provides \"rsyslogd\", a system utility providing support for message logging. Support for both internet and Unix domain sockets enables this utility to support both local and remote logging. Coupling this utility with \"gnutls\" (a secure communications library implementing the SSL, TLS, and DTLS protocols) creates a method to securely encrypt and offload auditing.\n\n\"Rsyslog\" supported authentication modes include:\nanon - anonymous authentication\nx509/fingerprint - certificate fingerprint authentication\nx509/certvalid - certificate validation only\nx509/name - certificate validation and subject name authentication\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133, SRG-OS-000479-GPOS-00224","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001851"],"reference_identifier":"5889","uuid":"5a095dad-bd99-49b3-8f24-769d590e00c5","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: AC3F06701B97EB0521E3352C5AEE2BBD21909C24\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must authenticate the remote logging server for offloading audit logs via rsyslog.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271855","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271855","title":"SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271855","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133","rule_id_src":"SV-271855r1092277_rule","rule_id":"SV-271855","rule_version":"OL09-00-005020","rule_title":"OL 9 must encrypt the transfer of audit records offloaded onto a different system or media from the system being audited via rsyslog.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to encrypt offloaded audit records via rsyslog by setting the following options in \"/etc/rsyslog.conf\" or \"/etc/rsyslog.d/[customfile].conf\":\n\n$ActionSendStreamDriverMode 1","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 encrypts audit records offloaded onto a different system or media from the system being audited via rsyslog with the following command:\n\n$ grep -i '$ActionSendStreamDriverMode' /etc/rsyslog.conf /etc/rsyslog.d/*.conf \n/etc/rsyslog.conf:$ActionSendStreamDriverMode 1 \n\nIf the value of the \"$ActionSendStreamDriverMode\" option is not set to \"1\" or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Information stored in one location is vulnerable to accidental or incidental deletion or alteration.\n\nOffloading is a common process in information systems with limited audit storage capacity.\n\nOL 9 installation media provides \"rsyslogd\", a system utility providing support for message logging. Support for both internet and Unix domain sockets enables this utility to support both local and remote logging. Coupling this utility with \"gnutls\" (a secure communications library implementing the SSL, TLS, and DTLS protocols) creates a method to securely encrypt and offload auditing.\n\n\"Rsyslog\" supported authentication modes include:\nanon - anonymous authentication\nx509/fingerprint - certificate fingerprint authentication\nx509/certvalid - certificate validation only\nx509/name - certificate validation and subject name authentication\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133, SRG-OS-000479-GPOS-00224","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001851"],"reference_identifier":"5416","uuid":"9862968d-dfc8-49cd-97b3-3210be577c29","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 585D276D1A03928554402DDA6E381D47DEF9BBA5\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'OL 9 must encrypt the transfer of audit records offloaded onto a different system or media from the system being audited via rsyslog.' is not present or not in use on this the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271856","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271856","title":"SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271856","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133","rule_id_src":"SV-271856r1092280_rule","rule_id":"SV-271856","rule_version":"OL09-00-005025","rule_title":"OL 9 must encrypt via the gtls driver the transfer of audit records offloaded onto a different system or media from the system being audited via rsyslog.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to use the gtls driver to encrypt offloaded audit records by setting the following options in \"/etc/rsyslog.conf\" or \"/etc/rsyslog.d/[customfile].conf\":\n\n$DefaultNetstreamDriver gtls","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 uses the gtls driver to encrypt audit records offloaded onto a different system or media from the system being audited with the following command:\n\n$ grep -i '$DefaultNetstreamDriver' /etc/rsyslog.conf /etc/rsyslog.d/*.conf \n/etc/rsyslog.conf:$DefaultNetstreamDriver gtls \n\nIf the value of the \"$DefaultNetstreamDriver\" option is not set to \"gtls\" or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Information stored in one location is vulnerable to accidental or incidental deletion or alteration.\n\nOffloading is a common process in information systems with limited audit storage capacity.\n\nOL 9 installation media provides \"rsyslogd\", a system utility providing support for message logging. Support for both internet and Unix domain sockets enables this utility to support both local and remote logging. Coupling this utility with \"gnutls\" (a secure communications library implementing the SSL, TLS, and DTLS protocols) creates a method to securely encrypt and offload auditing.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133, SRG-OS-000479-GPOS-00224","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001851"],"reference_identifier":"5320","uuid":"86d35b98-bcd4-4112-86c1-b7295d7b21c7","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-271857","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271857","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271857","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271857r1184229_rule","rule_id":"SV-271857","rule_version":"OL09-00-005030","rule_title":"OL 9 must be configured so that the rsyslog daemon does not accept log messages from other servers unless the server is being used for log aggregation.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to not receive remote logs using rsyslog.\n\nRemove the lines in /etc/rsyslog.conf and any files in the /etc/rsyslog.d directory that match any of the following:\nInputTCPServerRun\nUDPServerRun\nRELPServerRun\nmodule(load=\"imtcp\")\nmodule(load=\"imudp\")\nmodule(load=\"imrelp\")\ninput(type=\"imudp\" port=\"514\")\ninput(type=\"imtcp\" port=\"514\")\ninput(type=\"imrelp\" port=\"514\")\n\nThe rsyslog daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart rsyslog.service","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Note: If the system administrator can demonstrate that another tool (e.g., SPLUNK) is being used to manage log offload and aggregation in lieu of rsyslog, this is not applicable.\n\nVerify OL 9 is not configured to receive remote logs using rsyslog with the following commands:\n\n$ ss -tulnp | grep rsyslog\n\nIf no output is returned, rsyslog is not listening for remote messages and is compliant.\n\nIf output appears, check for configured ports (514 is the default for syslog).\n\nCheck for remote logging configuration in rsyslog by examining the rsyslog configuration files:\n\n$ sudo grep -E 'InputTCPServerRun|UDPServerRun|RELPServerRun|imtcp|imudp|imrelp' /etc/rsyslog.conf /etc/rsyslog.d/*\n\nIf this command returns uncommented lines enabling network listeners, the system is accepting remote logs. If this system is not documented and authorized as a log aggregation server, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Unintentionally running a rsyslog server accepting remote messages puts the system at increased risk. Malicious rsyslog messages sent to the server could exploit vulnerabilities in the server software itself, could introduce misleading information into the system's logs, or could fill the system's storage leading to a denial of service.\n\nIf the system is intended to be a log aggregation server, its use must be documented with the information system security officer (ISSO).","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"7253","uuid":"3df6eb33-f331-4f0d-9218-faff43a0b9f7","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":""},{"group_id_src":"V-271858","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271858","title":"SRG-OS-000420-GPOS-00186","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271858","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000420-GPOS-00186","rule_id_src":"SV-271858r1092286_rule","rule_id":"SV-271858","rule_version":"OL09-00-006000","rule_title":"OL 9 must protect against or limit the effects of denial-of-service (DoS) attacks by ensuring rate-limiting measures on impacted network interfaces are implemented.","fix_text":"Configure \"nftables\" to be the default \"firewallbackend\" for \"firewalld\" by adding or editing the following line in \"/etc/firewalld/firewalld.conf\":\n\nFirewallBackend=nftables\n\nEstablish rate-limiting rules based on organization-defined types of DoS attacks on impacted network interfaces.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 nftables is configured to allow rate limits on any connection to the system with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -i firewallbackend /etc/firewalld/firewalld.conf\n# FirewallBackend\nFirewallBackend=nftables\n\nIf the \"nftables\" is not set as the \"FirewallBackend\" default, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"DoS is a condition when a resource is not available for legitimate users. When this occurs, the organization either cannot accomplish its mission or must operate at degraded capacity.\n\nThis requirement addresses the configuration of OL 9 to mitigate the impact of DoS attacks that have occurred or are ongoing on system availability. For each system, known and potential DoS attacks must be identified and solutions for each type implemented. A variety of technologies exists to limit or, in some cases, eliminate the effects of DoS attacks (e.g., limiting processes or establishing memory partitions). Employing increased capacity and bandwidth, combined with service redundancy, may reduce the susceptibility to some DoS attacks.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002385"],"reference_identifier":"9663","uuid":"83c6573a-9f8c-4759-9c5e-44d9481f2112","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 3532100C1CBB85015845B5F4054FE0803A4A15CF\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must protect against or limit the effects of denial-of-service (DoS) attacks by ensuring rate-limiting measures on impacted network interfaces are implemented.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271859","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271859","title":"SRG-OS-000299-GPOS-00117","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271859","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000299-GPOS-00117","rule_id_src":"SV-271859r1092289_rule","rule_id":"SV-271859","rule_version":"OL09-00-006001","rule_title":"OL 9 wireless network adapters must be disabled.","fix_text":"Configure the system to disable all wireless network interfaces with the following command:\n\n$ sudo nmcli radio all off","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Note: For systems that do not have physical wireless network radios, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nVerify that OL 9 allows no wireless interfaces to be configured on the system with the following command:\n\n$ nmcli device status\nDEVICE           TYPE       STATE         CONNECTION\nvirbr0           bridge     connected     virbr0\nwlp7s0           wifi       connected     wifiSSID\nenp6s0           ethernet   disconnected  --\np2p-dev-wlp7s0   wifi-p2p   disconnected  --\nlo               loopback   unmanaged     --\nvirbr0-nic       tun        unmanaged     --\n\nIf a wireless interface is configured and has not been documented and approved by the information system security officer (ISSO), this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"This requirement applies to wireless peripheral technologies (e.g., wireless mice, keyboards, displays, etc.) used with OL 9 systems. Wireless peripherals (e.g., Wi-Fi/Bluetooth/IR keyboards, mice and pointing devices, and near field communications [NFC]) present a unique challenge by creating an open, unsecured port on a computer. Wireless peripherals must meet DOD requirements for wireless data transmission and be approved for use by the authorizing official (AO). Even though some wireless peripherals, such as mice and pointing devices, do not ordinarily carry information that need to be protected, modification of communications with these wireless peripherals may be used to compromise the OL 9 operating system.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000299-GPOS-00117, SRG-OS-000300-GPOS-00118, SRG-OS-000424-GPOS-00188, SRG-OS-000481-GPOS-00481","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001444","CCI-001443","CCI-002421","CCI-002418"],"reference_identifier":"6000","uuid":"4f483532-3156-41c6-97a8-e51b4a59c1c6","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 0E092EF4A374F84A3AF4401E89AB1EA35E24B8F1\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 wireless network adapters must be disabled.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271860","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271860","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271860","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271860r1092292_rule","rule_id":"SV-271860","rule_version":"OL09-00-006002","rule_title":"OL 9 must configure a DNS processing mode set be Network Manager.","fix_text":"Configure NetworkManager in OL 9 to use a DNS mode.\n\nIn \"/etc/NetworkManager/NetworkManager.conf\" add the following line in the \"[main]\" section:\n\ndns = none\n\nNetworkManager must be reloaded for the change to take effect.\n\n$ sudo systemctl reload NetworkManager","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 has a DNS mode configured in Network Manager.\n\n$ NetworkManager --print-config\n[main]\ndns=none\n\nIf the DNS key under main does not exist or is not set to \"none\" or \"default\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"To ensure that DNS resolver settings are respected, a DNS mode in Network Manager must be configured.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"1217","uuid":"cf78f25b-496a-4dc6-9cce-98caced6e4c1","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 82DE7FBB6FE07518A95ABFEC66E870CAAA862101\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'OL 9 must configure a DNS processing mode set be Network Manager.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271861","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271861","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271861","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271861r1092295_rule","rule_id":"SV-271861","rule_version":"OL09-00-006003","rule_title":"OL 9 systems using Domain Name Servers (DNS) resolution must have at least two name servers configured.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to use two or more name servers for DNS resolution based on the DNS mode of the system.\n\nIf the NetworkManager DNS mode is set to \"none\", then add the following lines to \"/etc/resolv.conf\":\n\nnameserver [name server 1]\nnameserver [name server 2]\n\nReplace [name server 1] and [name server 2] with the IPs of two different DNS resolvers.\n\nIf the NetworkManager DNS mode is set to \"default\" then add two DNS servers to a NetworkManager connection. Using the following commands:\n\n$ sudo nmcli connection modify [connection name] ipv4.dns [name server 1]\n$ sudo nmcli connection modify [connection name] ipv4.dns [name server 2]\n\nReplace [name server 1] and [name server 2] with the IPs of two different DNS resolvers. Replace [connection name] with a valid NetworkManager connection name on the system. Replace ipv4 with ipv6 if IPv6 DNS servers are used.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 configures name servers used by the system with the following command:\n\n$ grep nameserver /etc/resolv.conf\nnameserver 192.168.1.2\nnameserver 192.168.1.3\n\nIf less than two lines are returned that are not commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"To provide availability for name resolution services, multiple redundant name servers are mandated. A failure in name resolution could lead to the failure of security functions requiring name resolution, which may include time synchronization, centralized authentication, and remote system logging.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"4658","uuid":"f23a56f9-93d2-4fdf-afbb-dbd5b11348ee","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 033C1C322039D0C406D6B23308CCE0628C6EA0A5\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 systems using Domain Name Servers (DNS) resolution must have at least two name servers configured.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271862","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271862","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271862","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271862r1092298_rule","rule_id":"SV-271862","rule_version":"OL09-00-006004","rule_title":"OL 9 network interfaces must not be in promiscuous mode.","fix_text":"Configure network interfaces to turn off promiscuous mode unless approved by the ISSO and documented.\n\nSet the promiscuous mode of an interface to off with the following command:\n\n$ sudo ip link set dev <devicename> multicast off promisc off","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 configures network interfaces to not operate in promiscuous mode with the following command:\n\n$ ip link | grep -i promisc\n\nIf network interfaces are found on the system in promiscuous mode and their use has not been approved by the ISSO and documented, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Network interfaces in promiscuous mode allow for the capture of all network traffic visible to the system. If unauthorized individuals can access these applications, it may allow them to collect information such as logon IDs, passwords, and key exchanges between systems.\n\nIf the system is being used to perform a network troubleshooting function, the use of these tools must be documented with the information systems security officer (ISSO) and restricted to only authorized personnel.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"8076","uuid":"3699482a-bb14-4e27-ad46-f6e02e89a6c7","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: FECFFB467B771F28D830CD7977E2F82C35288945\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 network interfaces must not be in promiscuous mode.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271863","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271863","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271863","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271863r1092639_rule","rule_id":"SV-271863","rule_version":"OL09-00-006010","rule_title":"OL 9 must not have unauthorized IP tunnels configured.","fix_text":"Remove all unapproved tunnels from the system, or document them with the ISSO.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 does not have unauthorized IP tunnels configured.\n\nDetermine if the IPsec service is active with the following command:\n\n$ systemctl status ipsec\nipsec.service - Internet Key Exchange (IKE) Protocol Daemon for IPsec\nLoaded: loaded (/usr/lib/systemd/system/ipsec.service; disabled)\nActive: inactive (dead)\n\nIf the IPsec service is active, check for configured IPsec connections (\"conn\"), with the following command:\n\n$ grep -rni conn /etc/ipsec.conf /etc/ipsec.d/ \n\nVerify any returned results are documented with the ISSO.\n\nIf the IPsec tunnels are active and not approved, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"IP tunneling mechanisms can be used to bypass network filtering. If tunneling is required, it must be documented with the information system security officer (ISSO).","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"7428","uuid":"52ae9435-5fae-49c8-aac5-8b099e827d63","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 7CA4B7E7037F56F743CBD5035FE7B592F3727EFD\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must not have unauthorized IP tunnels configured.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271864","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271864","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271864","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271864r1092304_rule","rule_id":"SV-271864","rule_version":"OL09-00-006020","rule_title":"OL 9 must ignore Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4) Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) redirect messages.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to ignore IPv4 ICMP redirect messages.\n\nAdd or edit the following line in a single system configuration file in the \"/etc/sysctl.d/\" directory:\n\nnet.ipv4.conf.all.accept_redirects = 0\n\nLoad settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 will not accept IPv4 ICMP redirect messages.\n\nCheck the value of all \"accept_redirects\" variables with the following command:\n\n$ sysctl net.ipv4.conf.all.accept_redirects\nnet.ipv4.conf.all.accept_redirects = 0\n\nIf the returned line does not have a value of \"0\", a line is not returned, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"ICMP redirect messages are used by routers to inform hosts that a more direct route exists for a particular destination. These messages modify the host's route table and are unauthenticated. An illicit ICMP redirect message could result in a man-in-the-middle attack.\n\nThis feature of the IPv4 protocol has few legitimate uses. It should be disabled unless absolutely required.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"9617","uuid":"dee08faa-6d23-479c-97ce-94064016088b","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: E6590F0E9588BEE6676FCAF820E0862FE38167BD\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'OL 9 must ignore Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4) Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) redirect messages.' is not present or not in use on this the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271865","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271865","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271865","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271865r1092307_rule","rule_id":"SV-271865","rule_version":"OL09-00-006021","rule_title":"OL 9 must not forward Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4) source-routed packets.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to ignore IPv4 source-routed packets.\n\nAdd or edit the following line in a single system configuration file in the \"/etc/sysctl.d/\" directory:\n\nnet.ipv4.conf.all.accept_source_route = 0\n\nLoad settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 will not accept IPv4 source-routed packets.\n\nCheck the value of the all \"accept_source_route\" variables with the following command:\n\n$ sysctl net.ipv4.conf.all.accept_source_route\nnet.ipv4.conf.all.accept_source_route = 0\n\nIf the returned line does not have a value of \"0\", a line is not returned, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Source-routed packets allow the source of the packet to suggest routers forward the packet along a different path than configured on the router, which can be used to bypass network security measures. This requirement applies only to the forwarding of source-routed traffic, such as when IPv4 forwarding is enabled and the system is functioning as a router.\n\nAccepting source-routed packets in the IPv4 protocol has few legitimate uses. It must be disabled unless it is absolutely required.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"8222","uuid":"244f783f-775a-41eb-8214-28943e2358f3","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 9983C25F51F4A3B51D70D033F43426CF9F3F5FD2\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must not forward Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4) source-routed packets.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271866","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271866","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271866","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271866r1092310_rule","rule_id":"SV-271866","rule_version":"OL09-00-006022","rule_title":"OL 9 must log IPv4 packets with impossible addresses.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to log martian packets on IPv4 interfaces.\n\nAdd or edit the following line in a single system configuration file in the \"/etc/sysctl.d/\" directory:\n\nnet.ipv4.conf.all.log_martians=1\n\nLoad settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 logs IPv4 martian packets.\n\nCheck the value of the accept source route variable with the following command:\n\n$ sysctl net.ipv4.conf.all.log_martians\nnet.ipv4.conf.all.log_martians = 1\n\nIf the returned line does not have a value of \"1\", a line is not returned, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The presence of \"martian\" packets (which have impossible addresses) as well as spoofed packets, source-routed packets, and redirects could be a sign of nefarious network activity. Logging these packets enables this activity to be detected.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"3380","uuid":"40d16ba6-fd35-442d-b8ee-2b264e4e4470","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 52CFE0763686BC5954F7FC8A1037B53717F23E22\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must log IPv4 packets with impossible addresses.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271867","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271867","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271867","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271867r1092313_rule","rule_id":"SV-271867","rule_version":"OL09-00-006023","rule_title":"OL 9 must log IPv4 packets with impossible addresses by default.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to log martian packets on IPv4 interfaces by default.\n\nAdd or edit the following line in a single system configuration file in the \"/etc/sysctl.d/\" directory:\n\nnet.ipv4.conf.default.log_martians=1\n\nLoad settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 logs IPv4 martian packets by default.\n\nCheck the value of the accept source route variable with the following command:\n\n$ sysctl net.ipv4.conf.default.log_martians\nnet.ipv4.conf.default.log_martians = 1\n\nIf the returned line does not have a value of \"1\", a line is not returned, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The presence of \"martian\" packets (which have impossible addresses) as well as spoofed packets, source-routed packets, and redirects could be a sign of nefarious network activity. Logging these packets enables this activity to be detected.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2740","uuid":"d924439e-d078-435f-bd18-145ad36dbf83","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 250080D31ADCEBBCEBDE82D6BFA029B00FC0D601\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must log IPv4 packets with impossible addresses by default.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271868","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271868","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271868","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271868r1172845_rule","rule_id":"SV-271868","rule_version":"OL09-00-006024","rule_title":"OL 9 must use reverse path filtering on all IPv4 interfaces.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to use reverse path filtering on all IPv4 interfaces. \n\nAdd or edit the following line in a single system configuration file in the \"/etc/sysctl.d/\" directory:\n\nnet.ipv4.conf.all.rp_filter = 1\n\nThe system configuration files need to be reloaded for the changes to take effect. To reload the contents of the files, run the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify OL 9 uses reverse path filtering on all IPv4 interfaces with the following commands:\n\n$ sysctl net.ipv4.conf.all.rp_filter\nnet.ipv4.conf.all.rp_filter = 1\n\nIf the returned line does not have a value of \"1\", or a line is not returned, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Enabling reverse path filtering drops packets with source addresses that should not have been able to be received on the interface on which they were received. It must not be used on systems that are routers for complicated networks but is helpful for end hosts and routers serving small networks.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"5599","uuid":"742f7c4b-9802-4ff7-a76d-88838563e384","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: F147738B8E607C04600098B3547433FEB0D8821C\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must use reverse path filtering on all IPv4 interfaces.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271869","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271869","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271869","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271869r1092319_rule","rule_id":"SV-271869","rule_version":"OL09-00-006025","rule_title":"OL 9 must prevent IPv4 Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) redirect messages from being accepted.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to prevent IPv4 ICMP redirect messages from being accepted.\n\nAdd or edit the following line in a single system configuration file in the \"/etc/sysctl.d/\" directory:\n\nnet.ipv4.conf.default.accept_redirects = 0\n\nLoad settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 will not accept IPv4 ICMP redirect messages.\n\nCheck the value of the default \"accept_redirects\" variables with the following command:\n\n$ sysctl net.ipv4.conf.default.accept_redirects\nnet.ipv4.conf.default.accept_redirects = 0\n\nIf the returned line does not have a value of \"0\", a line is not returned, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"ICMP redirect messages are used by routers to inform hosts that a more direct route exists for a particular destination. These messages modify the host's route table and are unauthenticated. An illicit ICMP redirect message could result in a man-in-the-middle attack.\n\nThis feature of the IPv4 protocol has few legitimate uses. It must be disabled unless absolutely required.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"5029","uuid":"ae475970-628f-4265-b11d-c550dfc29161","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: B804D3C53165CFFC1C756F28C1A0BE5E6CD3AA6F\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'OL 9 must prevent IPv4 Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) redirect messages from being accepted.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271870","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271870","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271870","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271870r1092322_rule","rule_id":"SV-271870","rule_version":"OL09-00-006026","rule_title":"OL 9 must not forward IPv4 source-routed packets by default.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to not forward IPv4 source-routed packets by default.\n\nAdd or edit the following line in a single system configuration file in the \"/etc/sysctl.d/\" directory:\n\nnet.ipv4.conf.default.accept_source_route = 0\n\nLoad settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 does not accept IPv4 source-routed packets by default.\n\nCheck the value of the accept source route variable with the following command:\n\n$ sysctl net.ipv4.conf.default.accept_source_route\nnet.ipv4.conf.default.accept_source_route = 0\n\nIf the returned line does not have a value of \"0\", a line is not returned, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Source-routed packets allow the source of the packet to suggest routers forward the packet along a different path than configured on the router, which can be used to bypass network security measures.\n\nAccepting source-routed packets in the IPv4 protocol has few legitimate uses. It must be disabled unless it is absolutely required, such as when IPv4 forwarding is enabled and the system is legitimately functioning as a router.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"3390","uuid":"8b887dd5-ddc5-4be0-9490-60ec40594942","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 7273DC72D7D2AB37913C34B7824EE8DBAD90BD02\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must not forward IPv4 source-routed packets by default.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271871","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271871","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271871","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271871r1172843_rule","rule_id":"SV-271871","rule_version":"OL09-00-006027","rule_title":"OL 9 must use a reverse-path filter for IPv4 network traffic, when possible, by default.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to use reverse path filtering on IPv4 interfaces by default.\n\nAdd or edit the following line in a single system configuration file in the \"/etc/sysctl.d/\" directory:\n\nnet.ipv4.conf.default.rp_filter = 1\n\nLoad settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify OL 9 uses reverse path filtering on IPv4 interfaces with the following commands:\n\n$ sysctl net.ipv4.conf.default.rp_filter\nnet.ipv4.conf.default.rp_filter = 1\n\nIf the returned line does not have a value of \"1\", or a line is not returned, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Enabling reverse path filtering drops packets with source addresses that should not have been able to be received on the interface on which they were received. It must not be used on systems that are routers for complicated networks but is helpful for end hosts and routers serving small networks.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"7180","uuid":"0756ac8a-bb24-4300-b98e-d716fb57ba67","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 2676A62A20DD644398E325F2E09083ADF5FF056F\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must use a reverse-path filter for IPv4 network traffic, when possible, by default.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271872","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271872","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271872","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271872r1092328_rule","rule_id":"SV-271872","rule_version":"OL09-00-006028","rule_title":"OL 9 must not enable IPv4 packet forwarding unless the system is a router.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to not allow IPv4 packet forwarding unless the system is a router.\n\nAdd or edit the following line in a single system configuration file in the \"/etc/sysctl.d/\" directory:\n\nnet.ipv4.conf.all.forwarding = 0\n\nLoad settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is not performing IPv4 packet forwarding, unless the system is a router.\n\nCheck that IPv4 forwarding is disabled using the following command:\n\n$ sysctl net.ipv4.conf.all.forwarding\nnet.ipv4.conf.all.forwarding = 0\n\nIf the IPv4 forwarding value is not \"0\" and is not documented with the information system security officer (ISSO) as an operational requirement, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Routing protocol daemons are typically used on routers to exchange network topology information with other routers. If this capability is used when not required, system network information may be unnecessarily transmitted across the network.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"1053","uuid":"8be7deea-2883-4a24-be45-a97f7b6144d9","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 183155990E2595EBAA8F283E2C1BCF92FF4CF68E\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must not enable IPv4 packet forwarding unless the system is a router.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271873","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271873","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271873","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271873r1092331_rule","rule_id":"SV-271873","rule_version":"OL09-00-006030","rule_title":"OL 9 must not respond to Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) echoes sent to a broadcast address.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to not respond to IPv4 ICMP echoes sent to a broadcast address.\n\nAdd or edit the following line in a single system configuration file in the \"/etc/sysctl.d/\" directory:\n\nnet.ipv4.icmp_echo_ignore_broadcasts = 1\n\nLoad settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 does not respond to ICMP echoes sent to a broadcast address.\n\nCheck the value of the \"icmp_echo_ignore_broadcasts\" variable with the following command:\n\n$ sysctl net.ipv4.icmp_echo_ignore_broadcasts\nnet.ipv4.icmp_echo_ignore_broadcasts = 1\n\nIf the returned line does not have a value of \"1\", a line is not returned, or the retuned line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Responding to broadcast (ICMP) echoes facilitates network mapping and provides a vector for amplification attacks.\n\nIgnoring ICMP echo requests (pings) sent to broadcast or multicast addresses makes the system slightly more difficult to enumerate on the network.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"9824","uuid":"507cde96-95fe-417f-99ea-eac8c8048160","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 0D74A976E54A4003CB956ED0BC3F489100449904\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'OL 9 must not respond to Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) echoes sent to a broadcast address.' is not present or not in use on this the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271874","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271874","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271874","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271874r1092612_rule","rule_id":"SV-271874","rule_version":"OL09-00-006031","rule_title":"OL 9 must limit the number of bogus Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) response errors logs.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to not log bogus ICMP errors: \n\nAdd or edit the following line in a single system configuration file in the \"/etc/sysctl.d/\" directory:\n\nnet.ipv4.icmp_ignore_bogus_error_responses = 1\n\nLoad settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 limits the number of bogus ICMP response errors logs.\n\nThe runtime status of the net.ipv4.icmp_ignore_bogus_error_responses kernel parameter can be queried by running the following command:\n\n$ sysctl net.ipv4.icmp_ignore_bogus_error_responses \nnet.ipv4.icmp_ignore_bogus_error_responses = 1\n\nIf \"net.ipv4.icmp_ignore_bogus_error_responses\" is not set to \"1\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Some routers will send responses to broadcast frames that violate RFC-1122, which fills up a log file system with many useless error messages. An attacker may take advantage of this and attempt to flood the logs with bogus error logs. Ignoring bogus ICMP error responses reduces log size, although some activity would not be logged.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"8167","uuid":"6f4ee534-e5b9-4105-b768-a270ad150aae","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 040B068EA63D8BD41D12CD3FB1672F0946A613D2\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must limit the number of bogus Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) response errors logs.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271875","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271875","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271875","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271875r1092337_rule","rule_id":"SV-271875","rule_version":"OL09-00-006032","rule_title":"OL 9 must not send Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) redirects.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to not allow interfaces to perform IPv4 ICMP redirects.\n\nAdd or edit the following line in a single system configuration file in the \"/etc/sysctl.d/\" directory:\n\nnet.ipv4.conf.all.send_redirects = 0\n\nLoad settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 does not IPv4 ICMP redirect messages.\n\nCheck the value of the \"all send_redirects\" variables with the following command:\n\n$ sysctl net.ipv4.conf.all.send_redirects\nnet.ipv4.conf.all.send_redirects = 0\n\nIf \"net.ipv4.conf.all.send_redirects\" is not set to \"0\" and is not documented with the information system security officer (ISSO) as an operational requirement or is missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"ICMP redirect messages are used by routers to inform hosts that a more direct route exists for a particular destination. These messages contain information from the system's route table possibly revealing portions of the network topology.\n\nThe ability to send ICMP redirects is only appropriate for systems acting as routers.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"8529","uuid":"bf8e50f7-67ca-4148-95de-81df7b8613e9","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 213ACE489575731907BD219378DEE58E609ED487\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must not send Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) redirects.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271876","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271876","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271876","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271876r1092641_rule","rule_id":"SV-271876","rule_version":"OL09-00-006033","rule_title":"OL 9 must not allow interfaces to perform Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) redirects by default.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to not allow interfaces to perform IPv4 ICMP redirects by default.\n\nAdd or edit the following line in a single system configuration file in the \"/etc/sysctl.d/\" directory:\n\nnet.ipv4.conf.default.send_redirects = 0\n\nLoad settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 does not allow interfaces to perform Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4) ICMP redirects by default.\n\nCheck the value of the \"default send_redirects\" variables with the following command:\n\n$ sysctl net.ipv4.conf.default.send_redirects\nnet.ipv4.conf.default.send_redirects=0\n\nIf \"net.ipv4.conf.default.send_redirects\" is not set to \"0\" and is not documented with the information system security officer (ISSO) as an operational requirement or is missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"ICMP redirect messages are used by routers to inform hosts that a more direct route exists for a particular destination. These messages contain information from the system's route table possibly revealing portions of the network topology.\n\nThe ability to send ICMP redirects is only appropriate for systems acting as routers.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2014","uuid":"b6667a3c-db57-447c-98e7-2549713f8fca","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 779F774598A17DCA056F1EE781134C7385C2BC9A\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'OL 9 must not allow interfaces to perform Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) redirects by default.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271877","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271877","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271877","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271877r1092343_rule","rule_id":"SV-271877","rule_version":"OL09-00-006040","rule_title":"OL 9 must not accept router advertisements on all IPv6 interfaces.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to not accept router advertisements on all IPv6 interfaces unless the system is a router.\n\nAdd or edit the following line in a single system configuration file in the \"/etc/sysctl.d/\" directory:\n\nnet.ipv6.conf.all.accept_ra = 0\n\nLoad settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Note: If IPv6 is disabled on the system, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nVerify that OL 9 does not accept router advertisements on all IPv6 interfaces, unless the system is a router.\n\nDetermine if router advertisements are not accepted by using the following command:\n\n$ sysctl net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_ra\nnet.ipv6.conf.all.accept_ra = 0\n\nIf the \"accept_ra\" value is not \"0\" and is not documented with the information system security officer (ISSO) as an operational requirement, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"An illicit router advertisement message could result in a man-in-the-middle attack.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"8590","uuid":"6d1d8aba-8975-43e1-b074-05d97c2b1ba4","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: AB0C282388D46DE5AFC36865FB6F5E47E6F06227\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must not accept router advertisements on all IPv6 interfaces.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271878","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271878","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271878","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271878r1092346_rule","rule_id":"SV-271878","rule_version":"OL09-00-006041","rule_title":"OL 9 must ignore IPv6 Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) redirect messages.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to ignore IPv6 ICMP redirect messages.\n\nAdd or edit the following line in a single system configuration file in the \"/etc/sysctl.d/\" directory:\n\nnet.ipv6.conf.all.accept_redirects = 0\n\nLoad settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Note: If IPv6 is disabled on the system, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nVerify that OL 9 ignores IPv6 ICMP redirect messages.\n\nCheck the value of the \"accept_redirects\" variables with the following command:\n\n$ sysctl net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_redirects\nnet.ipv6.conf.all.accept_redirects = 0\n\nIf the returned line does not have a value of \"0\", a line is not returned, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"An illicit ICMP redirect message could result in a man-in-the-middle attack.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"9148","uuid":"7dd4b274-9129-43e8-9e34-bdcaef071d6c","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: AEA8962C65A7141CF16374306F41E78F10BA85CF\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'OL 9 must ignore IPv6 Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) redirect messages.' is not present or not in use on this the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271879","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271879","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271879","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271879r1092349_rule","rule_id":"SV-271879","rule_version":"OL09-00-006042","rule_title":"OL 9 must not forward IPv6 source-routed packets.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to not forward IPv6 source-routed packets.\n\nAdd or edit the following line in a single system configuration file in the \"/etc/sysctl.d/\" directory:\n\nnet.ipv6.conf.all.accept_source_route = 0\n\nLoad settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Note: If IPv6 is disabled on the system, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nVerify that OL 9 does not accept IPv6 source-routed packets.\n\nCheck the value of the accept source route variable with the following command:\n\n$ sysctl net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_source_route\nnet.ipv6.conf.all.accept_source_route = 0\n\nIf the returned line does not have a value of \"0\", a line is not returned, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Source-routed packets allow the source of the packet to suggest that routers forward the packet along a different path than configured on the router, which can be used to bypass network security measures. This requirement applies only to the forwarding of source-routed traffic, such as when forwarding is enabled and the system is functioning as a router.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"4000","uuid":"edf149b8-40de-4dc2-b6d1-b2b526886b3e","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 6EAF775836E9174291AF5CFC3C9F5A482F698BC1\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must not forward IPv6 source-routed packets.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271880","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271880","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271880","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271880r1092352_rule","rule_id":"SV-271880","rule_version":"OL09-00-006043","rule_title":"OL 9 must not enable IPv6 packet forwarding unless the system is a router.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to not allow IPv6 packet forwarding unless the system is a router.\n\nAdd or edit the following line in a single system configuration file in the \"/etc/sysctl.d/\" directory:\n\nnet.ipv6.conf.all.forwarding = 0\n\nLoad settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Note: If IPv6 is disabled on the system, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nVerify that OL 9 is not performing IPv6 packet forwarding, unless the system is a router.\n\nCheck that IPv6 forwarding is disabled using the following commands:\n\n$ sysctl net.ipv6.conf.all.forwarding\nnet.ipv6.conf.all.forwarding = 0\n\nIf the IPv6 forwarding value is not \"0\" and is not documented with the information system security officer (ISSO) as an operational requirement, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"IP forwarding permits the kernel to forward packets from one network interface to another. The ability to forward packets between two networks is only appropriate for systems acting as routers.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"4234","uuid":"467f0f56-fe04-422e-8673-7f27f16a660f","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: A23F3AC9C695CFFFABFC985497EFFFB2BD6B39C0\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'OL 9 must not enable IPv6 packet forwarding unless the system is a router.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271881","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271881","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271881","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271881r1092355_rule","rule_id":"SV-271881","rule_version":"OL09-00-006044","rule_title":"OL 9 must not accept router advertisements on all IPv6 interfaces by default.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to not accept router advertisements on all IPv6 interfaces by default unless the system is a router.\n\nAdd or edit the following line in a single system configuration file in the \"/etc/sysctl.d/\" directory:\n\nnet.ipv6.conf.default.accept_ra = 0\n\nLoad settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Note: If IPv6 is disabled on the system, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nVerify that OL 9 does not accept router advertisements on all IPv6 interfaces by default unless the system is a router.\n\nDetermine if router advertisements are not accepted by default by using the following command:\n\n$ sysctl net.ipv6.conf.default.accept_ra\nnet.ipv6.conf.default.accept_ra = 0\n\nIf the \"accept_ra\" value is not \"0\" and is not documented with the information system security officer (ISSO) as an operational requirement, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"An illicit router advertisement message could result in a man-in-the-middle attack.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"7765","uuid":"3534811c-b154-45fb-91b7-45a29bddec72","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 73C7B52FFB10181FCC7B20A0DA37E26B02F39FD2\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must not accept router advertisements on all IPv6 interfaces by default.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271882","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271882","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271882","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271882r1092358_rule","rule_id":"SV-271882","rule_version":"OL09-00-006045","rule_title":"OL 9 must prevent IPv6 Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) redirect messages from being accepted.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to prevent IPv6 ICMP redirect messages from being accepted.\n\nAdd or edit the following line in a single system configuration file in the \"/etc/sysctl.d/\" directory:\n\nnet.ipv6.conf.default.accept_redirects = 0\n\nLoad settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Note: If IPv6 is disabled on the system, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nVerify that OL 9 will not accept IPv6 ICMP redirect messages.\n\nCheck the value of the default \"accept_redirects\" variables with the following command:\n\n$ sysctl net.ipv6.conf.default.accept_redirects\nnet.ipv6.conf.default.accept_redirects = 0\n\nIf the returned line does not have a value of \"0\", a line is not returned, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"ICMP redirect messages are used by routers to inform hosts that a more direct route exists for a particular destination. These messages modify the host's route table and are unauthenticated. An illicit ICMP redirect message could result in a man-in-the-middle attack.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"3522","uuid":"9a65e83b-5848-43b2-87e7-7006c51ec537","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 813AE61C2B7815AF808697F4A05338E2FA79B492\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must prevent IPv6 Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) redirect messages from being accepted.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271883","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271883","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271883","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","rule_id_src":"SV-271883r1092361_rule","rule_id":"SV-271883","rule_version":"OL09-00-006046","rule_title":"OL 9 must not forward IPv6 source-routed packets by default.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to not forward IPv6 source-routed packets by default.\n\nAdd or edit the following line in a single system configuration file in the \"/etc/sysctl.d/\" directory:\n\nnet.ipv6.conf.default.accept_source_route = 0\n\nLoad settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Note: If IPv6 is disabled on the system, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nVerify that OL 9 does not accept IPv6 source-routed packets by default.\n\nCheck the value of the accept source route variable with the following command:\n\n$ sysctl net.ipv6.conf.default.accept_source_route\nnet.ipv6.conf.default.accept_source_route = 0\n\nIf the returned line does not have a value of \"0\", a line is not returned, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Source-routed packets allow the source of the packet to suggest that routers forward the packet along a different path than configured on the router, which can be used to bypass network security measures. This requirement applies only to the forwarding of source-routed traffic, such as when forwarding is enabled and the system is functioning as a router.\n\nAccepting source-routed packets in the IPv6 protocol has few legitimate uses. It must be disabled unless it is absolutely required.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"7920","uuid":"f214941c-fc79-43bb-8bfb-4eaf3280b4bd","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 90F63CAA7ECF386830B9A59F57BA4AD105DFE13F\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'OL 9 must not forward IPv6 source-routed packets by default.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271884","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271884","title":"SRG-OS-000420-GPOS-00186","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271884","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000420-GPOS-00186","rule_id_src":"SV-271884r1184231_rule","rule_id":"SV-271884","rule_version":"OL09-00-006050","rule_title":"OL 9 must be configured to use TCP syncookies.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to use TCP syncookies.\n\nAdd or edit the following line in a system configuration file in the \"/etc/sysctl.d/\" directory:\n\n net.ipv4.tcp_syncookies = 1\n\nLoad settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify OL 9 is configured to use IPv4 TCP syncookies.\n\nDetermine if syncookies are used with the following command:\n\n$ sysctl net.ipv4.tcp_syncookies\nnet.ipv4.tcp_syncookies = 1\n\nVerify the configuration files are present to enable this kernel parameter.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Denial of service (DoS) is a condition when a resource is not available for legitimate users. When this occurs, the organization either cannot accomplish its mission or must operate at degraded capacity. \n\nManaging excess capacity ensures that sufficient capacity is available to counter flooding attacks. Employing increased capacity and service redundancy may reduce the susceptibility to some DoS attacks. Managing excess capacity may include, for example, establishing selected usage priorities, quotas, or partitioning.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000420-GPOS-00186, SRG-OS-000142-GPOS-00071","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002385","CCI-001095"],"reference_identifier":"3732","uuid":"3b1b1e40-ee20-4ddc-8b71-1da51e75936b","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 287CEF781DC000A8B9CA0EA85472671E00D468B2\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must be configured to use TCP syncookies.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271885","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271885","title":"SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271885","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206","rule_id_src":"SV-271885r1092367_rule","rule_id":"SV-271885","rule_version":"OL09-00-008000","rule_title":"OL 9 audit system must protect logon UIDs from unauthorized change.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 auditing to prevent modification of login UIDs once they are set by adding the following line to /etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules:\n\n--loginuid-immutable\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.\n\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 audit system configuration prevents unauthorized changes to logon UIDs with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -i immutable /etc/audit/audit.rules\n--loginuid-immutable\n\nIf the \"--loginuid-immutable\" option is not returned in the \"/etc/audit/audit.rules\", or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If modification of login user identifiers (UIDs) is not prevented, they can be changed by nonprivileged users and make auditing complicated or impossible.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000475-GPOS-00220, SRG-OS-000057-GPOS-00027, SRG-OS-000058-GPOS-00028, SRG-OS-000059-GPOS-00029","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000172","CCI-000162","CCI-000163","CCI-000164"],"reference_identifier":"8237","uuid":"3bc71efe-f4aa-42b0-b114-69215bc20483","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: F475BAB89319C4C5B12ED926D3CB2AFD153BD0C1\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'OL 9 audit system must protect logon UIDs from unauthorized change.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271886","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271886","title":"SRG-OS-000057-GPOS-00027","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271886","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000057-GPOS-00027","rule_id_src":"SV-271886r1092370_rule","rule_id":"SV-271886","rule_version":"OL09-00-008005","rule_title":"OL 9 audit system must protect auditing rules from unauthorized change.","fix_text":"Configure the audit system to set the audit rules to be immutable by adding the following line to end of \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\"\n\n-e 2\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.\n\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 audit system configuration prevents unauthorized changes with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep \"^\\s*[^#]\" /etc/audit/audit.rules | tail -1\n-e 2\n\nIf the audit system is not set to be immutable by adding the \"-e 2\" option to the end of \"/etc/audit/audit.rules\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Unauthorized disclosure of audit records can reveal system and configuration data to attackers, thus compromising its confidentiality.\n\nAudit information includes all information (e.g., audit records, audit settings, audit reports) needed to successfully audit OL 9 system activity.\n\nIn immutable mode, unauthorized users cannot execute changes to the audit system to potentially hide malicious activity and then put the audit rules back. A system reboot would be noticeable, and a system administrator could then investigate the unauthorized changes.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000057-GPOS-00027, SRG-OS-000058-GPOS-00028, SRG-OS-000059-GPOS-00029","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000162","CCI-000163","CCI-000164"],"reference_identifier":"7557","uuid":"7e2faf9f-8757-48ff-a1d0-e02b568831b7","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 502B50F84542C50183524CBE21C7277E0AC14CC6\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 audit system must protect auditing rules from unauthorized change.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-271901","group_tree":[{"id":"V-271901","title":"SRG-OS-000403-GPOS-00182","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-271901","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000403-GPOS-00182","rule_id_src":"SV-271901r1092415_rule","rule_id":"SV-271901","rule_version":"OL09-00-900140","rule_title":"OL 9 must only allow the use of DOD PKI-established certificate authorities for authentication in the establishment of protected sessions to OL 9.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to only allow the use of DOD PKI-established certificate authorities.\n\nFor each untrusted CA, export the certificate to a file and add it to the blocklist:\n\n$ trust dump --filter \"pkcs11:id=%7C%42%96%AE%DE%4B%48%3B%FA%92%F8%9E%8C%CF%6D%8B%A9%72%37%95;type=cert\" > /etc/pki/ca-trust/source/blocklist/ISRGRootX2\n\n$ update-ca-trust \n\nVerify that the certificate is in the blocklist:\n\n$ trust list --filter=blocklist\np11-kit: overriding trust for anchor in blocklist: ISRGRootX2\npkcs11:id=%7C%42%96%AE%DE%4B%48%3B%FA%92%F8%9E%8C%CF%6D%8B%A9%72%37%95;type=cert\n    type: certificate\n    label: ISRG Root X2\n    trust: distrusted\n    category: authority\n\npkcs11:id=%88%68%BF%E0%8E%35%C4%3B%38%6B%62%F7%28%3B%84%81%C8%0C%D7%4D;type=cert\n    type: certificate\n    label: Explicitly Distrust DigiNotar Root CA\n    trust: distrusted\n    category: authority","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify OL 9 only allows the use of DOD PKI-established certificate authorities using the following command:\n\n$ trust list\n\npkcs11:id=%7C%42%96%AE%DE%4B%48%3B%FA%92%F8%9E%8C%CF%6D%8B%A9%72%37%95;type=cert\n    type: certificate\n    label: ISRG Root X2\n    trust: anchor\n    category: authority\n\nIf any nonapproved CAs are returned, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Untrusted certificate authorities (CA) can issue certificates, but they may be issued by organizations or individuals that seek to compromise DOD systems or by organizations with insufficient security controls. If the CA used for verifying the certificate is not a DOD-approved CA, trust of this CA has not been established.\n\nThe DOD will only accept PKI-certificates obtained from a DOD-approved internal or external certificate authority. Reliance on CAs for the establishment of secure sessions includes, for example, the use of SSL/TLS certificates.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002470"],"reference_identifier":"3032","uuid":"1314ae5e-0e60-48be-8277-f57c27b50744","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 98239DC4566E7D9460173D21AD53D78916D3935E\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'OL 9 must only allow the use of DOD PKI-established certificate authorities for authentication in the establishment of protected sessions to OL 9.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-278952","group_tree":[{"id":"V-278952","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-278952","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-278952r1135407_rule","rule_id":"SV-278952","rule_version":"OL09-00-002584","rule_title":"OL 9 must audit any script or executable called by cron as root or by any privileged user.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to audit the execution of any system call made by cron as root or as any privileged user.\n\nAdd or update the following file system rules to \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\nauditctl -w /etc/cron.d/ -p wa -k cronjobs\nauditctl -w /var/spool/cron/ -p wa -k cronjobs\n\nTo load the rules to the kernel immediately, use the following command:\n\n$ sudo augenrules --load","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 is configured to audit the execution of any system call made by cron as root or as any privileged user.\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep /etc/cron.d\n-w /etc/cron.d -p wa -k cronjobs\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep /var/spool/cron\n-w /var/spool/cron -p wa -k cronjobs\n\nIf either of these commands do not return the expected output, or the lines are commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Any script or executable called by cron as root or by any privileged user must be owned by that user, must have the permissions 0755 or more restrictive, and should have no extended rights that allow any nonprivileged user to modify the script or executable.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000130","CCI-000135","CCI-000169","CCI-000172","CCI-002884"],"reference_identifier":"7390","uuid":"0b1986bc-7735-48b0-a162-658a1125c0c1","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 08B6D4A6EA34C8576324E87BAA76BF7DC2E3D0A4\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'OL 9 must audit any script or executable called by cron as root or by any privileged user.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-279935","group_tree":[{"id":"V-279935","title":"SRG-OS-000163-GPOS-00072","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-279935","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000163-GPOS-00072","rule_id_src":"SV-279935r1156358_rule","rule_id":"SV-279935","rule_version":"OL09-00-002376","rule_title":"OL 9 must terminate idle user sessions.","fix_text":"Configure OL 9 to log out idle sessions by editing the /etc/systemd/logind.conf file with the following line:\n\nStopIdleSessionSec=600\n\nThe \"logind\" service must be restarted for the changes to take effect. To restart the \"logind\" service, run the following command:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart systemd-logind","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that OL 9 logs out sessions that are idle for 10 minutes with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -i ^StopIdleSessionSec /etc/systemd/logind.conf\n\nStopIdleSessionSec=600\n\nIf \"StopIdleSessionSec\" is not configured to \"600\" seconds, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Oracle_Linux_9_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Terminating an idle session within a short time period reduces the window of opportunity for unauthorized personnel to take control of a management session enabled on the console or console port that has been left unattended.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001134"],"reference_identifier":"5404","uuid":"4fb1bfb3-4a63-4a14-8baf-c78c161df47b","stig_uuid":"9f4b762d-8654-4328-882b-f95f4ce5315e","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-OracleLinux9_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 26EFB66DA4FE06D9EC56FC1E770FA5855E64058E\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'OL 9 must terminate idle user sessions.' matches the expected value on the Oracle Linux 9 host."}]}],"target_data":{"target_type":"Computing","host_name":"OEL9-SVC02","ip_address":"10.20.8.12","mac_address":"00:1C:42:01:00:1B","fqdn":"oel9-svc02.utsec.mil","comments":"","role":"Member Server","is_web_database":false,"technology_area":"None","web_db_site":"","web_db_instance":"","classification":""},"title":"Evaluate-STIG_COMBINED"}